e.com/books?id=ZtWdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT39 | access-date=2020-04-20 | page=39}}</ref> He was obsessed with [[boombox]]es as a child and had an older sister who was into early disco music in the seventies, bringing records home to listen to.<ref name=\"NPR.org 2020\">{{cite web | title=On Their Debut Album, Stretch And Bobbito Are Taking 'No Requests' | website=NPR.org | date=2020-01-17 | url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/17/797299976/on-their-debut-album-stretch-and-bobbito-are-taking-no-requests | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He started DJing in downtown New York City, making his own concert flyers out of cardboard, scissors, and glue.<ref name=\"Owerko\" /><ref name=\"powerHouse\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://stretchandbobbito.com/ Stretch and Bobbito film website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bartos, Adrian}}\n[[Category:American hip hop DJs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Jessamyn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DJ_Stretch_Armstrong"}
{"title_page": "Sumatran tiger", "text_new": "{{Subspeciesbox\n| name = Sumatran tiger\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n| image = Sumatran Tiger Berlin Tierpark.jpg\n| image_caption = Sumatran tiger in the [[Tierpark Berlin]]\n| genus = Panthera\n| species = tigris\n| species_link = Tiger\n| range_map = Panthera tigris sumatrae distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = Distribution map\n| subspecies = sondaica\n| authority =([[Coenraad Jacob Temminck|Temminck]], 1844)\n|synonyms = formerly ''P. t. sumatrae'' [[Reginald Innes Pocock|Pocock]], 1929\n}}\n\nThe '''Sumatran tiger''' is a ''[[Panthera tigris sondaica]]'' population in the [[Indonesia]]n island of [[Sumatra]].<ref name=catsg2017>{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O\u2019Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |pages=66\u201368 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Luo_al2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Liu |first1=Y.-C. |first2=X. |last2=Sun |first3=C. |last3=Driscoll |first4=D. G. |last4=Miquelle |first5=X. |last5=Xu |first6=P. |last6=Martelli |first7=O. |last7=Uphyrkina |first8=J. L. D. |last8=Smith |first9=S. J. |last9=O\u2019Brien |first10=S.-J. |last10=Luo |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genome-wide evolutionary analysis of natural history and adaptation in the world's tigers |journal=Current Biology |volume=28 |issue=23 |year=2018 |pages=3840\u20133849 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2018.09.019 |pmid=30482605|doi-access=free }}</ref> This population was listed as [[Critically Endangered]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] in 2008, as it was estimated at 441 to 679 individuals, with no subpopulation larger than 50 individuals and a declining trend.<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |last1=Linkie |first1=M. |last2=Wibisono |first2=H. T. |last3=Martyr |first3=D. J. |last4=Sunarto |first4=S. |last-author-amp=yes |date=2008 |title=''Panthera tigris ssp. sumatrae'' |page=e.T15966A5334836}}</ref>\n\nThe Sumatran tiger is the only surviving tiger population in the [[Sunda Islands]], where the [[Bali tiger|Bali]] and [[Javan tiger]]s are extinct.<ref name=mazak06>{{cite journal |author1=Maz\u00e1k, J. H. |author2=Groves, C. P. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |title=A taxonomic revision of the tigers (''Panthera tigris'') |journal=Mammalian Biology |volume=71 |issue=5 |pages=268\u2013287 |doi=10.1016/j.mambio.2006.02.007 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313144127/http://arts.anu.edu.au/grovco/tiger%20SEAsia%20Mazak.pdf}}</ref> [[DNA sequencing|Sequences]] from complete [[mitochondrial gene]]s of 34 tigers support the hypothesis that Sumatran tigers are diagnostically distinct from mainland subspecies.<ref name=Cracraft1998>{{cite journal |author=Cracraft, J. |author2=Feinstein, J. |author3=Vaughn, J. |author4=Helm-Bychowski, K. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1998 |title=Sorting out tigers (''Panthera tigris''): Mitochondrial sequences, nuclear inserts, systematics, and conservation genetics |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013150 |url=http://research.amnh.org/vz/ornithology/pdfs/1998c.%20tiger%20conservation.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.1998.tb00021.x}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the Cat Classification Task Force of the Cat Specialist Group revised felid taxonomy and recognizes the living and extinct tiger populations in Indonesia as ''[[Sunda Island tiger|P. t. sondaica]]''.<ref name=catsg2017/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis tigris sondaicus'' was the [[scientific name]] proposed by [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]] in 1844 for a tiger specimen from [[Java]].<ref name=Temminck>{{cite book |author=Temminck, C. J. |year=1844 |chapter=Aper\u00e7u g\u00e9n\u00e9ral et sp\u00e9cifique sur les mammif\u00e8res qui habitent le Japon et les iles qui en d\u00e9pendent |title=Fauna Japonica sive Descriptio animalium, quae in itinere per Japoniam, jussu et auspiciis superiorum, qui summum in India Batava imperium tenent, suscepto, annis 1825 - 1830. Mammalia |editor1=von Siebold, F. |editor2=Temminck, C. J. |editor3=Schlegel, H. |editor4=de Haan, W. |editor5=Nakazawa, K. |editor6=Tanaka, S. |editor7=Kuroda, N. |editor8=Okada, Y. |location=Lugduni Batavorum |publisher=Arnz et Socius |pages=1\u201359 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/faunajaponicasi00sieb#page/42/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nThe genus ''[[Panthera]]'' was proposed by [[Reginald Innes Pocock]] in 1929 who described a skin and a skull of a tiger specimen from Sumatra using the name ''Panthera tigris sumatrae''.<ref name=Pocock1929>{{cite journal |author=Pocock, R. I. |year=1929 |title=Tigers |journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society |volume=33 |issue= |pages=505\u2013541 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofbomb33341929bomb/page/n185}}</ref>\nSkull and pelage pattern of tiger specimens from Java and Sumatra do not differ significantly.<ref name=Mazak2006/><ref>{{cite book |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Yamaguchi, N. |year=2010 |chapter=What is a tiger? Biogeography, morphology, and taxonomy |pages=53\u201384 |title=Tigers of the World |editor1=Tilson, R. |editor2=Nyhus, P. J. |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |edition=Second  |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266794969 |doi=10.1016/B978-0-8155-1570-8.00004-9 |isbn=9780080947518}}</ref>\n''P. t. sondaica'' is therefore considered the [[Valid name (zoology)|valid name]] for the living and extinct tiger populations in Indonesia.<ref name=catsg2017/>\n\n== Evolution ==\nAnalysis of [[DNA]] is consistent with the hypothesis that Sumatran tigers became isolated from other tiger populations after a rise in sea level that occurred at the [[Pleistocene]] to [[Holocene]] border about 12,000\u20136,000 years ago. In agreement with this evolutionary history, the Sumatran tiger is genetically isolated from all living mainland tigers, which form a distinct group closely related to each other.<ref name=Cracraft1998/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n[[File:Panthera tigris sumatrae (Sumatran Tiger) close-up.jpg|thumb|Close-up of a tiger at [[San Antonio Zoo and Aquarium]], [[Texas]]]]\nThe Sumatran tiger was described on the basis of two zoological specimens that differed in [[skull]] size and striping pattern from [[Bengal tiger|Bengal]] and [[Javan tiger]] specimen. It is darker in fur colour and has broader stripes than the Javan tiger.<ref name=Pocock1929/> Stripes tend to dissolve into spots near their ends, and on the back, flanks and hind legs are lines of small, dark spots between the regular stripes.<ref name=Mazak1981>{{cite journal|author=Maz\u00e1k, V. |year=1981 |title=''Panthera tigris'' |journal=Mammalian Species |volume=152 |pages=1\u20138 |doi=10.2307/3504004 |issue=152 |jstor=3504004 |url=http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-152-01-0001.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309125526/http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-152-01-0001.pdf|archive-date=2012-03-09|df=}}</ref><ref name=Mazak2006>{{cite journal |author=Maz\u00e1k, J. H. |author2=Groves, C. P. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |title=A taxonomic revision of the tigers (''Panthera tigris'') of Southeast Asia |journal=Mammalian Biology-Zeitschrift f\u00fcr S\u00e4ugetierkunde |volume=71 |issue=5|pages=268\u2013287 |doi=10.1016/j.mambio.2006.02.007}}</ref> The frequency of stripes is higher than in other subspecies.<ref>{{cite book |author=Kitchener, A. |year=1999 |chapter=Tiger distribution, phenotypic variation and conservation issues |chapterurl=http://www.nfwf.org/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Home&CONTENTID=3060&TEMPLATE=/CM/ContentDisplay.cfm |pages=19\u201339 |title=Riding the Tiger. Tiger Conservation in human-dominated landscapes |editor1-last=Seidensticker |editor1-first=J. |editor2-last=Christie |editor2-first=S., Jackson, P. |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-521-64057-2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423162028/http://www.nfwf.org/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Home |archivedate=2012-04-23 }}</ref>\nMales have a prominent ruff, which is especially marked in the Sumatran tiger.<ref name=Nowell1996>Nowell, K., Jackson, P. (1996). [http://www.catsg.org/catsgportal/cat-website/catfolk/tiger-01.htm Tiger ''Panthera tigris'' (Linnaeus 1758)] in: ''Wild Cats: status survey and conservation action plan.'' IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group, Gland, Switzerland</ref>\n\nThe Sumatran tiger is one of the smallest tigers. Males measure between the pegs {{convert|2.2|to|2.55|m|in|abbr=on}} in head-to-body length, with a greatest length of skull of {{convert|295|to|335|mm|abbr=on}}, and weigh {{convert|100|to|140|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Females weigh {{convert|75|to|100|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and measure {{convert|2.15|to|2.30|m|in|abbr=on}} in length between the pegs with a greatest length of skull of {{convert|263|to|294|mm|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Mazak1981 />\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe Sumatran tiger persists in small and fragmented populations across Sumatra, from [[sea level]] in the coastal lowland forest of [[Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park]] on the southeastern tip of [[Lampung Province]] to {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} in mountain forests of [[Gunung Leuser National Park]] in [[Aceh Province]]. It is present in 27 habitat patches larger than {{convert|250|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, which cover {{convert|140226|km2|abbr=on}}. About a third of these patches are inside protected areas.<ref name=OBrien2003>{{cite journal|author=O\u2019Brien, T. G.|author2=Kinnard, M. F.|author3=Wibisono, H. T.|last-author-amp=yes |year=2003|title=Crouching tigers, hidden prey: Sumatran tiger and prey populations in a tropical forest landscape |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=131\u2013139 |doi=10.1017/S1367943003003172|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f89556b08c9b31e3a27dcd7464c8b9dfb0d6fca7}}</ref><ref name=Wibisono2010>{{cite journal|author1=Wibisono, H. T. |author2=Pusarini, W. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Sumatran tiger (''Panthera tigris sumatrae''): A review of conservation status |doi=10.1111/j.1749-4877.2010.00219.x |year=2010|journal=Integrative Zoology|volume=5|issue=4|pages=313\u2013323 |pmid=21392349 |url=https://www.academia.edu/4002510}}</ref>\n\nSumatran tigers prefer lowland and hill forests, where up to three tigers live in an area of {{convert|100|km2|abbr=on}}. They use non-forest habitats and human-dominated landscapes at the fringes of protected areas to a lesser degree.<ref name=Luskin_al2017>{{cite journal |last1=Luskin |first1=M. S. |last2=Albert |first2=W. R. |last3=Tobler |first3=M. W. |year=2017 |title=Sumatran tiger survival threatened by deforestation despite increasing densities in parks |journal=Nature Communications |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=1783 |doi=10.1038/s41467-017-01656-4 |pmid=29208916 |pmc=5717059 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, the Sumatran tiger population was estimated at 1,000 individuals, based on responses to a questionnaire survey.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Borner, M. |year=1978 |title=Status and conservation of the Sumatran tiger |journal=Carnivore |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages= 97\u2013102}}</ref> In 1985, a total of 26 protected areas across Sumatra containing about 800 tigers were identified.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Santiapillai, C. |author2=Ramono, W. S. |year=1987 |chapter=Tiger numbers and habitat evaluation in Indonesia |chapterurl= |pages=85\u201391 |title=Tigers of the World: The Biology, Biopolitics, Management, and Conservation of an Endangered Species |editor1=Tilson, R. L. |editor2=Seal, U. S. |publisher=Noyes Publications |location=New Jersey |isbn=0815511337}}</ref> In 1992, an estimated 400\u2013500 tigers lived in five [[List of national parks of Indonesia#Sumatra|Sumatran national parks]] and two [[Protected areas of Indonesia|protected areas]]. At that time, the largest population comprising 110\u2013180 individuals was reported to live in Gunung Leuser National Park.<ref>{{cite book |editor1=Tilson, R. L. |editor2=Soemarna, K. |editor3=Ramono, W. S. |editor4=Lusli, S. |editor5=Traylor-Holzer, K. |editor6=Seal, U. S. |year=1994 |title=Sumatran Tiger Populations and Habitat Viability Analysis |publisher=Indonesian Directorate General of Forest Protection and Nature Conservation and IUCN/SSC Conservation Breeding Specialist Group |location=Apple Valley |author=Griffiths, M. |chapter=Population density of Sumatran tigers in Gunung Leuser National Park |pages=93\u2013102}}</ref>\nAs of 2011, the tiger population in [[Kerinci Seblat National Park]] in central Sumatra comprised 165\u2013190 individuals, which is more than anywhere else on the island. The park has the highest tiger occupancy rate of Sumatra's protected areas, with 83% of the park showing signs of tigers.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Wibisono, H. T. |author2=Linkie, M. |author3=Guillera-Arroita, G. |author4=Smith, J. A. |author5=Sunarto |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0025931 |title=Population Status of a Cryptic Top Predator: An Island-Wide Assessment of Tigers in Sumatran Rainforests |year=2011 |journal= [[PLoS ONE]] |volume=6 |issue=11 |pages=e25931 |pmid=22087218 |pmc=3206793 |bibcode=2011PLoSO...625931W}}</ref>\n\nSumatra's total tiger population was estimated at 618\u2009\u00b1\u2009290 individuals in 2017.<ref name=Luskin_al2017/>\n\n== Ecology and behaviour ==\n[[File:Wild Sumatran tiger.jpg|thumb|A wild Sumatran tiger photographed by a camera trap]]\n[[File:Beautiful Sumatran Tiger Cub (9711349588).jpg|thumb|Sumatran tiger cub at the [[Chester Zoo]]]]\nSumatran tigers strongly prefer uncultivated forest and make little use of [[plantations]] of [[acacia]] and [[oil palm]] even if these are available. Within natural forest areas, they tend to use areas with higher elevation, lower annual rainfall, farther from forest edge, and closer to forest centres. They prefer forest with dense understory cover and steep slope, and they strongly avoid forest areas with high human influence in the forms of encroachment and settlement. In acacia plantations, they tend to use areas closer to water, and prefer areas with older plants, more leaf litter, and thicker subcanopy cover. Tiger records in oil palm plantations and in [[rubber plantation]]s are scarce. The availability of adequate vegetation cover at the ground level serves as an environmental condition fundamentally needed by tigers regardless of the location. Without adequate understory cover, tigers are even more vulnerable to persecution by humans. Human disturbance-related variables negatively affect tiger occupancy and habitat use. Variables with strong impacts include settlement and encroachment within forest areas, [[logging]], and the intensity of maintenance in acacia plantations.<ref name=Sunarto2012>{{cite journal|author=Sunarto |author2=Kelly, M. J.|author3=Parakkasi, K. |author4=Klenzendorf, S.|author5=Septayuda, E.|author6=Kurniawan, H. |year=2012 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0030859 |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=7|issue=1|page= e30859 |title=Tigers Need Cover: Multi-Scale Occupancy Study of the Big Cat in Sumatran Forest and Plantation Landscapes |editor=Gratwicke, B. |pmid=22292063|pmc=3264627 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...730859S}}</ref>\n[[Camera trap]]ping surveys conducted in southern [[Riau]] revealed an extremely low abundance of potential prey and a low tiger density in [[peat swamp forest]] areas. Repeated sampling in the newly established [[Tesso Nilo National Park]] documented a trend of increasing tiger density from 0.90 individuals per {{convert|100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} in 2005 to 1.70 individuals per {{convert|100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} in 2008.<ref>{{Cite thesis |last=Sunarto |title=Ecology and restoration of Sumatran tigers in forest and plantation landscapes |type=PhD dissertation |year=2011 |publisher=Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University |location=Blacksburg |url= http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/theses/available/etd-02232011-212053/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130526011016/http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/theses/available/etd-02232011-212053/|archivedate= 2013-05-26}}</ref>\n\nIn the Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park, nine prey species larger than {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of body weight were identified including [[great argus]], [[pig-tailed macaque]], [[Malayan porcupine]], [[Malayan tapir]], [[banded pig]], [[Greater mouse-deer|greater]] and [[lesser mouse-deer]], [[Indian muntjac]], and [[Sambar deer]].<ref name=OBrien2003/>\n\n== Threats ==\n[[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Groep mensen bij tijgerval met tijger te Soepajang Padangse Bovenlanden Sumatra`s Westkust TMnr 60003566.jpg|thumb|Group of people at a tiger trap with a tiger in Soepajang, Bovenlanden Padang, on Sumatra's west coast (Circa 1895)]]\nMajor threats include habitat loss due to expansion of [[palm oil]] plantations and planting of acacia plantations, prey-base depletion, and [[Wildlife trade#In Asia|illegal trade]] primarily for the domestic market.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nTigers need large contiguous forest blocks to thrive.<ref name=Sunarto2012/> Between 1985 and 1999, forest loss within Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park averaged 2% per year. A total of {{convert|661|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of forest disappeared inside the park, and {{convert|318|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} were lost in a 10-km buffer, eliminating forest outside the park. Lowland forest disappeared faster than [[Montane ecology#Montane forests|montane forest]], and forests on gentle slopes disappeared faster than forests on steep slopes. Most forest conversion resulted from agricultural development, leading to predictions that by 2010, 70% of the park will be in agriculture. Camera-trap data indicated avoidance of forest boundaries by tigers. Classification of forest into core and peripheral forest based on mammal distribution suggests that by 2010, core forest area for tigers will be fragmented and reduced to 20% of remaining forest.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinnaird | first1 = M. F. | last2 = Sanderson | first2 = E. W. |last3=O'Brien | first3=T. G. |last4=Wibisono |first4=H. |last5=Woolmer |first5=G. |year=2003 |title=Deforestation trends in a tropical landscape and implications for forest mammals |journal=[[Conservation Biology (journal)|Conservation Biology]] |volume=17 |issue= |pages=245\u2013257 |doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.2003.02040.x |url=http://crs.itb.ac.id/media/jurnal/refs/draft/Social/Deforestation%20Trends%20in%20a%20Tropical%20Landscape%20and%20Implications%20for%20Endangered%20Large%20Mammals.pdf}}</ref>\n\nSumatra's largest tiger population in Kerinci Seblat National Park is threatened by a high rate of [[deforestation]] in its outer regions. Drivers are an unsustainable demand for natural resources created by a human population with the highest rate of growth in Indonesia, and a government initiative to increase tree-crop plantations and high-intensity commercial [[logging]], which ultimately leads to forest fires. The majority of the tigers found in the park were relocated to its center where conservation efforts are focused, but issues in the lowland hill forests of the outskirts remain. While being highly suitable tiger habitat, these areas are also heavily targeted by logging efforts, which substantially contributes to declines in local tiger numbers.<ref>{{Cite journal |author1=Linkie, M. |author2=Martyr, D. J. |author3=Holden, J. |author4=Yanuar, A. |author5=Hartana, A. T.  |author6=Sugardjito, J. |author7=Leader-Williams, N. |date=2003 |title=Habitat Destruction and Poaching Threaten the Sumatran Tiger in Kerinci Seblat National Park, Sumatra |journal=Oryx |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=41\u201348 |doi=10.1017/s0030605303000103 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231908557|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nThe expansion of plantations is also increasing greenhouse-gas emissions, playing a part in [[anthropogenic climate change]], thus further adding to environmental pressures on endangered species.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Sumatran deforestation driving climate change and species extinction, report warns |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/feb/27/climatechange.forests |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate = 2015-10-29 |first=J. |last=Aldred |date=2008}}</ref> Climate-based movement of tigers northwards may lead to increased conflict with human populations. From 1987 to 1997, Sumatran tigers reportedly killed 146 people and at least 870 livestock. In West Sumatra, Riau, and Aceh, a total of 128 incidents were reported; 265 tigers were killed and 97 captured in response, and 35 more tigers were killed from 1998 to 2002. From 2007 to 2010, the tigers caused the death of 9 humans and 25 further tigers were killed.<ref name=Wibisono2010/>\n\nIn 1997, an estimated 53 tigers were killed by poachers and their parts sold throughout most of northern Sumatra. Numbers for all of Sumatra are likely to be higher. Farmers killed many of the tigers to prevent livestock losses. They sold them to gold and souvenir shops, and pharmacies.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=The Illegal Market in Tiger Parts in Northern Sumatra, Indonesia |author=Plowden, C. |author2=Bowles, D. |date=1997 |journal=Oryx |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=59\u201366 |doi=10.1017/s0030605300021918}}</ref> In 2006, wildlife markets were surveyed in 28 cities and nine seaports in seven Sumatran provinces; 33 of 326 retail outlets offered tiger parts like skins, canines, bones, and whiskers. Tiger bones fetched the highest average price of US$116 per kg, followed by canines. There is evidence that tiger parts are smuggled out of Indonesia. In July 2005, over {{convert|140|kg|abbr=on}} of tiger bones and 24 skulls were confiscated in [[Taiwan]] in a shipment from [[Jakarta]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Ng, J. and Nemora |year=2007 |url=http://www.traffic.org/species-reports/traffic_species_mammals37.pdf |title=Tiger trade revisited in Sumatra, Indonesia |publisher=[[Traffic (conservation programme)|Traffic]], Southeast Asia |location=Petaling Jaya, Malaysia}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013\u20132014, Kerinci Seblat National Park experienced an upsurge in poaching, with the highest annual number of [[snare trap]]s being removed for a patrol effort similar to previous years. Evidence is scarce and misunderstood on whether the strategies implemented to diminish poaching are succeeding despite the investment of millions of dollars annually into conservation strategies.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Conservation ==\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n |image1=Tiger Melbourne.JPG |caption1=In the [[Melbourne Zoo]], [[Australia]]\n |image2=Tiger 14MAR(9)ed.jpg |caption2=In [[Dublin Zoo]], [[Ireland]]}}\n''Panthera tigris'' is listed on [[CITES Appendix I]]. Hunting is prohibited in Indonesia.<ref name=Nowell1996/>\n\nIn 1994, the Indonesian Sumatran Tiger Conservation Strategy addressed the potential crisis that tigers faced in Sumatra. The Sumatran Tiger Project (STP) was initiated in June 1995 in and around the [[Way Kambas National Park]] to ensure the long-term viability of wild Sumatran tigers and to accumulate data on tiger life-history characteristics vital for the management of wild populations.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Franklin, N. |author2=Bastoni |author3=Sriyanto |author4=Siswomartono, D. |author5=Manansang, J. |author6=Tilson, R.  |year=1999 |chapter=Last of the Indonesian tigers: a cause for optimism |pages=130\u2013147 |editor1-last=Seidensticker |editor1-first=J. |editor2-last=Christie |editor2-first=S. |editor3-last=Jackson |editor3-first=P. |title=Riding the Tiger: Tiger Conservation in Human-Dominated Landscapes |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521648356 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> By August 1999, the teams of the STP had evaluated 52 sites of potential tiger habitat in Lampung Province, of which only 15 were intact enough to contain tigers.<ref name=Tilson1999>{{cite book |author=Tilson, R. |year=1999 |title=Sumatran Tiger Project Report No. 17 & 18: July \u2212 December 1999. Grant number 1998-0093-059 |publisher=Indonesian Sumatran Tiger Steering Committee |location=Jakarta}}</ref> In the framework of the STP, a community-based conservation programme was initiated to document the tiger-human dimension in the park to enable conservation authorities to resolve tiger-human conflicts based on a comprehensive database rather than anecdotes and opinions.<ref name=Nyhus1999>{{cite book |author=Nyhus, P. |author2=Sumianto |author3=Tilson, R. |year=1999 |chapter=The tiger-human dimension in southeast Sumatra |pages=144\u2013145 |editor1-last=Seidensticker |editor1-first=J. |editor2-last=Christie |editor2-first=S. |editor3-last=Jackson |editor3-first=P. |title=Riding the Tiger: Tiger Conservation in Human-Dominated Landscapes |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521648356 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the [[Ministry of Environment and Forestry (Indonesia)|Indonesian Forestry Ministry]] and Safari Park established cooperation with the [[Australia Zoo]] for the conservation of Sumatran tigers and other endangered species. The program includes conserving Sumatran tigers and other endangered species in the wild, efforts to reduce conflicts between tigers and humans, and rehabilitating Sumatran tigers and reintroducing them to their [[natural habitat]]. One hectare of the 186-hectare [[Taman Safari]] is the world's only Sumatran tiger captive-breeding center that also has a [[sperm bank]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/12/15/sumatran-tiger-sperm-bank.html |title=Sumatran tiger sperm bank|first= Wahyoe|last= Boediwardhana|date=2012-12-15|work=The Jakarta Post|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141023063812/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/12/15/sumatran-tiger-sperm-bank.html|archive-date= 2014-10-23|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIndonesia's struggle with conservation has caused an upsurge in political momentum to protect and conserve wildlife and biodiversity. In 2009, Indonesia's president made a commitment to substantially reduce deforestation, and policies across the nation requiring spatial plans that would be environmentally sustainable at national, provincial and district levels.<ref name=\"Bhagabati_al2014\">{{Cite journal|title = Ecosystem services reinforce Sumatran tiger conservation in land use plans|journal = Biological Conservation|date =2014 |pages=147\u2013156 |volume=169 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2013.11.010 |first=Nirmal K. |last=Bhagabati|first2=T. |last2=Ricketts |first3=T. B. S. |last3=Sulistyawan |first4=M. |last4=Conte |first5=D. |last5=Ennaanay |first6=O.|last6=Hadian |first7=E. |last7=McKenzie |first8=N. |last8=Olwero |first9=A. |last9=Rosenthal}}</ref>\n\nSince about 2005, about US$210 million have been invested into tiger law-enforcement activities that support forest ranger patrols, as well as the implementations of front-line law-enforcement activities by the Global Tiger Recovery Plan, which aims to double the number of wild tigers by 2020.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2015 |title=Safeguarding Sumatran tigers: evaluating effectiveness of law enforcement patrols and local informant networks |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |pages=851\u2013860 |volume=52 |issue=4 |doi=10.1111/1365-2664.12461 |last1=Linkie |first1=M. |last2=Martyr|first2=D. J. |last3=Harihar |first3=A. |last4=Risdianto |first4=D. |last5=Nugraha |first5=R. T. |last6=Maryati |last7=Leader-Williams |first7=N. |last8=Wong |first8=W.-M.|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nA 2010 study examined a different strategy for promoting Sumatran tiger conservation while at the same time deriving a financial profit, by promoting \"tiger-friendly\" vegetable [[margarine]] as an alternative to palm oil. The study concluded that consumers were willing to pay a premium for high-quality margarine connected with tiger conservation.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Tigers, markets and palm oil: market potential for conservation |journal=Oryx |date=2010 |pages=230\u2013234 |volume=44|issue=2 |doi=10.1017/S0030605309990901|first=I. J. |last=Bateman |first2=B. |last2=Fisher|first3=E. |last3=Fitzherbert|first4=D. |last4=Glew |first5=R. |last5=Naidoo|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nA 110,000-acre conservation area and rehabilitation center, [[Tambling Wildlife Nature Conservation]], has been set up on the edge of a national park on the southern tip of Sumatra ([[Lampung]]).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://worldblog.nbcnews.com/_news/2010/11/19/5496434-on-the-prowl-for-man-eating-tigers|title= On the prowl for man-eating tigers|first= Ian|last= Williams|date= 2010-11-19|publisher= [[NBC News]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131113184902/http://worldblog.nbcnews.com/_news/2010/11/19/5496434-on-the-prowl-for-man-eating-tigers|archive-date= 2013-11-13|url-status= live}}</ref> On 26 October 2011, a tigress that had been captured with an injured leg in early October delivered three male cubs in a temporary cage while waiting for release after her recovery.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/11/01/272770/126/101/Tambling-Ketambahan-Tiga-Anak-Harimau|title= Tambling Ketambahan Tiga Anak Harimau |date=2011-11-01|work= [[Media Indonesia]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120407125506/http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/11/01/272770/126/101/Tambling-Ketambahan-Tiga-Anak-Harimau|archive-date= 2012-04-07|url-status= dead}} [https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=http%3A%2F%2Fweb.archive.org%2Fweb%2F20120407125506%2Fhttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.mediaindonesia.com%2Fread%2F2011%2F11%2F01%2F272770%2F126%2F101%2FTambling-Ketambahan-Tiga-Anak-Harimau&edit-text= English translation] at [[Google Translate]]</ref>\n\nDue to Indonesia's need for more sanctuaries for the Sumatran tiger, [[Sumatran elephant]], [[Sumatran orangutan]] and [[Sumatran rhinoceros]], the government opened the Batu Nanggar Sanctuary for the Sumatran tiger at [[North Padang Lawas Regency]], [[North Sumatra]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2016/11/25/sumatran-tigers-need-more-sanctuaries-government.html |title=Sumatran tigers need more sanctuaries: Government |author=Apriadi Gunawan |author2=Jon Afrizal |last-author-amp=yes |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n=== In captivity ===\nIn August 2011 two males and a female cub were born at [[Taronga Zoo Sydney|Taronga Zoo]] in Sydney, Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/29/tiger-cubs-debut-sydney-zoo_n_1033196.html|work=[[HuffPost]]|title=Tiger Cubs Make Their Debut At Sydney Zoo|date=29 October 2011}}</ref> On 6 February 2019, another two females and a male were born at the zoo.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/endangered-sumatran-tiger-gives-birth-002244447.html|title=Endangered Sumatran Tiger Gives Birth to Trio of Cubs at Taronga Zoo|last=|first= |date=2019|work=[[Yahoo! News]] |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, two cubs were born in [[London Zoo]], but one drowned in a pool two weeks later.<ref name=melati>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-24531460|work=[[BBC News]]|title=London Zoo newborn Sumatran tiger cub found dead |date=2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Sumatran tiger triplets born at London zoo |url= https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/13/sumatran-tiger-triplets-london-zoo |date=30 March 2014|first= J.|last= Aldred |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141024034021/http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/13/sumatran-tiger-triplets-london-zoo |archive-date=24 October 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2014, the female gave birth again, to three cubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-26550465 |title=Sumatran tiger cubs born at London Zoo |work=BBC News|date=13 March 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140325194005/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-26550465|archive-date=25 March 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> In June 2016, she gave birth to two cubs.<ref>{{cite news|title=ZSL London Zoo welcomes tiger cub twins|url=http://www.pressat.co.uk/releases/zsl-london-zoo-welcomes-tiger-cub-twins-c1ff7b5f4167344181b337788979c6f9/|date=30 June 2016|publisher=Pressat}}</ref>\nIn August 2017, two cubs were born at [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]] in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disney's Animal Kingdom Celebrates Birth of Critically Endangered Sumatran Tiger Cubs |url=https://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2017/08/wildlife-wednesday-disneys-animal-kingdom-celebrates-birth-of-critically-endangered-sumatran-tiger-cubs |website=Disney Parks Blog |first=M. |last=Penning |date=2017}}</ref>\nIn February 2019, a male tiger on [[stud (animal)|stud loan]] from a Danish safari park to London Zoo, killed his intended female mate during their first meeting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-47170454|work=BBC News|title=London Zoo Sumatran tiger Melati killed in fight |date=2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/08/sumatran-tiger-killed-by-potential-mate-on-first-meeting-in-london-zoo|newspaper=The Guardian|title=Sumatran tiger killed by potential mate on first meeting in London zoo|first=K. |last=Rawlinson |date=2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Bornean tiger]]\n* [[Caspian tiger]]\n* [[Indochinese tiger]]\n* [[Malayan tiger]]\n* [[Siberian tiger]]\n* [[South China tiger]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies|Panthera tigris sumatrae}}\n{{Commons|Panthera tigris sumatrae}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=124|title= Species portrait ''Panthera tigris''|publisher= [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]/SSC Cat Specialist Group|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141112171012/http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=124|archive-date= 2014-11-12|url-status= live}} and {{cite web |url= http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=568|title= short portrait ''P. t. sumatrae''|publisher= International Union for Conservation of Nature/SSC Cat Specialist Group|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141213043652/http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=568|archive-date= 2014-12-13|url-status= live}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.waza.org/en/site/conservation/waza-conservation-projects/overview/sumatran-tiger-trust-conservation-program|title= Sumatran Tiger Trust Conservation Program|publisher= [[World Association of Zoos and Aquariums]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150301160238/http://www.waza.org/en/site/conservation/waza-conservation-projects/overview/sumatran-tiger-trust-conservation-program|archive-date= 2015-03-01|url-status= live}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.tigers.ca/Tigerworld/W3A1.html|title= Tiger Facts \u2212 Sumatran Tiger|publisher= The Tiger Foundation|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131231115658/http://www.tigers.ca/Tigerworld/W3A1.html|archive-date= 2013-12-31|url-status= live}}\n* [https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/trailing-the-big-cats-161975907/ Overweight captive Sumatran tiger] ({{convert|338|lbs|kg|abbr=on}}) at the [[National Zoological Park (United States)]]\n* [https://news.mongabay.com/2018/03/indonesia-races-to-catch-tiger-alive-as-villagers-threaten-to-kill-the-beast/ Indonesia races to catch tiger alive as villagers threaten to \u2018kill the beast\u2019]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q191129}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiger, Sumatran}}\n[[Category:Fauna of Sumatra]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1929]]\n[[Category:Tigers|Sumatran tiger]]\n", "text_old": "{{Subspeciesbox\n| name = Sumatran tiger\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n| image = Sumatran Tiger Berlin Tierpark.jpg\n| image_caption = Sumatran tiger in the [[Tierpark Berlin]]\n| genus = Panthera\n| species = tigris\n| species_link = Tiger\n| range_map = Panthera tigris sumatrae distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = Distribution map\n| subspecies = sondaica\n| authority =([[Coenraad Jacob Temminck|Temminck]], 1844)\n|synonyms = formerly ''P. t. sumatrae'' [[Reginald Innes Pocock|Pocock]], 1929\n}}\n\nThe '''Sumatran tiger''' is a ''[[Panthera tigris sondaica]]'' population in the [[Indonesia]]n island of [[Sumatra]].<ref name=catsg2017>{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O\u2019Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |pages=66\u201368 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Luo_al2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Liu |first1=Y.-C. |first2=X. |last2=Sun |first3=C. |last3=Driscoll |first4=D. G. |last4=Miquelle |first5=X. |last5=Xu |first6=P. |last6=Martelli |first7=O. |last7=Uphyrkina |first8=J. L. D. |last8=Smith |first9=S. J. |last9=O\u2019Brien |first10=S.-J. |last10=Luo |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genome-wide evolutionary analysis of natural history and adaptation in the world's tigers |journal=Current Biology |volume=28 |issue=23 |year=2018 |pages=3840\u20133849 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2018.09.019 |pmid=30482605|doi-access=free }}</ref> This population was listed as [[Critically Endangered]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] in 2008, as it was estimated at 441 to 679 individuals, with no subpopulation larger than 50 individuals and a declining trend.<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |last1=Linkie |first1=M. |last2=Wibisono |first2=H. T. |last3=Martyr |first3=D. J. |last4=Sunarto |first4=S. |last-author-amp=yes |date=2008 |title=''Panthera tigris ssp. sumatrae'' |page=e.T15966A5334836}}</ref>\n\nThe Sumatran tiger is the only surviving tiger population in the [[Sunda Islands]], where the [[Bali tiger|Bali]] and [[Javan tiger]]s are extinct.<ref name=mazak06>{{cite journal |author1=Maz\u00e1k, J. H. |author2=Groves, C. P. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |title=A taxonomic revision of the tigers (''Panthera tigris'') |journal=Mammalian Biology |volume=71 |issue=5 |pages=268\u2013287 |doi=10.1016/j.mambio.2006.02.007 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313144127/http://arts.anu.edu.au/grovco/tiger%20SEAsia%20Mazak.pdf}}</ref> [[DNA sequencing|Sequences]] from complete [[mitochondrial gene]]s of 34 tigers support the hypothesis that Sumatran tigers are diagnostically distinct from mainland subspecies.<ref name=Cracraft1998>{{cite journal |author=Cracraft, J. |author2=Feinstein, J. |author3=Vaughn, J. |author4=Helm-Bychowski, K. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1998 |title=Sorting out tigers (''Panthera tigris''): Mitochondrial sequences, nuclear inserts, systematics, and conservation genetics |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013150 |url=http://research.amnh.org/vz/ornithology/pdfs/1998c.%20tiger%20conservation.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.1998.tb00021.x}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the Cat Classification Task Force of the Cat Specialist Group revised felid taxonomy and recognizes the living and extinct tiger populations in Indonesia as ''[[Sunda Island tiger|P. t. sondaica]]''.<ref name=catsg2017/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis tigris sondaicus'' was the [[scientific name]] proposed by [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]] in 1844 for a tiger specimen from [[Java]].<ref name=Temminck>{{cite book |author=Temminck, C. J. |year=1844 |chapter=Aper\u00e7u g\u00e9n\u00e9ral et sp\u00e9cifique sur les mammif\u00e8res qui habitent le Japon et les iles qui en d\u00e9pendent |title=Fauna Japonica sive Descriptio animalium, quae in itinere per Japoniam, jussu et auspiciis superiorum, qui summum in India Batava imperium tenent, suscepto, annis 1825 - 1830. Mammalia |editor1=von Siebold, F. |editor2=Temminck, C. J. |editor3=Schlegel, H. |editor4=de Haan, W. |editor5=Nakazawa, K. |editor6=Tanaka, S. |editor7=Kuroda, N. |editor8=Okada, Y. |location=Lugduni Batavorum |publisher=Arnz et Socius |pages=1\u201359 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/faunajaponicasi00sieb#page/42/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nThe genus ''[[Panthera]]'' was proposed by [[Reginald Innes Pocock]] in 1929 who described a skin and a skull of a tiger specimen from Sumatra using the name ''Panthera tigris sumatrae''.<ref name=Pocock1929>{{cite journal |author=Pocock, R. I. |year=1929 |title=Tigers |journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society |volume=33 |issue= |pages=505\u2013541 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofbomb33341929bomb/page/n185}}</ref>\nSkull and pelage pattern of tiger specimens from Java and Sumatra do not differ significantly.<ref name=Mazak2006/><ref>{{cite book |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Yamaguchi, N. |year=2010 |chapter=What is a tiger? Biogeography, morphology, and taxonomy |pages=53\u201384 |title=Tigers of the World |editor1=Tilson, R. |editor2=Nyhus, P. J. |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |edition=Second  |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266794969 |doi=10.1016/B978-0-8155-1570-8.00004-9 |isbn=9780080947518}}</ref>\n''P. t. sondaica'' is therefore considered the [[Valid name (zoology)|valid name]] for the living and extinct tiger populations in Indonesia.<ref name=catsg2017/>\n\n== Evolution ==\nAnalysis of [[DNA]] is consistent with the hypothesis that Sumatran tigers became isolated from other tiger populations after a rise in sea level that occurred at the [[Pleistocene]] to [[Holocene]] border about 12,000\u20136,000 years ago. In agreement with this evolutionary history, the Sumatran tiger is genetically isolated from all living mainland tigers, which form a distinct group closely related to each other.<ref name=Cracraft1998/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n[[File:Panthera tigris sumatrae (Sumatran Tiger) close-up.jpg|thumb|Close-up of a tiger at [[San Antonio Zoo and Aquarium]], [[Texas]]]]\nThe Sumatran tiger was described on the basis of two zoological specimens that differed in [[skull]] size and striping pattern from [[Bengal tiger|Bengal]] and [[Javan tiger]] specimen. It is darker in fur colour and has broader stripes than the Javan tiger.<ref name=Pocock1929/> Stripes tend to dissolve into spots near their ends, and on the back, flanks and hind legs are lines of small, dark spots between the regular stripes.<ref name=Mazak1981>{{cite journal|author=Maz\u00e1k, V. |year=1981 |title=''Panthera tigris'' |journal=Mammalian Species |volume=152 |pages=1\u20138 |doi=10.2307/3504004 |issue=152 |jstor=3504004 |url=http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-152-01-0001.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309125526/http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-152-01-0001.pdf|archive-date=2012-03-09|df=}}</ref><ref name=Mazak2006>{{cite journal |author=Maz\u00e1k, J. H. |author2=Groves, C. P. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |title=A taxonomic revision of the tigers (''Panthera tigris'') of Southeast Asia |journal=Mammalian Biology-Zeitschrift f\u00fcr S\u00e4ugetierkunde |volume=71 |issue=5|pages=268\u2013287 |doi=10.1016/j.mambio.2006.02.007}}</ref> The frequency of stripes is higher than in other subspecies.<ref>{{cite book |author=Kitchener, A. |year=1999 |chapter=Tiger distribution, phenotypic variation and conservation issues |chapterurl=http://www.nfwf.org/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Home&CONTENTID=3060&TEMPLATE=/CM/ContentDisplay.cfm |pages=19\u201339 |title=Riding the Tiger. Tiger Conservation in human-dominated landscapes |editor1-last=Seidensticker |editor1-first=J. |editor2-last=Christie |editor2-first=S., Jackson, P. |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-521-64057-2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423162028/http://www.nfwf.org/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Home |archivedate=2012-04-23 }}</ref>\nMales have a prominent ruff, which is especially marked in the Sumatran tiger.<ref name=Nowell1996>Nowell, K., Jackson, P. (1996). [http://www.catsg.org/catsgportal/cat-website/catfolk/tiger-01.htm Tiger ''Panthera tigris'' (Linnaeus 1758)] in: ''Wild Cats: status survey and conservation action plan.'' IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group, Gland, Switzerland</ref>\n\nThe Sumatran tiger is one of the smallest tigers. Males measure between the pegs {{convert|2.2|to|2.55|m|in|abbr=on}} in head-to-body length, with a greatest length of skull of {{convert|295|to|335|mm|abbr=on}}, and weigh {{convert|100|to|140|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Females weigh {{convert|75|to|110|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and measure {{convert|2.15|to|2.30|m|in|abbr=on}} in length between the pegs with a greatest length of skull of {{convert|263|to|294|mm|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Mazak1981 />\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe Sumatran tiger persists in small and fragmented populations across Sumatra, from [[sea level]] in the coastal lowland forest of [[Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park]] on the southeastern tip of [[Lampung Province]] to {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}} in mountain forests of [[Gunung Leuser National Park]] in [[Aceh Province]]. It is present in 27 habitat patches larger than {{convert|250|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, which cover {{convert|140226|km2|abbr=on}}. About a third of these patches are inside protected areas.<ref name=OBrien2003>{{cite journal|author=O\u2019Brien, T. G.|author2=Kinnard, M. F.|author3=Wibisono, H. T.|last-author-amp=yes |year=2003|title=Crouching tigers, hidden prey: Sumatran tiger and prey populations in a tropical forest landscape |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=131\u2013139 |doi=10.1017/S1367943003003172|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f89556b08c9b31e3a27dcd7464c8b9dfb0d6fca7}}</ref><ref name=Wibisono2010>{{cite journal|author1=Wibisono, H. T. |author2=Pusarini, W. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Sumatran tiger (''Panthera tigris sumatrae''): A review of conservation status |doi=10.1111/j.1749-4877.2010.00219.x |year=2010|journal=Integrative Zoology|volume=5|issue=4|pages=313\u2013323 |pmid=21392349 |url=https://www.academia.edu/4002510}}</ref>\n\nSumatran tigers prefer lowland and hill forests, where up to three tigers live in an area of {{convert|100|km2|abbr=on}}. They use non-forest habitats and human-dominated landscapes at the fringes of protected areas to a lesser degree.<ref name=Luskin_al2017>{{cite journal |last1=Luskin |first1=M. S. |last2=Albert |first2=W. R. |last3=Tobler |first3=M. W. |year=2017 |title=Sumatran tiger survival threatened by deforestation despite increasing densities in parks |journal=Nature Communications |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=1783 |doi=10.1038/s41467-017-01656-4 |pmid=29208916 |pmc=5717059 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, the Sumatran tiger population was estimated at 1,000 individuals, based on responses to a questionnaire survey.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Borner, M. |year=1978 |title=Status and conservation of the Sumatran tiger |journal=Carnivore |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages= 97\u2013102}}</ref> In 1985, a total of 26 protected areas across Sumatra containing about 800 tigers were identified.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Santiapillai, C. |author2=Ramono, W. S. |year=1987 |chapter=Tiger numbers and habitat evaluation in Indonesia |chapterurl= |pages=85\u201391 |title=Tigers of the World: The Biology, Biopolitics, Management, and Conservation of an Endangered Species |editor1=Tilson, R. L. |editor2=Seal, U. S. |publisher=Noyes Publications |location=New Jersey |isbn=0815511337}}</ref> In 1992, an estimated 400\u2013500 tigers lived in five [[List of national parks of Indonesia#Sumatra|Sumatran national parks]] and two [[Protected areas of Indonesia|protected areas]]. At that time, the largest population comprising 110\u2013180 individuals was reported to live in Gunung Leuser National Park.<ref>{{cite book |editor1=Tilson, R. L. |editor2=Soemarna, K. |editor3=Ramono, W. S. |editor4=Lusli, S. |editor5=Traylor-Holzer, K. |editor6=Seal, U. S. |year=1994 |title=Sumatran Tiger Populations and Habitat Viability Analysis |publisher=Indonesian Directorate General of Forest Protection and Nature Conservation and IUCN/SSC Conservation Breeding Specialist Group |location=Apple Valley |author=Griffiths, M. |chapter=Population density of Sumatran tigers in Gunung Leuser National Park |pages=93\u2013102}}</ref>\nAs of 2011, the tiger population in [[Kerinci Seblat National Park]] in central Sumatra comprised 165\u2013190 individuals, which is more than anywhere else on the island. The park has the highest tiger occupancy rate of Sumatra's protected areas, with 83% of the park showing signs of tigers.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Wibisono, H. T. |author2=Linkie, M. |author3=Guillera-Arroita, G. |author4=Smith, J. A. |author5=Sunarto |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0025931 |title=Population Status of a Cryptic Top Predator: An Island-Wide Assessment of Tigers in Sumatran Rainforests |year=2011 |journal= [[PLoS ONE]] |volume=6 |issue=11 |pages=e25931 |pmid=22087218 |pmc=3206793 |bibcode=2011PLoSO...625931W}}</ref>\n\nSumatra's total tiger population was estimated at 618\u2009\u00b1\u2009290 individuals in 2017.<ref name=Luskin_al2017/>\n\n== Ecology and behaviour ==\n[[File:Wild Sumatran tiger.jpg|thumb|A wild Sumatran tiger photographed by a camera trap]]\n[[File:Beautiful Sumatran Tiger Cub (9711349588).jpg|thumb|Sumatran tiger cub at the [[Chester Zoo]]]]\nSumatran tigers strongly prefer uncultivated forest and make little use of [[plantations]] of [[acacia]] and [[oil palm]] even if these are available. Within natural forest areas, they tend to use areas with higher elevation, lower annual rainfall, farther from forest edge, and closer to forest centres. They prefer forest with dense understory cover and steep slope, and they strongly avoid forest areas with high human influence in the forms of encroachment and settlement. In acacia plantations, they tend to use areas closer to water, and prefer areas with older plants, more leaf litter, and thicker subcanopy cover. Tiger records in oil palm plantations and in [[rubber plantation]]s are scarce. The availability of adequate vegetation cover at the ground level serves as an environmental condition fundamentally needed by tigers regardless of the location. Without adequate understory cover, tigers are even more vulnerable to persecution by humans. Human disturbance-related variables negatively affect tiger occupancy and habitat use. Variables with strong impacts include settlement and encroachment within forest areas, [[logging]], and the intensity of maintenance in acacia plantations.<ref name=Sunarto2012>{{cite journal|author=Sunarto |author2=Kelly, M. J.|author3=Parakkasi, K. |author4=Klenzendorf, S.|author5=Septayuda, E.|author6=Kurniawan, H. |year=2012 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0030859 |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=7|issue=1|page= e30859 |title=Tigers Need Cover: Multi-Scale Occupancy Study of the Big Cat in Sumatran Forest and Plantation Landscapes |editor=Gratwicke, B. |pmid=22292063|pmc=3264627 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...730859S}}</ref>\n[[Camera trap]]ping surveys conducted in southern [[Riau]] revealed an extremely low abundance of potential prey and a low tiger density in [[peat swamp forest]] areas. Repeated sampling in the newly established [[Tesso Nilo National Park]] documented a trend of increasing tiger density from 0.90 individuals per {{convert|100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} in 2005 to 1.70 individuals per {{convert|100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} in 2008.<ref>{{Cite thesis |last=Sunarto |title=Ecology and restoration of Sumatran tigers in forest and plantation landscapes |type=PhD dissertation |year=2011 |publisher=Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University |location=Blacksburg |url= http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/theses/available/etd-02232011-212053/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130526011016/http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/theses/available/etd-02232011-212053/|archivedate= 2013-05-26}}</ref>\n\nIn the Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park, nine prey species larger than {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of body weight were identified including [[great argus]], [[pig-tailed macaque]], [[Malayan porcupine]], [[Malayan tapir]], [[banded pig]], [[Greater mouse-deer|greater]] and [[lesser mouse-deer]], [[Indian muntjac]], and [[Sambar deer]].<ref name=OBrien2003/>\n\n== Threats ==\n[[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Groep mensen bij tijgerval met tijger te Soepajang Padangse Bovenlanden Sumatra`s Westkust TMnr 60003566.jpg|thumb|Group of people at a tiger trap with a tiger in Soepajang, Bovenlanden Padang, on Sumatra's west coast (Circa 1895)]]\nMajor threats include habitat loss due to expansion of [[palm oil]] plantations and planting of acacia plantations, prey-base depletion, and [[Wildlife trade#In Asia|illegal trade]] primarily for the domestic market.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nTigers need large contiguous forest blocks to thrive.<ref name=Sunarto2012/> Between 1985 and 1999, forest loss within Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park averaged 2% per year. A total of {{convert|661|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of forest disappeared inside the park, and {{convert|318|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} were lost in a 10-km buffer, eliminating forest outside the park. Lowland forest disappeared faster than [[Montane ecology#Montane forests|montane forest]], and forests on gentle slopes disappeared faster than forests on steep slopes. Most forest conversion resulted from agricultural development, leading to predictions that by 2010, 70% of the park will be in agriculture. Camera-trap data indicated avoidance of forest boundaries by tigers. Classification of forest into core and peripheral forest based on mammal distribution suggests that by 2010, core forest area for tigers will be fragmented and reduced to 20% of remaining forest.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinnaird | first1 = M. F. | last2 = Sanderson | first2 = E. W. |last3=O'Brien | first3=T. G. |last4=Wibisono |first4=H. |last5=Woolmer |first5=G. |year=2003 |title=Deforestation trends in a tropical landscape and implications for forest mammals |journal=[[Conservation Biology (journal)|Conservation Biology]] |volume=17 |issue= |pages=245\u2013257 |doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.2003.02040.x |url=http://crs.itb.ac.id/media/jurnal/refs/draft/Social/Deforestation%20Trends%20in%20a%20Tropical%20Landscape%20and%20Implications%20for%20Endangered%20Large%20Mammals.pdf}}</ref>\n\nSumatra's largest tiger population in Kerinci Seblat National Park is threatened by a high rate of [[deforestation]] in its outer regions. Drivers are an unsustainable demand for natural resources created by a human population with the highest rate of growth in Indonesia, and a government initiative to increase tree-crop plantations and high-intensity commercial [[logging]], which ultimately leads to forest fires. The majority of the tigers found in the park were relocated to its center where conservation efforts are focused, but issues in the lowland hill forests of the outskirts remain. While being highly suitable tiger habitat, these areas are also heavily targeted by logging efforts, which substantially contributes to declines in local tiger numbers.<ref>{{Cite journal |author1=Linkie, M. |author2=Martyr, D. J. |author3=Holden, J. |author4=Yanuar, A. |author5=Hartana, A. T.  |author6=Sugardjito, J. |author7=Leader-Williams, N. |date=2003 |title=Habitat Destruction and Poaching Threaten the Sumatran Tiger in Kerinci Seblat National Park, Sumatra |journal=Oryx |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=41\u201348 |doi=10.1017/s0030605303000103 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231908557|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nThe expansion of plantations is also increasing greenhouse-gas emissions, playing a part in [[anthropogenic climate change]], thus further adding to environmental pressures on endangered species.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Sumatran deforestation driving climate change and species extinction, report warns |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/feb/27/climatechange.forests |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate = 2015-10-29 |first=J. |last=Aldred |date=2008}}</ref> Climate-based movement of tigers northwards may lead to increased conflict with human populations. From 1987 to 1997, Sumatran tigers reportedly killed 146 people and at least 870 livestock. In West Sumatra, Riau, and Aceh, a total of 128 incidents were reported; 265 tigers were killed and 97 captured in response, and 35 more tigers were killed from 1998 to 2002. From 2007 to 2010, the tigers caused the death of 9 humans and 25 further tigers were killed.<ref name=Wibisono2010/>\n\nIn 1997, an estimated 53 tigers were killed by poachers and their parts sold throughout most of northern Sumatra. Numbers for all of Sumatra are likely to be higher. Farmers killed many of the tigers to prevent livestock losses. They sold them to gold and souvenir shops, and pharmacies.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=The Illegal Market in Tiger Parts in Northern Sumatra, Indonesia |author=Plowden, C. |author2=Bowles, D. |date=1997 |journal=Oryx |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=59\u201366 |doi=10.1017/s0030605300021918}}</ref> In 2006, wildlife markets were surveyed in 28 cities and nine seaports in seven Sumatran provinces; 33 of 326 retail outlets offered tiger parts like skins, canines, bones, and whiskers. Tiger bones fetched the highest average price of US$116 per kg, followed by canines. There is evidence that tiger parts are smuggled out of Indonesia. In July 2005, over {{convert|140|kg|abbr=on}} of tiger bones and 24 skulls were confiscated in [[Taiwan]] in a shipment from [[Jakarta]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Ng, J. and Nemora |year=2007 |url=http://www.traffic.org/species-reports/traffic_species_mammals37.pdf |title=Tiger trade revisited in Sumatra, Indonesia |publisher=[[Traffic (conservation programme)|Traffic]], Southeast Asia |location=Petaling Jaya, Malaysia}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013\u20132014, Kerinci Seblat National Park experienced an upsurge in poaching, with the highest annual number of [[snare trap]]s being removed for a patrol effort similar to previous years. Evidence is scarce and misunderstood on whether the strategies implemented to diminish poaching are succeeding despite the investment of millions of dollars annually into conservation strategies.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Conservation ==\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical\n |image1=Tiger Melbourne.JPG |caption1=In the [[Melbourne Zoo]], [[Australia]]\n |image2=Tiger 14MAR(9)ed.jpg |caption2=In [[Dublin Zoo]], [[Ireland]]}}\n''Panthera tigris'' is listed on [[CITES Appendix I]]. Hunting is prohibited in Indonesia.<ref name=Nowell1996/>\n\nIn 1994, the Indonesian Sumatran Tiger Conservation Strategy addressed the potential crisis that tigers faced in Sumatra. The Sumatran Tiger Project (STP) was initiated in June 1995 in and around the [[Way Kambas National Park]] to ensure the long-term viability of wild Sumatran tigers and to accumulate data on tiger life-history characteristics vital for the management of wild populations.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Franklin, N. |author2=Bastoni |author3=Sriyanto |author4=Siswomartono, D. |author5=Manansang, J. |author6=Tilson, R.  |year=1999 |chapter=Last of the Indonesian tigers: a cause for optimism |pages=130\u2013147 |editor1-last=Seidensticker |editor1-first=J. |editor2-last=Christie |editor2-first=S. |editor3-last=Jackson |editor3-first=P. |title=Riding the Tiger: Tiger Conservation in Human-Dominated Landscapes |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521648356 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> By August 1999, the teams of the STP had evaluated 52 sites of potential tiger habitat in Lampung Province, of which only 15 were intact enough to contain tigers.<ref name=Tilson1999>{{cite book |author=Tilson, R. |year=1999 |title=Sumatran Tiger Project Report No. 17 & 18: July \u2212 December 1999. Grant number 1998-0093-059 |publisher=Indonesian Sumatran Tiger Steering Committee |location=Jakarta}}</ref> In the framework of the STP, a community-based conservation programme was initiated to document the tiger-human dimension in the park to enable conservation authorities to resolve tiger-human conflicts based on a comprehensive database rather than anecdotes and opinions.<ref name=Nyhus1999>{{cite book |author=Nyhus, P. |author2=Sumianto |author3=Tilson, R. |year=1999 |chapter=The tiger-human dimension in southeast Sumatra |pages=144\u2013145 |editor1-last=Seidensticker |editor1-first=J. |editor2-last=Christie |editor2-first=S. |editor3-last=Jackson |editor3-first=P. |title=Riding the Tiger: Tiger Conservation in Human-Dominated Landscapes |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521648356 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the [[Ministry of Environment and Forestry (Indonesia)|Indonesian Forestry Ministry]] and Safari Park established cooperation with the [[Australia Zoo]] for the conservation of Sumatran tigers and other endangered species. The program includes conserving Sumatran tigers and other endangered species in the wild, efforts to reduce conflicts between tigers and humans, and rehabilitating Sumatran tigers and reintroducing them to their [[natural habitat]]. One hectare of the 186-hectare [[Taman Safari]] is the world's only Sumatran tiger captive-breeding center that also has a [[sperm bank]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/12/15/sumatran-tiger-sperm-bank.html |title=Sumatran tiger sperm bank|first= Wahyoe|last= Boediwardhana|date=2012-12-15|work=The Jakarta Post|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141023063812/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/12/15/sumatran-tiger-sperm-bank.html|archive-date= 2014-10-23|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIndonesia's struggle with conservation has caused an upsurge in political momentum to protect and conserve wildlife and biodiversity. In 2009, Indonesia's president made a commitment to substantially reduce deforestation, and policies across the nation requiring spatial plans that would be environmentally sustainable at national, provincial and district levels.<ref name=\"Bhagabati_al2014\">{{Cite journal|title = Ecosystem services reinforce Sumatran tiger conservation in land use plans|journal = Biological Conservation|date =2014 |pages=147\u2013156 |volume=169 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2013.11.010 |first=Nirmal K. |last=Bhagabati|first2=T. |last2=Ricketts |first3=T. B. S. |last3=Sulistyawan |first4=M. |last4=Conte |first5=D. |last5=Ennaanay |first6=O.|last6=Hadian |first7=E. |last7=McKenzie |first8=N. |last8=Olwero |first9=A. |last9=Rosenthal}}</ref>\n\nSince about 2005, about US$210 million have been invested into tiger law-enforcement activities that support forest ranger patrols, as well as the implementations of front-line law-enforcement activities by the Global Tiger Recovery Plan, which aims to double the number of wild tigers by 2020.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2015 |title=Safeguarding Sumatran tigers: evaluating effectiveness of law enforcement patrols and local informant networks |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |pages=851\u2013860 |volume=52 |issue=4 |doi=10.1111/1365-2664.12461 |last1=Linkie |first1=M. |last2=Martyr|first2=D. J. |last3=Harihar |first3=A. |last4=Risdianto |first4=D. |last5=Nugraha |first5=R. T. |last6=Maryati |last7=Leader-Williams |first7=N. |last8=Wong |first8=W.-M.|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nA 2010 study examined a different strategy for promoting Sumatran tiger conservation while at the same time deriving a financial profit, by promoting \"tiger-friendly\" vegetable [[margarine]] as an alternative to palm oil. The study concluded that consumers were willing to pay a premium for high-quality margarine connected with tiger conservation.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Tigers, markets and palm oil: market potential for conservation |journal=Oryx |date=2010 |pages=230\u2013234 |volume=44|issue=2 |doi=10.1017/S0030605309990901|first=I. J. |last=Bateman |first2=B. |last2=Fisher|first3=E. |last3=Fitzherbert|first4=D. |last4=Glew |first5=R. |last5=Naidoo|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nA 110,000-acre conservation area and rehabilitation center, [[Tambling Wildlife Nature Conservation]], has been set up on the edge of a national park on the southern tip of Sumatra ([[Lampung]]).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://worldblog.nbcnews.com/_news/2010/11/19/5496434-on-the-prowl-for-man-eating-tigers|title= On the prowl for man-eating tigers|first= Ian|last= Williams|date= 2010-11-19|publisher= [[NBC News]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131113184902/http://worldblog.nbcnews.com/_news/2010/11/19/5496434-on-the-prowl-for-man-eating-tigers|archive-date= 2013-11-13|url-status= live}}</ref> On 26 October 2011, a tigress that had been captured with an injured leg in early October delivered three male cubs in a temporary cage while waiting for release after her recovery.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/11/01/272770/126/101/Tambling-Ketambahan-Tiga-Anak-Harimau|title= Tambling Ketambahan Tiga Anak Harimau |date=2011-11-01|work= [[Media Indonesia]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120407125506/http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/11/01/272770/126/101/Tambling-Ketambahan-Tiga-Anak-Harimau|archive-date= 2012-04-07|url-status= dead}} [https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=http%3A%2F%2Fweb.archive.org%2Fweb%2F20120407125506%2Fhttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.mediaindonesia.com%2Fread%2F2011%2F11%2F01%2F272770%2F126%2F101%2FTambling-Ketambahan-Tiga-Anak-Harimau&edit-text= English translation] at [[Google Translate]]</ref>\n\nDue to Indonesia's need for more sanctuaries for the Sumatran tiger, [[Sumatran elephant]], [[Sumatran orangutan]] and [[Sumatran rhinoceros]], the government opened the Batu Nanggar Sanctuary for the Sumatran tiger at [[North Padang Lawas Regency]], [[North Sumatra]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2016/11/25/sumatran-tigers-need-more-sanctuaries-government.html |title=Sumatran tigers need more sanctuaries: Government |author=Apriadi Gunawan |author2=Jon Afrizal |last-author-amp=yes |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n=== In captivity ===\nIn August 2011 two males and a female cub were born at [[Taronga Zoo Sydney|Taronga Zoo]] in Sydney, Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/29/tiger-cubs-debut-sydney-zoo_n_1033196.html|work=[[HuffPost]]|title=Tiger Cubs Make Their Debut At Sydney Zoo|date=29 October 2011}}</ref> On 6 February 2019, another two females and a male were born at the zoo.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/endangered-sumatran-tiger-gives-birth-002244447.html|title=Endangered Sumatran Tiger Gives Birth to Trio of Cubs at Taronga Zoo|last=|first= |date=2019|work=[[Yahoo! News]] |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, two cubs were born in [[London Zoo]], but one drowned in a pool two weeks later.<ref name=melati>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-24531460|work=[[BBC News]]|title=London Zoo newborn Sumatran tiger cub found dead |date=2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Sumatran tiger triplets born at London zoo |url= https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/13/sumatran-tiger-triplets-london-zoo |date=30 March 2014|first= J.|last= Aldred |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141024034021/http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/13/sumatran-tiger-triplets-london-zoo |archive-date=24 October 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2014, the female gave birth again, to three cubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-26550465 |title=Sumatran tiger cubs born at London Zoo |work=BBC News|date=13 March 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140325194005/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-26550465|archive-date=25 March 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> In June 2016, she gave birth to two cubs.<ref>{{cite news|title=ZSL London Zoo welcomes tiger cub twins|url=http://www.pressat.co.uk/releases/zsl-london-zoo-welcomes-tiger-cub-twins-c1ff7b5f4167344181b337788979c6f9/|date=30 June 2016|publisher=Pressat}}</ref>\nIn August 2017, two cubs were born at [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]] in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disney's Animal Kingdom Celebrates Birth of Critically Endangered Sumatran Tiger Cubs |url=https://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2017/08/wildlife-wednesday-disneys-animal-kingdom-celebrates-birth-of-critically-endangered-sumatran-tiger-cubs |website=Disney Parks Blog |first=M. |last=Penning |date=2017}}</ref>\nIn February 2019, a male tiger on [[stud (animal)|stud loan]] from a Danish safari park to London Zoo, killed his intended female mate during their first meeting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-47170454|work=BBC News|title=London Zoo Sumatran tiger Melati killed in fight |date=2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/08/sumatran-tiger-killed-by-potential-mate-on-first-meeting-in-london-zoo|newspaper=The Guardian|title=Sumatran tiger killed by potential mate on first meeting in London zoo|first=K. |last=Rawlinson |date=2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Bornean tiger]]\n* [[Caspian tiger]]\n* [[Indochinese tiger]]\n* [[Malayan tiger]]\n* [[Siberian tiger]]\n* [[South China tiger]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies|Panthera tigris sumatrae}}\n{{Commons|Panthera tigris sumatrae}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=124|title= Species portrait ''Panthera tigris''|publisher= [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]/SSC Cat Specialist Group|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141112171012/http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=124|archive-date= 2014-11-12|url-status= live}} and {{cite web |url= http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=568|title= short portrait ''P. t. sumatrae''|publisher= International Union for Conservation of Nature/SSC Cat Specialist Group|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141213043652/http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=568|archive-date= 2014-12-13|url-status= live}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.waza.org/en/site/conservation/waza-conservation-projects/overview/sumatran-tiger-trust-conservation-program|title= Sumatran Tiger Trust Conservation Program|publisher= [[World Association of Zoos and Aquariums]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150301160238/http://www.waza.org/en/site/conservation/waza-conservation-projects/overview/sumatran-tiger-trust-conservation-program|archive-date= 2015-03-01|url-status= live}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.tigers.ca/Tigerworld/W3A1.html|title= Tiger Facts \u2212 Sumatran Tiger|publisher= The Tiger Foundation|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131231115658/http://www.tigers.ca/Tigerworld/W3A1.html|archive-date= 2013-12-31|url-status= live}}\n* [https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/trailing-the-big-cats-161975907/ Overweight captive Sumatran tiger] ({{convert|338|lbs|kg|abbr=on}}) at the [[National Zoological Park (United States)]]\n* [https://news.mongabay.com/2018/03/indonesia-races-to-catch-tiger-alive-as-villagers-threaten-to-kill-the-beast/ Indonesia races to catch tiger alive as villagers threaten to \u2018kill the beast\u2019]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q191129}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiger, Sumatran}}\n[[Category:Fauna of Sumatra]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1929]]\n[[Category:Tigers|Sumatran tiger]]\n", "name_user": "69.180.113.127", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacteristics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumatran_tiger"}
{"title_page": "Emilia Mernes", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Emilia Mernes\n| image              = https://amp.tn.com.ar/show/basicas/preocupacion-en-las-redes-emi-mernes-la-excantante-de-rombai-se-hizo-un-tratamiento-facial-y-quedo_959849\n| alt                = 80\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Mar\u00eda Emilia Mernes\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1996|10|29}}\n| birth_place        = [[Nogoy\u00e1]], [[Entre R\u00edos Province|Entre R\u00edos]], Argentina\n| residence          = Miami\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|model|dancer}}\n| organization       = \n| years_active       = 2016\u2013present\n| net_worth          = US$100 m\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed        = yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Reggaet\u00f3n]]\n* pop\n* [[Urban pop]]\n}}\n| instrument   = Vocals\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sony Music]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[:es:Rombai|Rombai]] \n* \n* [[Oriana Sabatini]]\n* [[Ana Mena]]\n}}\n| website             = \n}}\n}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Emilia Mernes''' (October 29, 1996), better known as '''Emilia''', is an Argentine singer,songwriter, dancer and model. Born in [[Nogoy\u00e1, Entre R\u00edos]], Emilia rose to fame in the late 2016s as lead singer of the cumbia-pop group Rombai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elobservador.com.uy/nota/-quien-es-emilia-mernes-la-nueva-cantante-de-rombai--201611813150|title=Qui\u00e9n es Emilia Mernes, la nueva cantante de Rombai|date=November 8, 2016|accessdate=September 21, 2019|language=Spanish|work=[[El Observador (Uruguay)|El Observador]]}}</ref> From 2016 to 2018, the group performed on some of the most important stages of Latin America, until Emilia announced her departure from the group to focus on her solo career. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pantallazo.com.uy/Pantallazo/Emi-Mernes-ya-no-formara-parte-de-Rombai-e-iniciara-una-carrera-solista-uc679694|title=Emi Mernes ya no formar\u00e1 parte de Rombai e iniciar\u00e1 una carrera solista|date=April 7, 2018|accessdate=September 21, 2019|language=Spanish|work=Pantallazo}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, after signing a contract with [[Walter Kolm|W. K. Entertainment]] and [[Sony Music]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8494418/emilia-mernes-contract-walter-kolm-entertainment|title=Argentine Singer Emilia Mernes Signs With Walter Kolm Entertainment|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=September 21, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> Emilia released her debut single \"Recalienta,\" which peaked at number 68 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Argentina Hot 100]]\n\n==Discography==\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles as lead artist with chart positions, showing year released\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Peaks\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Argentina Hot 100|ARG]]<br/><ref name=\"ARG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artist=Emilia&title=&label=&chart_name=Billboard+Argentina+Hot+100&chart_date=|title=Chart Search: Emilia, Billboard Argentina Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[National-Report|ECU]]<br/><ref name=\"ECU\">Peak positions in Ecuador:\n* \"Boomshakalaka\": {{cite web|url=http://www.national-report.com/top-ecuador/|title=Top 100 Ecuador \u2013 Semana 12 del 2020 \u2013 Del 13/03/2020 al 19/03/2020|publisher=[[National