{"title_page": "List of fugitives from justice who disappeared", "text_new": "{{For|other lists of disappeared persons|Lists of people who disappeared}}\n{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Confusing|date=May 2019}}\n{{Globalize|article|the US and Europe|date=May 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{dynamic list}}\nThis is a list of [[fugitive]]s from justice, notable people who disappeared{{explain|date=May 2019}} while being sought by [[law enforcement agencies]] in connection with a crime, and are currently sought. Listing here does not imply guilt and may include persons who are or were wanted only for questioning.\n\n<!--Entries must be those of people or disappearances that are notable because an article about them already exists. Do not add an entry if you cannot link to such an article.-->\n{{horizontal TOC|nonum=yes}}\n\n==Before 1900==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n!Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1696-01-01\"|1696\n|[[Henry Every]] (sometimes spelled 'Avery') \n|37\n|{{flagcountry|Kingdom of England}}\n|Every, an [[English people|English]] pirate, vanished after perpetrating one of the most profitable pirate raids in history. Despite a worldwide manhunt and an enormous bounty on his head, Every was never heard from again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/henry-avery-pirate-who-kept-loot-2136226|title=Henry Avery: The Pirate Who Kept His Loot|work=ThoughtCo|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> In March, Every had led his ship, the ''[[Fancy (ship)|Fancy]]'', to the island of [[New Providence]]. He and his crew spent months living there and soon lost their ship. By June, Every and his crew were forced to flee the island. The crew then split up, with Every possibly setting sail toward [[Ireland]]. A manhunt for Every lasted for at least a decade. There were several unconfirmed sightings of him and contradictory reports of his death during the 18th century. Most of them are considered unreliable, however, and his fate is unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goldenageofpiracy.org/infamous-pirates/henry-every.php|title=Infamous Pirates {{!}} Henry Every, the 'King of Pirates'|last=Humanity|first=History of|website=www.goldenageofpiracy.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1873-11-22\"|1873\n|[[William J. Sharkey (murderer)|William J. Sharkey]]\n|26\u201327\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1867}}}}\n|Sharkey was a convicted murderer and minor [[New York City]] [[politician]] who earned national notoriety for escaping from a [[New York City]] prison disguised as a woman in 1873. He reportedly fled to [[Cuba]], which had no extradition treaty with the United States. His ultimate fate is unknown.<ref>Sutton, Charles, James B. Mix, and Samuel A. Mackeever. ''The New York Tombs: Its Secrets and Its Mysteries. Being a History of Noted Criminals, with Narratives of their Crimes.'' New York: United States Pub. Co., 1974. 482\u2013498.</ref>\n|-\n|1875\n||[[Moses Ehrich]]\n|24\u201325\n|{{Flag|United States|1867}}\n|Ehrich was an American businessman and underworld figure known as \"'Old Unger\" who served as a [[fence (criminal)|fence]] to burglars, thieves and shoplifters from his Eldridge Street store throughout the mid to late 19th century.<ref>Crapsey, Edward. ''The Nether Side of New York, Or, the Vice, Crime and Poverty of the Great Metropolis''. Sheldon & Company, 1872. (p. 85)</ref><ref>Harlow, Alvin F. ''Old Bowery Days: The Chronicles of a Famous Street''. New York and London: D. Appleton & Company, 1931. (p. 377)</ref><ref>Nadel, Stanley. ''Little Germany: Ethnicity, Religion, and Class in New York City, 1845\u201380''. Urbana: University of Illinois Press, 1990. (p. 88) {{ISBN|0-252-01677-7}}</ref> He was indicted four or five times on charges of receiving stolen goods during the administration of [[A. Oakley Hall]], but always escaped conviction. Ehrich was represented by Hall in later years.<ref name=\"Article\">\"The Adams Express Robbery \u2013 Disappearance of Moses Ehrich\". ''New York Times''. 17 Mar 1875</ref> Ehrich disappeared from [[New York City]] in 1875 and escaped to Canada,<ref>Walling, George W. ''Recollections of a New York Chief of Police: An Official Record of Thirty-eight Years as Patrolman, Detective, Captain, Inspector and Chief of the New York Police''. New York: Caxton Book Concern, 1887. (p. 222)</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/recollectionsan00wallgoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/recollectionsan00wallgoog/page/n228 222]|quote=Moses Ehrich.|title=Recollections of a New York Chief of Police|last=Walling|first=George Washington|date=1887|publisher=Caxton book concern, limited|language=en}}</ref> and was never seen again.\n|-\n|1881\n|[[Michael O'Rourke (gambler)|Michael O'Rourke]] \n|19\u201320\n|{{Flag|United States|1877}}\n|O'Rourke, an American fugitive and [[Gambling|gambler]] who was imprisoned later escaped from jail on 18 April 1881.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2016/08/the-legend-of-johnny-behind-deuce.html|title=The Legend Of Johnny-Behind-The-Deuce|last=Correa|first=Tom|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1885\n|[[Servant Girl Annihilator]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|United States|1885}}\n|An American [[serial killer]], who became known as the \"Servant Girl Annihilator\" had killed multiple people in the city of [[Austin, Texas]],<ref name=TexasMonthly>{{cite news |last=Hollandsworth |first=Skip |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/capital-murder/ |title=Capital Murder |newspaper=Texas Monthly |date=July 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/94680/how-servant-girl-annihilator-terrorized-1880s-austin|title=How the 'Servant Girl Annihilator' Terrorized 1880s Austin|date=2017-04-25|website=www.mentalfloss.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> during the years 1884 and 1885.<ref name=TexasMonthly /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://truecrimesociety.com/2019/09/28/the-servant-girl-annihilator/|title=True Crime Society - The Servant Girl Annihilator|date=2019-09-29|website=True Crime Society|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> The 26 December 1885 issue of ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the \"murders were committed by some cunning madman, who is insane on the subject of [[Femicide|killing women]]\"<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news |title=Three Murders in One Night |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1885/12/26/103647562.pdf |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 26, 1885}}</ref>. He disappeared in 1885, and was thought to have been seen in 1888, but still was never captured.\n|-\n|1888\n|[[Jack the Ripper]]\n|unknown\n|{{flagcountry|Kingdom of England}}\n|Jack the Ripper was a [[serial killer]] whose real identity was unknown, and who was mainly active in the largely impoverished areas in and around the [[Whitechapel]] district of [[London]]. He was last seen in 1888 and no one knows what became of him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jack-the-ripper.org/jack-the-ripper-victim-number-4.htm|title=The Last Sighting of Jack the Ripper Victim Catherine Eddowes.|website=www.jack-the-ripper.org|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> \n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1888-01-01\"|1888  \n|[[Boston Corbett]]\n|56\n|{{Flag|United States|1877}}\n|Corbett, the [[Union Army]] soldier who fatally shot [[John Wilkes Booth]], later went insane and was incarcerated in a mental asylum in 1887. He escaped from the facility a year later and was never seen again, though some historians suspect he may have perished in the [[Great Hinckley Fire]] of 1 September 1894.<ref name=Herald>''Lincoln Herald'', Volume 86, Lincoln Memorial University Press., 1984, pp. 152\u2013155.</ref><ref name=Kubicek>Kubicek, Earl C, \"The Case of the Mad Hatter\", ''Lincoln Herald'', Volume 83, Lincoln Memorial University Press, 1981, pp. 708\u2013719.</ref>\n|}\n\n==1900s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n!Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1908-04-28\"|1908 \n|[[Belle Gunness]]\n|48\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1908}}}}\n|Gunness, a Norwegian-American serial killer, vanished on 28 April 1908 after a house fire (suspected arson) and withdrawing huge amounts of money from her bank accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swordandscale.com/did-belle-get-away-with-murder/|title=Did Belle Get Away with Murder?|date=2013-12-30|publisher=[[Sword and Scale]]|accessdate=2017-10-02}}</ref> Although the remains of a headless woman found after the fire were suspected to be that of Belle Gunness, this remains unverified and debated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/belle-gunness|title=Belle Gunness|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1908\n|[[Butch Cassidy|Robert Leroy Parker]] <br>([[Pseudonym|''alias'']] Butch Cassidy)\n|42\n|{{Flag|United States|1908}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |After the two outlaws escaped from jail, \"Wanted dead or alive\" posters were posted throughout the country, with rewards of as much as $30,000 for information leading to their capture or deaths.<ref name=\"Outlaw3\">{{cite web|url=http://wycarboncounty.tripod.com/outlaw3.html|title=Carbon County Outlaws: Butch Cassidy|last=Jaramillo|first=Arthur J.|date=29 July 2009|work=Wyoming: Carbon County Facts and Fiction|access-date=19 January 2019}}</ref> They were supposedly killed in a shootout with Bolivian police around 7\u20138 November, although authorities were unable to positively identify the bodies.\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[Sundance Kid|Harry Alonzo Longabaugh]]}} (''alias'' The Sundance Kid)\n|40\u201341\n|{{Flag|United States|1908}}\n|}\n\n==1910s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|1914\n|[[Peter Madden (gang leader)|Peter Madden]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1914}}}}\n|Madden, an American thief, gang leader, and labor racketeer who in June 1914 was arrested for his suspected involvement in a street mugging.<ref>[[Herbert Asbury|Asbury, Herbert]]. ''The Gangs of New York: An Informal History of the New York Underworld''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 1928. (p. 336) {{ISBN|1-56025-275-8}}</ref> On 25 June he was sent to [[The Tombs]], as he was with another mugging that he did with a man named John Ryan as they were both charged with stealing the wallet of man named a William Beard in [[Madison Square]]. On 10 September he and Ryan were handcuffed together and sent to the nearby [[New York City Criminal Court|Criminal Courts Building]]. Two deputy sheriffs then noticed that Madden was missing. Finding Ryan alone, he explained that Madden had escaped while crossing the bridge. However, authorities believed Madden had slipped away down one of the two unguarded stairways while the prisoners were marched through the second floor of the Criminal Courts Building.<ref>\"Third Escape By Peter Madden; On Bridge of Sighs He Slips Out of Handcuffs Binding Him to Another Man\". <i>The New York Times.</i> 11 Sep 1914</ref> Madden was never seen again and what became of him is unknown.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1915-01-01\"|1915\n|[[Frederick Mors]]  \n|24\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1914}}}}\n|The Austrian-American serial killer Frederick Mors (born as Carl Menarik) murdered at least eight people in an [[Independent Order of Odd Fellows|Odd Fellows]]' home, where he was employed as a porter. Mors was declared to be [[criminally insane]] and was committed to an insane asylum. In May 1915 he escaped from the asylum grounds and was never seen again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/dr-jack-kevorkian-young-orderly-yonkers-old-folks-home-caused-sensation-article-1.144018|title=Before Dr. Jack Kevorkian young orderly from a Yonkers old folks home caused a sensation|last=Bovsun|first=Mara|date=2011-05-15|website=NY Daily News|access-date=2018-04-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1916-01-01\"|1916\n|[[B\u00e9la Kiss]]  \n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Hungary|1914}}}}\n|Kiss was a Hungarian serial killer and murderer of 24 young women before he was drafted in the [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] in the [[World War I|First World War]]. Upon the discovery of his crimes he was traced to a Serbian military hospital but escaped a few days before investigators arrived. Although there were several reported sightings of the killer (notably in [[New York City|New York]] in 1932), his true fate remains a mystery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddlyhistorical.com/2015/02/14/bela-kiss/|title=Bela Kiss \u2013 The Monster of Cinkota|date=2015-02-14|website=Oddly Historical|access-date=2016-11-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029111944/http://www.oddlyhistorical.com/2015/02/14/bela-kiss/|archivedate=29 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==1920s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n!Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1922-01-01\"| 1922  \n|[[Edward F. Sands]] \n|27\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1922}}}}\n|Sands was a suspect in the murder of [[Hollywood]] director [[William Desmond Taylor]] on 1 February 1922, disappeared shortly after that, and was never seen again.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Badly Wanted |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,751984,00.html |quote=Edward F. Sands, 34, 5 ft 5 in., for the murder of William Desmond Taylor, cinema director, whose butler he was. Questioned in this case were Cinemactresses Mabel Normand, last to see Taylor alive, and Mary Miles Minter whose lingerie and love letters were found in the Taylor apartment. |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= 26 August 1929|accessdate=2007-07-21 }}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1925-01-01\"|1925\n|[[Dave Brown (baseball)|David Brown]]\n|29\u201330\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1925}}}}\n|Brown, a left-handed [[pitcher]] in [[Negro league baseball]], disappeared in 1925<ref>Riley, p. 118.</ref> before he could be questioned about a man's murder.<ref name=\"Riley\">{{cite book|last1=Riley|first1=James A.|title=The Biographical Encyclopedia of the Negro Baseball Leagues|date=2002|publisher=Carroll and Graf Publishers|isbn=0-7867-0959-6}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==1930s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n!Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|1937\n|[[Theodore Cole and Ralph Roe]]\n|Cole \u2013 24, Roe \u2013 31\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1937}}}}\n|Cole and Roe, both convicted bank robbers (Cole went into Alcatraz for kidnapping also) in [[Oklahoma]], had been caught during earlier, independent escape attempts from that state's [[McAlester, Oklahoma|McAlester]] [[Oklahoma State Penitentiary|Prison]]. Judged to be escape risks, they were both incarcerated in high-security [[Leavenworth Prison]], then transferred to higher-security [[Alcatraz]] in 1936.<ref name=\"Munger\">{{Cite web|url=https://seanmunger.com/2014/12/16/escape-from-alcatraz-did-cole-and-roe-make-it-off-the-rock/|title=Escape from Alcatraz: Did Cole and Roe make it off \"The Rock\"?|last=Munger|first=Sean|date=2014-12-17|website=SeanMunger.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> They escaped from Alcatraz, on 16 December 1937,<ref name=\"Munger\"/> and although officials were quick to conclude they perished in the attempt, their remains were never found and their fate remains unknown.<ref>{{Citation|title=A Gas Can and a Prayer {{!}} Sharkatraz|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=llSyFLKL6vU|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n==1940s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1940-08-08\"| 1940 \n|[[Eleanor Jarman]] \n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1940}}}}\n|In 1933, Jarman and two men robbed a clothing store in [[Chicago, Illinois]], murdering the store owner in the process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12388833/tiger_woman_is_given_term/|title=\"Tiger Woman\" Is Given Term|date=1 September 1933|publisher=Hope Star|location=Hope, Arkansas|page=1|accessdate=15 July 2017|via=newspapers.com}}</ref> Jarman was jailed and served about six years of her sentence, but escaped in 1940. She eluded police while making intermittent contact with her family and son. She is thought to have died when contact ended in the 1990s.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1944-08-08\"| 1944\n|[[Mieczys\u0142aw Kosmowski]]\n|30\u201331\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Poland}}}}\n|Kosmowski, a [[Poles|Polish]] [[Nazism|Nazi]] [[Collaboration in German-occupied Poland|collaborator]], [[Gestapo|Gestapo agent]] and [[War crime|war criminal]]<ref>[http://www.jewishgen.org/yizkor/szczuczyn/szc044.html The Shtutsin (Szczuczyn) Holocaust]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=pl&u=http://odkrywca.pl/ipn-wytropil-agenta-gestapo-ktory-wydal-na-smierc-wielu-polakow,655429.html&prev=search|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> was last seen in 1944 in [[Bydgoszcz]], when he evacuated with the [[German Army (1935\u20131945)|German army]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=pl&u=https://www.pch24.pl/niemcy-organizowali-pogrom-w-jedwabnem--przypadek-agenta-kosmowskiego-vel-krause,53876,i.html&prev=search|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> In 1955, he was accused of denouncing several Poles to the Germans and a wanted poster was issued for him in 1957, and at the request of the court after a warrant was issued, which was valid from 1957 until 2009.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1945-01-01\"| 1945\n|[[Szilveszter Matuska]]\n|52\u201353\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Hungary|1945}}}}\n|Matuska was a convicted [[Hungarians|Hungarian]] mass murderer and mechanical engineer. He had made two successful and at least two unsuccessful attempts to derail passenger trains in three European countries. His execution was commuted to life imprisonment under an extradition agreement. He escaped from jail in [[V\u00e1c]] in 1945 and his ultimate fate is unknown.\n|-\n|1945\n|[[Petar Brzica]]\n|28\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Independent State of Croatia}}}}\n|An [[Ustashe]] guard at the [[Jasenovac Concentration Camp]], Petar Brzica was involved in a \"contest\" to kill the most inmates in one night. He won the \"contest\", bragging of murdering 1,360 people, though this figure is debatable.{{cn|date=February 2020}} Brzica's post-war fate remains unknown, though reports of him living as an elderly man in [[Croatia]] surfaced in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commissiononassisteddying.co.uk/petar-brzica/|title=Petar Brzica|date=2018-02-22|website=Commission on Assisted Dying|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n|-\n|1946\n|[[Texarkana Moonlight Murders|Phantom Killer]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1946}}}}\n|Responsible for the [[Texarkana]] Moonlight Murders of 1946, this serial killer would shoot random couples at lovers' lanes and often [[Sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] the female victims. He caused a panic in the city and the [[Texas Rangers Division|Texas Rangers]] were even called in to hunt down the perpetrator. The Phantom Killer committed his last murder on 3 May 1946 before vanishing. To this date, no one has ever been charged with the murders and the killer's identity remains a mystery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/feb/07/fbi-releases-archive-texarkanas-phantom-killer-ove/|title=FBI releases archive on Texarkana's Phantom Killer; over 1,000 pages available online|date=2020-02-07|website=Arkansas Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> \n|-\n|1947\n|[[Frederick J. Tenuto]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1947}}}}\n|Tenuto also known as \"Angel of Death\" was a New York City mobster and criminal<ref name=Dolan>{{cite book|last1=Dolan|first1=Francis X.|title=Eastern State Penitentiary|date=2007|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=0738550396|page=67|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vOksh31rBSAC|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref> who escaped from the Philadelphia County Prison in a jailbreak on 10 February 1947. He would be on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives by year, 1950|FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list as number 14 for over a decade, the longest on record at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/ten-most-wanted-fugitives-faq/ten-most-wanted-1-100|title=Ten Most Wanted Fugitives 1 to 100|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref> He replaced Stephen William Davenport who was number 12, as the first replacement who was not among the original ten, but was removed on 9 March 1964, due to reports that Tenuto had been killed and secretly buried, though it is not known for sure if this is true. His ultimate fate is unknown. \n|-\n|}\n\n==1960s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"1960-01-01\"| 1960 \n|[[James Squillante]] \n|41\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1960}}}}\n|Squillante, a [[caporegime]] in the [[Gambino crime family]], disappeared after being indicted on [[extortion]] charges. He is believed to have been murdered and his body disposed of in a [[car crusher]] that was subsequently melted down in an [[open hearth furnace]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/jim-goad/2014/10/13-spooky-unexplained-disappearances/|title=13 Spooky & Unexplained Disappearances|date=2014-10-14|newspaper=Thought Catalog|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factofun.com/top-10-unusual-missing-persons-cases/|title=Top 10 Unusual Missing Persons Cases \u2013 FactoFun|website=factofun.com|access-date=2016-12-01}}</ref> No physical evidence has ever been found to substantiate this claim and no one was ever charged in connection with the disappearance.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" data-sort-value=\"1962-01-01\"|1962 \n|[[June 1962 Alcatraz escape attempt#Frank Morris|Frank Morris]] \n|35\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1962}}}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Morris and brothers Clarence and John Anglin [[June 1962 Alcatraz escape|escaped]] from [[Alcatraz|Alcatraz prison]] in the U.S. state of [[California]] and disappeared. After extensive investigation, authorities presumed that they drowned in attempting to escape from the island prison, but no bodies were ever recovered. They may have survived, and the official investigation is still open nearly 60 years after their escape. The [[U.S. Marshals|U.S. Marshal Service]] has stated that the investigation will remain open on each individual man until proof of death has been established or the date of the fugitive's 100th birthday, whichever comes first.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-11-15/news/9311150178_1_alcatraz-escaped-angel-island|title=3 May Have Escaped From Alcatraz Alive|newspaper=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[June 1962 Alcatraz escape attempt#John and Clarence Anglin|Clarence Anglin]]\n|31\n|-\n|[[June 1962 Alcatraz escape attempt#John and Clarence Anglin|John Anglin]]\n|32\n|-\n|1965\n|[[Hammersmith nude murders|Jack the Stripper]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|England|1965}}}}\n|The \"Hammersmith nude murder\" were the murders of six human females that took place in [[London]], England, in 1964 and 1965.<ref>{{cite news|title=Retro: The mystery of the Jack the Stripper murders|first=James|last=Gates|date=12 March 2012|work=[[Trinity Mirror|Get West London]]|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/lifestyle/nostalgia/retro-mystery-jack-stripper-murders-5978691|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> The victims who were all prostitutes were found dead naked in or near the [[River Thames]], leading the press to give the killer the nickname of \"Jack the Stripper\" (which is a knockoff of the English killer \"[[Jack the Ripper]]\").<ref>{{cite news|title=Crime: Mark Sanderson on the seductively seamy side of 1960S london|first=Mark|last=Sanderson|work=[[The Sunday Telegraph]]|location=London|date=17 September 2006|accessdate=4 January 2017|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A151494043/STND?sid=wikipedia|url-access=subscription |via=[[InfoTrac]]}}</ref><ref name=\"stewart\">{{cite news|title=A gruesome echo of the Suffolk horror|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=16 December 2006|page=19|first=Graham|last=Stewart|issue=68885}}</ref> Jack the Stripper has never been captured and his whereabouts remain unknown.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1965-01-01\"|1965\n|[[Charles Rogers (murder suspect)|Charles Rogers]]\n|43\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1965}}}}\n|Rogers, a reclusive unemployed [[seismology|seismologist]] in [[Houston|Houston, Texas]], has remained at large since the \"Icebox Murders\" of his parents were discovered on 23 June, leading to a warrant for his detention as a material witness. He was declared legally dead in 1975.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.onlyinyourstate.com/texas/unsolved-mysteries-tx|title=7 Disturbing Unsolved Mysteries In Texas That Will Leave You Baffled|newspaper=OnlyInYourState|language=en-US|accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatliesbeyond.boards.net/thread/2757/5-creepy-houston-murder-mysteries|title=5 Creepy Houston Murder Mysteries {{!}} What Lies Beyond|website=whatliesbeyond.boards.net|accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1969\n|[[Bible John]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Scotland|1969}}}}\n|\"Bible John\" is an unidentified [[serial killer]] who was given his nickname since he often quoted the bible and is believed to have murdered three young women between the years of 1968 and 1969 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland after which he was never seen again.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lister|first=David Brown, Sean O\u2019Neill and David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bible-john-the-sanctimonious-dancehall-killer-who-vanished-gmfgpwb7j6d|title=\u2018Bible John\u2019 \u2013 the sanctimonious dancehall killer who vanished|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> His current whereabouts are unknown, and is still being sought by the police.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1969-12-07\"|1969 \n|[[Sharon Kinne]] \n|30\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1969}}}}\n|Kinne (known as La Pistolera) was an American woman convicted of homicide in Mexico and was awaiting trial for the murder of her husband James Kinne when she [[prison escape|escaped]] [[Ixtapalapa]] prison on 7 December 1969. Despite extensive manhunts in Mexico and the United States, her whereabouts are unknown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/3792236/sharon-kinne-patricia-jones-la-pistolera-killers-story-on-ids-a-crime-to-remember-where-is-she-now/|title=Sharon Kinne, Patricia Jones: 'La Pistolera' Killer's Story On ID's 'A Crime To Remember' \u2013 Where Is She Now?|date=2016-12-13|work=The Inqisitir|access-date=2018-04-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1969\n|[[Zodiac Killer]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1969}}}}\n|The Zodiac Killer was an unidentified serial killer in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] that mainly targeted young couples at lovers' lanes in [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]]. The suspect almost always used a firearm and claimed no less than five lives. He committed his first canonical murders on 20 December 1968 and was last sighted on 11 October 1969, shortly after slaying his final confirmed victim. The killer would taunt the public and authorities through letters he sent anonymously, instead coining his name \"The Zodiac\". In them, he claimed credit for his murders and would also send [[Cryptogram|ciphers]] to newspapers, most notably, the [[San Francisco Chronicle]]. Only one of the messages has been conclusively decoded. The Zodiac continued to threaten the public throughout the 1970s before he stopped writing for a couple of years. He resurfaced for the final time in the form of his last verified letter in 1978.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zodiackiller.com/|title=Zodiac Killer - Crimes, Letters, Codes, DNA|website=www.zodiackiller.com|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==1970s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1970-01-01\"|1970\n|[[Leo Burt]]\n|22\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1970}}}}\n|Burt allegedly participated in the bombing of Sterling Hall on the campus of the [[University of Wisconsin]] on 24 August 1970, and on 2 September was indicted federally in [[Madison, Wisconsin]]. He disappeared in 1970 and has not been seen since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2010/08/05/could-1970-bombing-fugitive-be-at-henley|title=Could 1970 bombing fugitive be at Henley?|last=nurun.com|website=Welland Tribune|language=en-CA|accessdate=2017-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821214511/http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2010/08/05/could-1970-bombing-fugitive-be-at-henley|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/dt/leo-frederick-burt|title=Leo Frederick Burt|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|accessdate=2017-06-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|1971\n|[[Crawford family murder#Inquest|Elmer Crawford]]\n|40\u201341\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Australia|1971}}}}\n|The [[Crawford family murder]] was the 1970 killing of pregnant mother Therese and her three children: Kathryn, James, and Karen. The family car was located at the bottom of a cliff at [[Loch Ard Gorge]] in [[Port Campbell, Victoria]], Australia on 2 July 1970. The bodies of Therese and her children were still inside.<ref name=\"flooded\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/02/25/2171391.htm Police flooded with tips after posting murder suspect reward], [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], 25 February 2008</ref> A July 1971 coroner's inquest found that Elmer Crawford murdered his wife and three children in their Cardinal Road, [[Glenroy, Victoria|Glenroy]] home. Crawford had constructed an [[electric shock|electrocution]] device, using a {{convert|15|m|ft|adj=on}} length of electrical lead and [[Crocodile clip|alligator clips]]. He attached the alligator clips to his wife's ears while she slept and electrocuted her. He then beat his children to death, presumably using a hammer, then loaded their bodies into the family's FE [[Holden]] vehicle. He then drove them {{convert|200|km}} to Port Campbell where he connected a hose from the exhaust to the driver's side window,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Koubaridis|first1=Andrew|title=Elmer Crawford has avoided the police for more than 40 years|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/crime/elmer-crawford-has-avoided-the-police-for-more-than-40-years/news-story/93b1b24f7353c1ffa40b764aabf3c456|website=news.com.au|accessdate=5 September 2017|date=24 August 2015}}</ref> before pushing the car containing the bodies over the cliff edge in an effort to make the crime look like [[murder-suicide]].<ref name=\"whereis\">[http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/where-is-elmer-crawford/2005/06/30/1119724753989.html?from=moreStories Where is Elmer Crawford?], [[The Age]], 1 July 2005</ref> Crawford disappeared after and has not been seen since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/news/the-most-wanted-man-in-australia-irish-emigrant-still-hunted-by-police-almost-50-years-after-brutal-murders-36834552.html|title='The most wanted man in Australia' \u2013 Irish emigrant still hunted by police almost 50 years after brutal murders|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1971-01-01\"|1971\n|[[D. B. Cooper]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1971}}}}\n|Dan Cooper (also referred to as D. B. Cooper) was the name used by an unidentified man who hijacked a plane on 24 November, and parachuted from it during mid-flight with $200,000 he had extorted. No trace of him has ever been found.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citizensleuths.com/db-cooper-what-you-need-to-know.html| title=D.B. Cooper: Everything you need to know in 5 minutes|website=citizensleuths.com|language=en-gb|accessdate=2017-02-10}}</ref> Investigators now claim to have found the man who claimed to be Cooper whose name was Robert Rackstraw,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/d-b-cooper-investigators-claim-theyve-discovered-skyjackers-identity-693912/|title=D.B. Cooper: Investigators Claim They\u2019ve Discovered Skyjacker\u2019s Identity|last=McDonell-Parry|first=Amelia|last2=McDonell-Parry|first2=Amelia|date=2018-07-02|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> who died of [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]] on 9 June 2019.<ref>[https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/obituaries/story/2019-07-09/army-paratrooper-suspected-in-notorious-d-b-cooper-skyjacking-dies-in-bankers-hill-home San Diegan featured in program about notorious D.B. Cooper skyjacking case dies in Bankers Hill home]</ref> It has not been confirmed for certain if it was Rackstraw who was Cooper.\n|-\n|1972\n|[[Henri Young]]\n|61\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1972}}}}\n|Young was a convicted bank robber and murderer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alcatrazhistory.com/hyoung.htm|title=Henri Young|website=www.alcatrazhistory.com|access-date=2019-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426192750/http://www.alcatrazhistory.com/hyoung.htm|archive-date=26 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> who while serving one of a series of prison terms, attempted a 1939 escape from [[Alcatraz Federal Penitentiary]] with four other inmates. During the escape attempt two inmates were shot, and one died of his wounds. All surviving were quickly recaptured. Two, Young and [[Rufus McCain]], received sentences of solitary confinement and served them at Alcatraz for a period of three years (until autumn of 1942). He was released from Washington State Penitentiary in 1972, and then jumped [[parole]] and, according to Washington State authorities, his whereabouts are unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alcatrazhistory.com/hyoung.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426192750/http://www.alcatrazhistory.com/hyoung.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-04-26|title=Henri Young|date=2015-04-26|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|1973\n|[[Charlie Chop-off]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1973}}}}\n|\"Charlie Chop-off\" is the [[pseudonym]] given to an unidentified American [[serial killer]] who is known to have killed three children two who were black and one child who was Puerto Rican in [[Manhattan]] between 1972 and 1973. He is also known to have [[attempted murder|attempted to murder]] another child as well. A man named charged with botched an [[Child abduction|abduction]] named Erno Soto was arrested in Manhattan on 15 May 1974, and is thought to be Chop-off, but despite lack of evidence, it is unknown for sure if this is true. He did not stand trial due to have a case of acute [[Mental disorder|mental instability]].<ref>''The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'' {{ISBN|978-0-747-23731-0}} p. 321</ref> He was sent back to a [[mental institution]]. The true identity and fate of Chop-off remains unknown.\n|-\n|1973\n|[[Frank Matthews (drug trafficker)|Frank Matthews]]\n|38\u201339\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1973}}}}\n|Matthews was a major heroin and cocaine trafficker who operated throughout the eastern seaboard during the late 1960s and early 1970s. In 1973, the DEA arrested Matthews in [[Las Vegas]], but he paid bail then disappeared. Matthews allegedly took 15 to 20 million dollars with him and fled the country, leaving behind his common-law wife, their three sons, and their [[Staten Island]] mansion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.silive.com/news/2012/04/staten_island_drug_kings_vanis.html |title=Staten Island drug king's vanishing act |date=12 April 2012 |first=Tom |last=Wrobleski |newspaper=Staten Island Advance |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref> He was never seen again.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1974-11-07\"|1974\n|[[John Bingham, 7th Earl of Lucan|Lord Lucan]]\n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United Kingdom|1974}}}}\n|Lucan went missing after the murder in London of his children's nanny, Sandra Rivett, for which he was the prime suspect.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ranson|Strange|1994|pp=157\u2013159}}</ref> It was speculated that the murder in the family home in [[Belgravia]] was a case of mistaken identity, and that Lucan had intended to kill his wife. He was declared legally deceased in 2016, thereby making his son George the [[George Bingham, 8th Earl of Lucan|8th Earl of Lucan]].\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1976-01-01\"|1976\n|[[Frank Blackhorse]]\n|28\u201329\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1976}}}}\n|Blackhorse, (believed to be born Francis or Frank DeLuca, and also known under several aliases besides Blackhorse) was a member of the [[American Indian Movement]] and was charged with shooting an FBI officer during the [[Wounded Knee incident]] in 1973, although no conclusive evidence was presented.  Blackhorse is believed to have disappeared in 1976.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Perversions of Justice: Indigenous Peoples and Anglo-American Law|p=[https://archive.org/details/perversionsofjus00chur/page/297 297]|last=Churchill|first=Ward|year=2003|publisher=City Lights Books|isbn=978-0-872-86411-5|location=San Francisco, California|url=https://archive.org/details/perversionsofjus00chur/page/297}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1976-03-18\"|1976\n|[[Bradford Bishop]]\n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1976}}}}\n|Bishop disappeared 2 March from [[Bethesda, Maryland]], shortly after allegedly murdering his wife, mother, and children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/01/AR2006030102328_2.html|title=Where Is Brad Bishop?|date=2006-03-02|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-07-25|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> On 18 March, the Bishop family car was found abandoned at an isolated campground in [[Elkmont, Tennessee]].<ref>\"Missing Bishop Car Found in Smokies\", Donald Baker, ''Washington Post'', 19 March 1976.</ref> On 10 April 2014, the FBI named him the 502nd fugitive to be placed on its List of 10 Most Wanted Fugitives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/2014/april/william-bradford-bishop-added-to-fbi-top-ten-list/william-bradford-bishop-added-to-fbi-top-ten-list/|title=FBI \u2013 William Bradford Bishop Added to FBI Top Ten List|date=2014-04-16|access-date=2017-07-25|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416143734/http://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/2014/april/william-bradford-bishop-added-to-fbi-top-ten-list/william-bradford-bishop-added-to-fbi-top-ten-list/|archivedate=16 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1979-05-21\"|1979\n|[[William Morales]]\n|29\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1979}}}}\n|American bomb maker for [[Fuerzas Armadas de Liberaci\u00f3n Nacional Puertorrique\u00f1a]] who was convicted in February 1979 for possession of explosives, and possession and transportation of explosives and a shotgun. He escaped from [[Bellevue Hospital]] in May 1979 and subsequently fled to Mexico, where he was held by the authorities before he emigrated to Cuba in 1988. He is currently on the [[FBI Most Wanted Terrorists|FBI Most Wanted domestic terrorists]] list with a reward of $100,000 for information leading to his arrest.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/dt/william-guillermo-morales/view|title=FBI \u2013 William 'Guillermo' Morales|publisher=FBI.gov|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|1979\n|[[Assata Shakur]]\n|32\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1979}}}}\n|Shakur, born \"JoAnne Deborah Byron\" and sometimes known by her married name \"JoAnne Deborah Chesimard\" is a former member of the [[Black Liberation Army]] who was convicted of the first degree murder of State Trooper Werner Foerster during a shootout on the New Jersey Turnpike in 1973. While serving a life sentence, she escaped from prison in 1979 and reappeared in Cuba in 1984 where she was granted political asylum. The FBI added her to its [[FBI Most Wanted Terrorists|list of most-wanted terrorists]] as Joanne Deborah Chesimard,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/wanted_terrorists/joanne-deborah-chesimard|title=Joanne Deborah Chesimard|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation}}</ref> and is offering $2,000,000 for her capture.\n|-\n|}\n\n==1980s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n\u2212\t\n|-\n|1983\n|[[V\u00edctor Manuel Gerena]]\n|25\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1983}}}}\n|American [[fugitive]] wanted by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ranker.com/list/criminals-on-america-s-most-wanted-not-caught/philgibbons|title=Criminals On America's Most Wanted Who Were Never Caught|website=Ranker|language=en|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref> for the September 1983 [[White Eagle (robbery)|White Eagle armed robbery]]. The $7 million in cash that was stolen was the largest cash robbery in U.S. history at that time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/puertorico/avelino-captured.htm |title=Wells Fargo Fugitive Captured: Suspect Allegedly Transported Cash From $7 Million Robbery To Mexico |last=Mahony |first=Edmund H. |publisher=The Hartford Courant |date=2008-02-08 |accessdate=2009-11-30}}</ref> He was a known member of the ''[[Boricua Popular Army|Los Macheteros]]'' gang. On 14 May 1984, Gerena became the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 1980s|386th fugitive to be placed]] on the FBI's [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Top Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list.\n|-\n|1984\n|[[Sukumara Kurup]]\t\n|38\t\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|India|1984}}}}\n|Most wanted criminal in [[Kerala]], India, sought in connection to the infamous Chacko murder case. On 21 January 1984, Kurup, under the pretense of offering a lift to Chacko, spiked his drink and subsequently strangled him and burnt his body. Kurup allegedly committed the crime with his two accomplices to fake his own death and claim the insurance proceeds. Upon realizing that the police were on to him, he fled and has been in hiding since January 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/140119/news-current-affairs/article/30-years-%E2%80%98chacko-murder%E2%80%99-still-alive-files|title=30 years on, \u2018Chacko murder\u2019 still alive in files|last=Bose|first=Abhish K|date=2014-01-19|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1984-01-01\"|1984\n|[[Edward L. Montoro]] \n|52\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1984}}}}\n|Motion picture producer/distributor Edward L. Montoro disappeared in 1984 after taking more than $1 million from his own company, [[Film Ventures International]]. It was speculated that he fled to Mexico.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/08/from-grizzly-to-great-white-the-death-of-film-vent.html|title=From Grizzly to Great White: The Death of Film Ventures International|work=pastemagazine.com|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1985\n|[[Christopher Dale Flannery]]\n|46\u201347\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Australia|1985}}}}\n|Flannery, nicknamed \"Mr. Rent-a-Kill\" is alleged to have been an [[Australians|Australian]] [[contract killing|contract killer]].  He left school at the age of fourteen and received his first criminal conviction later that year. At 17, he was convicted of [[housebreaking]], [[auto theft]], assault against police, carrying firearms and [[rape]], and was sentenced to seven years imprisonment.<ref name=Goodsir>{{cite book|author1=Goodsir, D.|title=Line of Fire: The inside story of the controversial shooting of undercover policeman Michael Drury|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=Crows Nest|year=1995|isbn=978-1-86448-002-3}}</ref> On 23 April 1985, Flannery was allegedly sent to murder Tony \"Spaghetti\" Eustace. Eustace was found by two schoolchildren who were returning home from sports training at about 7 pm. He had been shot six times in the back outside the Airport Hilton in North Arncliffe and was lying beside his gold Mercedes, bleeding profusely and then died. After this Flannery disappeared and police stated that they believed Flannery to have been responsible for up to a dozen murders.<ref name=\"Sunday: Ganglands Part 2 transcript\">{{Cite web |url=http://sunday.ninemsn.com.au/sunday/cover_stories/transcript_1490.asp |title=Sunday: Ganglands Part 2 transcript |access-date=26 February 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827012231/http://www.sunday.ninemsn.com.au/sunday/cover_stories/transcript_1490.asp |archive-date=27 August 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is presumed to be dead.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1985-06-01\"|1985\n|[[Elizabeth Ann Duke]]\n|44\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1985}}}}\n|Duke is an [[Americans|American]] fugitive and former teacher best known for her involvement with radical left-wing political organizations and subsequent flight from [[prosecution]]. She remains wanted by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] on charges related to the bombings carried out by the [[May 19th Communist Organization]] in the early 1980s. Duke disappeared in October 1985 and her fate remains unknown. The FBI is offering a reward of up to $50,000 for information leading directly to the arrest and conviction of Duke.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://breaking911.com/50k-reward-offered-fbi-wanted-fugitive-domestic-terrorist-elizabeth-ann-duke/|title=$50K Reward Offered For FBI Most Wanted Fugitive Domestic Terrorist Elizabeth Ann Duke|last=|date=2018-01-11|website=Breaking911|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1989-04-12\"|1989\n|[[Arthur Lee Washington Jr.]] \n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1989}}}}\n|Washington, a member of the [[Black Liberation Army]], disappeared in 1989 after being involved in a shootout with a New Jersey state trooper. He was on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list from 1989 to 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/01/07/nyregion/briefing-law-enforcement-less-wanted.html|title=Briefing: Law Enforcement; Less Wanted|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-01|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==1990s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1991-09-01\"|1991\n|[[Glen Stewart Godwin]]\n|33\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1991}}}}\n|Godwin was sentenced to 26 years to life in prison for the 1980 murder and robbery of drug dealer Kim LeValley in [[Palm Springs, California]].<ref>{{cite news |first= R. Robin |last=McDonald |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADA2BFC472C94D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Most Wanted |publisher=The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]] |date=27 October 1996 |format=Fee required |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> Godwin escaped from [[Folsom State Prison]] in [[Folsom, California|Folsom]], California, in 1987.<ref name=\"Foxnews\">{{cite news |first=Melissa |last=Underwood |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,326034,00.html |title=Glen Stewart Godwin Wanted for Murder, Escape From Prison |publisher=[[Fox News]] |location=[[New York City]] |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> He fled to Mexico, where he was arrested for drug trafficking and sentenced to seven years and six months in prison in 1991.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SB&p_theme=sb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB0D9D1C971B81E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=One Fugitive from Folsom Still Loose|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]] |location=[[Sacramento, California]] |date=3 April 1992 |format=Fee required |accessdate=31 March 2019 }}</ref> While American authorities were working on Godwin's [[extradition]] proceedings, one of his fellow inmates at Puente Grande prison who was a member of a [[Mexican drug cartel]] died, and Godwin's extradition was delayed as it was suspected that he killed the inmate. Godwin was last seen in September 1991 before he escaped from Puente Grande prison. He was on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list from 1996 to 2016.<ref>Don Babwin. [http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/32018931/fbi-adds-la-and-chicago-area-suspects-to-10-most-wanted-list FBI adds LA and Chicago area suspects to 10 Most Wanted list] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521143311/http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/32018931/fbi-adds-la-and-chicago-area-suspects-to-10-most-wanted-list |date=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1993-01-01\"|1993\n|[[Aarni Neuvonen]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Estonia|1993}}}}\n|Neuvonen, real name Vadim Rozenberg, also known under the aliases of Aarni Rozenberg and Vadim Petrov, is the largest ever perpetrator of [[employment fraud]] in [[Estonia]] who disappeared after 9 February 1993. He is known for having collected money with promise of overseas jobs from thousands of people and disappearing after having caused over (estimated) 10 million of [[Estonian kroon|EEK]] of damages in 1993,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=et&u=http://www.efis.ee/et/filmiliigid/film/id/10981/huvitavat-lugemist&prev=search|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> and has not been seen since.\n|-\n|1993\n|[[Chhota Shakeel]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|India|1993}}}}\n|Shakeel whose birth name was Mohammed Shakeel Babu Miyan Shaikh, is an Indian crime boss and also a high-ranking leader of the [[D-Company]] (Dawood Company), a criminal group who are based in South Asia. He became one of the most-wanted men in India and United States after his alleged participation in the [[1993 Bombay bombings]] on 12 March. He is rumored to be dead<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.opednews.com/articles/Mumbai-s-Dreaded-Underworl-by-Rob-Williamson-Gangsters_Secret-Empire_Secret-Ops-181212-603.html|title=Mumbai's Dreaded Underworld Secret|last=Williamson|first=Rob|date=12 December 2018|work=OpEdNews|access-date=}}</ref> and there are multiple ideas on how he died, but it is not known for sure if he is in fact really dead.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=1993|1993\n|[[Matteo Messina Denaro]]\n|57\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|1984}}}}\n|Messina Denaro, nicknamed 'U siccu (\"the skinny man\"), due to his physical constitution, or even Diabolik, is considered one of the most wanted and dangerous fugitives in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/2010/05/13/bin-laden-joaquin-guzman-dawood-ibrahim-business-world-most-wanted_slide_6.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731140000/http://www.forbes.com/2010/05/13/bin-laden-joaquin-guzman-dawood-ibrahim-business-world-most-wanted_slide_6.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-31|title=In Pictures: The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives \u2013 Matteo Messina De\u2026|date=2012-07-31|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> Undisputed leader and representative of the Trapani mafia, he is currently the richest and most powerful boss of all [[Cosa Nostra]].\n|-\n|1993\n|[[Roberto Solis]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1993}}}}\n|Solis is an [[Armored car (valuables)|armored car]] robber, [[Poetry|poet]], and was imprisoned 17 years for the murder of a security guard during a robbery in 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Sep-16-Fri-2005/news/27217154.html|title=News: Heist suspect turns self in|work=reviewjournal.com|accessdate=12 January 2011}}</ref> He was given parole in 1992,<ref name=\"AMW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amw.com/fugitives/case.cfm?id=26378|title=Roberto Solis|work=America's Most Wanted|accessdate=12 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225014902/http://www.amw.com/fugitives/case.cfm?id=26378|archivedate=25 December 2010}}</ref> but was involved with theft in October 1993 after which he disappeared and is currently wanted by the police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/16/us/fugitive-in-armored-car-theft-gives-up-after-12-years.html|title=Fugitive in Armored Car Theft Gives Up After 12 Years|last=Archibold|first=Randal C.|date=2005-09-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1993-11-10\"|1993\n|[[Adam Emery]]\n|31\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1993}}}}\n|Emery disappeared from the [[Claiborne Pell Newport Bridge]] with his wife after being convicted of second-degree murder in [[Rhode Island]] on 10 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/when-adam-lost-the-tail-light-of-his-t-bird-things-got-bad-then-they-got-worse-a-truth-is-stranger-1396426.html|title=When Adam lost the tail-light of his T-Bird, things got bad. Then they Got Worse a Truth is Stranger|newspaper=independent.co.uk|last=Botsford|first=Keith|date=26 February 1994}}</ref> He was released on bail the same day of his conviction, and the couple's car was found abandoned on the bridge. His wife's remains were found in 1994 in [[Narragansett Bay]], and Emery was [[Declared death in absentia|declared dead ''in absentia'']] in 2004. However, Emery is still currently on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|FBI's most wanted list]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1994/09/25/a-leap-of-fate/00f97615-edb2-48e4-add4-ecff04bd4170/|title=A Leap of Fate|publisher=washingtonpost.com|last=Powers|first=William F.|date=26 February 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://turnto10.com/archive/presumed-dead-emery-back-on-fbi-list|title=Presumed dead, Emery back on FBI list|publisher=turnto10.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1993-03-18\"|1993\n|[[Antonio Angl\u00e9s]]\n|27\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Spain|1993}}}}\n|Angl\u00e9s is a Spanish criminal sought in connection with the [[Alc\u00e0sser Girls]] crime that took place in [[Valencia]] during the night of 13 November 1992. Angl\u00e9s friend, Miquel Ricart, was convicted of raping and killing the three girls that night, and it was alleged that Angl\u00e9s was also present and participated. In 1993, Angl\u00e9s ran away from Spain. Some people saw him in various places such as Ireland, the United States, and his birth country, Brazil, but those alleged sightings have been proved wrong. Angl\u00e9s' whereabouts remain a mystery.\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Dawood Ibrahim]]\n|38\u201339\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|India|1994}}}}\n|Kaskar is a [[Organised crime in India#Mumbai underworld|Mumbai underworld]] criminal mobster and drug dealer most wanted by India with a reward of $25 million<ref name=\"reward\">{{cite web|title=3 students forced to end their 'Dawood hunt' after money runs out|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/3-students-forced-to-end-their-dawood-hunt-after-money-runs-out-1373291.html/amp|website=[[First Post]]|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> over his head, and has been wanted since 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://keralakaumudi.com/en/news/news.php?id=111752&u=new-evidence-proves-dawood-ibrahim-hiding-in-pakistans-karachi-111752|title=New evidence proves Dawood Ibrahim hiding in Pakistan's Karachi|last=Daily|first=Keralakaumudi|website=Keralakaumudi Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> He is currently believed to be residing in Pakistan, according to the Indian government, and heads the Indian [[organised crime]] syndicate [[D-Company]] which he founded in [[Mumbai]] in the 1970s.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article3093209.ece The name on the Mumbai street over terror attacks is Dawood Ibrahim.] ''The Times''. 13 July 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/dawood-ibrahim-kaskar/|newspaper=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21583285-growth-slows-and-reforms-falter-economic-activity-shifting-out-india-made-outside|title=Made outside India|website=The Economist|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/24/opinion/fix-the-link-to-pakistan-bond-with-india.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Fix the Link to Pakistan, Bond With India|last=Kugelman|first=Michael|date=2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/dec/02/mumbai-most-wanted|title=India names two most-wanted fugitives after Mumbai attacks|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=2008-12-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Dawood is wanted on the charges of [[murder]], [[extortion]], [[targeted killing]], [[drug trafficking]], [[terrorism]] and various other cases. He was designated as a global terrorist in 2003 by India and the United States with a reward of US$25 million for his capture for his believed role in the [[1993 Bombay bombings]]. In 2011, he was named number three on The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] and [[Forbes]].<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2011/06/14/most-wanted-fugitives_slide_4.html \"Dawood 4th 'most wanted' criminal on Forbes list\"]. ''The Times of India''. (29 April 2008). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n|-\n|1997\n|[[Attilio Cubeddu]]\n|52\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|1997}}}}\n|Cubeddu, a criminal from [[Sardinia]] who was a member of ''[[Anonima sarda]]'', a term used for [[Sardinian banditry|bandits]] engaged in various kinds of crime in the island, in particular kidnapping, from the 1960s onward.<ref name=blood1>Antonelli & Nuzzi, ''Blood Ties''</ref> Since 1997, he is on the \"[[List of most wanted fugitives in Italy]]\" of the ministry of the Interior, since he disappeared after he left the prison of ''[[Badu 'e Carros]]'' in [[Nuoro]], where he was detained for murder, serious injury and kidnapping. In 1998 investigations were extended internationally for his extradition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/app_notizia_17181.html |title=Ministero Dell'Interno \u2013 Approfondimento |publisher=Interno.it |date=1998-03-18 |accessdate=2010-07-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|1998\n|[[Ismael \"El Mayo\" Zambada|Ismael Zambada Garcia]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Mexico|1998}}}}\n|Garcia is [[Mexicans|Mexican]] suspected [[drug lord]] and fugitive<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foxsanantonio.com/news/local/deas-most-wanted-ismael-garcia|title=DEA's Most Wanted: Ismael Garcia|last=Nine|first=Yami Virgin, Fox News at|date=2018-09-18|website=KABB|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> who has been wanted since 1998.He was a farmer, but later became a drug lord  when began his criminal career by smuggling small amounts of drugs. Zambada has been featured on ''America's Most Wanted'',<ref>[http://www.amw.com/fugitives/brief.cfm?id=27173 America's Most Wanted] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608003656/http://www.amw.com/fugitives/brief.cfm?id=27173 |date=8 June 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Weissert |first=Will |title=Portrait Of A Mexican Drug Lord |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/10/24/world/main579960.shtml |accessdate=4 October 2012 |newspaper=[[CBS News]] |date=11 February 2009 |agency=[[CBS Interactive]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021164618/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/10/24/world/main579960.shtml |archivedate=21 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and there is a US $5 million for information leading for his capture offered by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] for his capture.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1998-03-09\"|1998 \n|[[Gilbert Wynter]]\n|37\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United Kingdom|1998}}}}\n|Wynter, a jeweler and enforcer for the Adams crime family, disappeared in London on 9 March 1998. His disappearance is believed to be related to the murder of Saul Nahome in December that year; both men were involved in a drug deal where \u00a3800,000 went missing.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hardiman |first=David |author-link=David Hardiman |title=New bid to find missing Tottenham man Gilbert Wynter |url=http://www.thetottenhamindependent.co.uk/news/9042416.New_bid_to_find_missing_Tottenham_man/ |date=23 May 2011 |access-date=8 December 2017 |newspaper=The Tottenham Independent |location=UK}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1998-09-11\"|1998 \n|[[John Ruffo]]\n|43\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1998}}}}\n|Ruffo is an American former [[business executive]], [[White-collar crime|white-collar criminal]] and [[confidence trick|confidence man]], who in 1998 was convicted in a scheme to defraud many US and foreign banking institutions of over 350 million dollars. The swindle is considered one of the most significant cases of [[bank fraud]] in US history.<ref name=\"WANTED - John Ruffo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usmarshals.gov/investigations/most_wanted/ruffo/ruffo15.htm|title=Wanted \u2013 John Ruffo|work=usmarshals.gov}}</ref> He disappeared on 9 November 1998 has been a [[fugitive]] from justice ever since, and is on the [[U.S. Marshals 15 Most Wanted Fugitives]] list.\n|-\n|1998\n|[[Pedro L\u00f3pez (serial killer)|Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez]]\n|53\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Colombia|1998}}\n|Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez is a serial killer who was active in the nations of Colombia, [[Ecuador]] and [[Peru]]. Known as the \"Monster of the Andes\", L\u00f3pez claimed to have raped and murdered over 300 young girls starting with his first victim in 1969. He mainly targeted girls who were 12 years old and came from impoverished families. In 1980, Pedro L\u00f3pez was arrested by Ecuadorian police after an attempted abduction, where he proceeded to confess to the murders of 103 girls. The authorities did not believe him and convicted him of only three murders, for which he was sentenced to 16 years imprisonment. After serving 14 years behind bars, Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez was declared \"insane\" and committed to a mental hospital in Colombia, where he spent the next year. In 1998, L\u00f3pez was found by officials to be \"legally sane\", so he was released from custody. His whereabouts are currently a mystery, but the \"Monster of the Andes\" is still wanted in connection to a 2002 cold case in Peru.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/pedro-alonso-lopez|title=Pedro Alonzo Lopez|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==2000s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age <small>(at disappearance)</small>\n!Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2001-01-01\"|2001\n|[[John Paul Sr. (racing driver)|John Paul]]\n|62\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Paul, an American [[racecar]] driver, who was last seen in Thailand,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.vice.com/nl/article/kzy889/rubber-wiet-en-tassen-met-geld-de-verdwijning-van-een-nederlandse-autocoureur|title=Rubber, wiet en tassen met geld: de verdwijning van een Nederlandse autocoureur|date=2018-04-05|work=Sports|access-date=2018-09-05|language=nl}}</ref> disappeared on his boat in 2001 while being sought for questioning by officials regarding the disappearance of his ex-girlfriend, and has not been seen since.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://autoweek.com/article/other-motorsports/special-report-part-two-racers-who-have-run-afoul-law|title=Special report, part two: Racers who have run afoul of the law|work=Autoweek|accessdate=2017-07-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|[[Giovanni Motisi]]\n|48\n|{{Flag|Italy}}\n|Motisi, also known as''<nowiki/>'' ''<nowiki/>'U Pacchiuni'' ({{langnf||Sicilian|\"The Fatman\"}}), is a member of [[the Mafia]] in [[Sicily]] from the Altarello neighborhood in [[Palermo]]. He has been on the [[List of most wanted fugitives in Italy|most wanted list]] of the Italian ministry of the Interior since 1998.<ref name=wanted>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/app_notizia_18280.html Most wanted list of the Italian ministry of the Interior] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206174614/http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/app_notizia_18280.html |date=6 February 2009 }}</ref> In March 2001, he escaped an attempt to arrest him.<ref name=rep240301>{{in lang|it}} [http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/03/24/sfugge-alla-cattura-il-latitante-motisi.html Sfugge alla cattura il latitante Motisi], La Repubblica, 24 March 2001</ref> In 2002 he was replaced as the [[capo mandamento]] of the Pagliarelli neighborhood by [[Antonio Rotolo]] when the latter left prison, because as a fugitive he did not manage the Mafia family sufficiently, and is currently wanted by the government.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2001-04-10\"|2001\n|[[Robert William Fisher]]\n|40\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Fisher disappeared after 10 April, after his house in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] blew up and caught fire. His family was found dead in the home and he is believed to be the person who murdered them and rigged the natural gas explosion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/ariz-fugitive-alive-15-years-vanishing-article-1.2593996|title=Ariz. fugitive may still be alive 15 years after vanishing|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=2017-06-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fbi.gov/pressrel02/fisher.htm|title=Federal Bureau of Investigation \u2013 Press Release|date=2010-04-11|accessdate=2017-06-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411084825/http://www.fbi.gov/pressrel/pressrel02/fisher.htm|archivedate=11 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2001-10-30\"|2001\n|[[Zeferino Pe\u00f1a Cu\u00e9llar]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|Mexico}}\n|Pe\u00f1a Cu\u00e9llar is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] fugitive who disappeared on 30 October 2001, after 14 gunmen dressed in military uniforms stormed an estate in the Hacienda Santa Luc\u00eda neighborhood in [[Monterrey]] in an attempt to kill him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnorte.com/|title=El Norte {{!}} Portada|website=www.elnorte.com|language=es|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> After several of his accomplices were arrested and/or killed, he disappeared from public view. Investigators suspect he may have retired from the Gulf Cartel, fleeing Mexico and hiding in Brazil, Canada, or Cuba with the fortune he made during his tenure.\n|-\n|2002\n|[[Renato Cinquegranella]]\n|52\u201353\n|{{Flag|Italy}}\n|[[Renato Cinquegranella]] is an [[Italians|Italian]] criminal and a member of the [[Camorra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stylo24.it/renato-cinquegranella-latitanti-pericolosi/|title=Renato Cinquegranella, il boss della camorra tra i 5 latitanti pi\u00f9 pericolosi d'Italia|last=Redazione|date=2019-11-07|website=Stylo24 \u2013 Giornale d'inchiesta|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> Cinquegranella is on the \"[[List of most wanted fugitives in Italy]]\" of the ministry of the Interior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilriformista.it/chi-e-renato-cinquegranella-il-latitante-che-aiuto-le-brigate-rosse-660/|title=Chi \u00e8 Renato Cinquegranella il latitante che aiut\u00f2 le Brigate Rosse \u2022 Il Riformista|date=2019-10-17|website=Il Riformista|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> Since 2002 Cinquegranella is wanted for mafia-type criminal association, murder, illegal possession of weapons and extortion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/cronache/caccia-ai-mafiosi-ecco-chi-sono-i-super-latitanti-ricercati-1780843.html|title=Caccia ai mafiosi: ecco chi sono i super latitanti ricercati dal Viminale|last=Chifari|first=Roberto|website=ilGiornale.it|language=it|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|2002\n|[[Mickey Green]]\n|71\u201372\n|{{Flag|United Kingdom}}\n|Green is an [[English people|English]] [[gangster]] and [[drug lord]] who has also held [[Ireland|Irish]] nationality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/pimpernel-who-chose-drugs-trade-6305077.html|title='Pimpernel' who chose drugs trade|date=2001-12-18|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> A convicted armed robber, he has allegedly been one of Britain's leading drug dealers for many years<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/cab-to-sell-off-wanted-drug-dealer-s-two-irish-properties-1.1088759|title=CAB to sell off wanted drug-dealer's two Irish properties|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> and is said to be worth at least \u00a375 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/3715205.stm|title=Underworld rich list|date=2004-05-16|access-date=2019-10-14|language=en-GB}}</ref> As of 2002, he is wanted by authorities in Ireland as they suspect he tampered with a jury at a prior inquest and his assets in the Republic of Ireland were seized by the Irish [[Criminal Assets Bureau]]. As of November 2007, he is understood to be living in and around the [[Marbella]] area,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theolivepress.es/spain-news/2011/06/08/britains-minted-mobsters-in-spain/|title=Britain's minted mobsters in Spain|last=Williams|first=Wendy|date=2011-06-08|website=Olive Press News Spain|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> but has not yet been captured.\n|-\n|2002\n|[[Achemez Gochiyayev]]\n|31\u201332\n|{{Flag|Russia}}\n|Gochiyayev, a Russian from [[Karachayevsk]] who is believed to be behind of the [[Russian apartment bombings]], terrorist actions that took place in 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/moscow-bombings-mikhail-trepashkin-and-putin|title=None Dare Call It a Conspiracy|last=Anderson|first=Scott|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> that killed 293 people and led Russia into the [[Second Chechen War]].<ref name=\"FSB\">[http://www.fsb.ru/search/criminal/gochi.html Gochiyayev's wanted page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318205506/http://www.fsb.ru/search/criminal/gochi.html |date=March 18, 2005 }} on [[FSB (Russia)|FSB]] web site.</ref> He is a wanted fugitive in Russia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090911100056/http://www.interpol.int/public/Data/Wanted/Notices/Data/1999/79/1999_37979.asp Interpol link]</ref> After 5 March 2002 according to news reports he is said to have fled to Georgia and later probably to Turkey, after he was last seen in 2002. His current whereabouts are unknown.\n|-\n|2003\n|[[Jorge L\u00f3pez P\u00e9rez]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|Mexico}}\n|P\u00e9rez, who is nicknamed \"El Chuta\", is a Mexican suspected drug lord and high-ranking member of [[Los Zetas]], a criminal group based in [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2019/12/el-chuta-paratrooper-who-became-zetas.html|title='El Chuta', the paratrooper who became a Zetas founder|last=Borderland Beat Reporter Chivis|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> P\u00e9rez an unspecified [[Bounty (reward)|bounty]] placed on him on 18 June 2003,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thedailyusnews.com/el-chuta-the-paratrooper-who-became-a-zetas-founder/|title='El Chuta', the paratrooper who became a Zetas founder|date=2019-12-11|website=Daily US News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> and had not been seen since then.\n|-\n|2004\n|[[Masood Azhar]]\n|45\n|{{Flag|Pakistan}}\n|Azhar is the founder and leader of the [[Pakistan]]-based terrorist organisation [[Jaish-e-Mohammed]], active mainly in the Pakistani-administered portion of the state of [[Jammu and Kashmir]],<ref>\n{{cite news |title=The astonishing rise of Jaish-e-Mohammed: It's bad news for Kashmir, India and Pakistan |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/jaish-e-mohammad-and-its-phenomenal-rise-its-bad-news-for-india-kashmir-and-pakistan-2582192.html |accessdate=17 January 2016 |agency=FirstPost |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116124623/http://www.firstpost.com/world/jaish-e-mohammad-and-its-phenomenal-rise-its-bad-news-for-india-kashmir-and-pakistan-2582192.html |archive-date=2016-01-16 |url-status=live}}\n</ref> who was arrested and detained for one year in December 2001,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/masood-azhar-global-terrorist-and-implications-pakistan|title=Masood Azhar \u2013 a global terrorist \u2013 and the implications for Pakistan|website=www.lowyinstitute.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> and reappeared on 26 January 2014 after being in seclusion, but was not seen after that, but was said to be behind masterminded attacks. On 1 May 2019, Masood Azhar was listed as an international terrorist by [[United Nations Security Council]],<ref name=\"UNSC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/securitycouncil/content/mohammad-masood-azhar-alvi|title=Mohammad Masood Azhar Alvi|date=1 May 2019|work=United Nations Security Council|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> and is currently wanted by the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/masood-azhar-not-in-pakistan-jail-but-at-jaish-e-mohammed-headquarters-sources-2097897|title=Masood Azhar Not In Pak Jail But At Sprawling Jaish Headquarters: Sources|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2005-06-01\"|2005\n|[[Alexis Flores]]\n|29\u201330\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Flores, a [[Hondurans|Honduran]] fugitive wanted for the kidnapping, rape and murder of five-year-old Iriana DeJesus in [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], was last seen when he was incarcerated for 60 days and deported to [[Honduras]] after his release in June 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwww2.fbi.gov/page2/june07/wanted060207.htm|title=Federal Bureau of Investigation \u2013 Press Room \u2013 Snapshot of Recent Investigations|website=www2.fbi.gov|accessdate=2017-08-21}}</ref> Flores was added to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]'s [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Top Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on 2 June 2007.<ref name=\"pressrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.fbi.gov/page2/june07/wanted060207.htm|title=New Top Ten Fugitive: Suspect in 2000 Philadelphia Murder|date=2 June 2007|accessdate=6 November 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2005-11-01\"|2005\n|[[Ye Zheyun]]\n|40\n|{{Flag|China}}\n|Zheyun, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] businessman who was accused of being involved in a [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Association football|football]] [[Political corruption|corruption]] and [[Gambling|betting]] [[List of sporting scandals|scandals]], was last seen in early November 2005 and hasn't been seen since.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expatica.com/be/news/Belgian-soccer-match-fixing-scandal-widens_133915.htm|title=Belgian soccer match-fixing scandal widens|accessdate=2017-09-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2006-01-01\"|2006\n|[[Fawzi Mutlaq al-Rawi]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|Iraq}}\n|Mutlaq al-Rawi, the leader of the Syrian led [[Ba'athism|Ba'athist]] movement in [[Iraq]], was added to the Iraq Most Wanted List in 2006<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iraq-releases-most-wanted-list/|title=Iraq Releases Most-Wanted List|accessdate=2017-09-16|language=en}}</ref> and has not been seen since.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2006-01-01\"|2006\n|[[Mohammed Younis al-Ahmed]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|Iraq}}\n|Younis al-Ahmed is a former senior member of the [[Ba'ath Party]] in Iraq. He disappeared in 2006, potentially went into hiding, and a large bounty has been placed on him.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/03/iraq/main1773952.shtm Iraq Releases Most-Wanted List] \u2013 [[CBS]], 3 July 2006</ref>\n|-\n|2006\n|[[Abdullah Al-Rimi]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|Yemen}}\n|Al-Rimi, or Abdullah Ahmed Al-Remi, has been described as an \"important al-Qaeda recruiter\",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Soufan|first1=Ali H.|title=The Black Banners: The Inside Story of 9/11 and the War Against Al-Qaeda|date=2011|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9781846145025|edition=illustrated|accessdate=28 September 2016|url={{Google books|pMneJ7KV3toC|The Black Banners|keywords=Abdullah Al-Rimi|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> and became wanted by the [[United States Department of Justice]]'s [[FBI]], and sought in connection with possible terrorist threats against the United States. On 3 February 2006, together with 22 others, 12 of them al-Qaeda members, Al-Rimi escaped from a Yemeni jail in San'a, according to a BBC report.<ref name=\"Bbc\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/4682214.stm Hunt on for Yemeni jailbreakers], ''[[BBC]]'', 4 February 2006</ref> They reportedly escaped by digging a tunnel, 140 meters, to a nearby mosque.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2006-01-07\"|2006\n|[[Iqlaque Fakir Mohammed Shaikh]]\n|29\n|{{Flag|India}}\n|Iqlaque Fakir Mohammed Shaikh is a 29-year-old of New Mangalwar Peth, [[India]]. He was sentenced to life imprisonment for committing the murder of Gudrun Corvinus, a German archaeologist of the [[Nepal Research Center]] in [[Kathmandu]]. She was a member of the Afar expedition in [[Ethiopia]] which discovered the famous skeleton called \"Lucy\". While working in the Namibian desert, she discovered animal fossils from the Miocene period. Corvinus moved to Nepal in 1984 and explored the region, specifically the Dang Deokhuri District, Dun valley, and Siwalik Hills. He was given 14-day [[parole]] to look after his sick wife, but on the last day of parole was suspected to have run off with his wife and mother. Despite numerous sightings, he is still at large and has not been taken into custody.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/lifeterm-convict-jumped-parole-in-june-not-found-yet/565124/|title=Life-term convict jumped parole in June, not found yet \u2013 Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2007-01-01\"|2007\n|[[Omid Tahvili]]\n|37\n|{{Flag|Canada}}\n|Tahvili, an [[Iranian Canadians|Iranian-Canadian]] gangster who is the kingpin of an [[organized crime]] family in [[Crime in Canada|Canada]] which is connected to various international crime organizations, escaped from jail in November 2007 dressed as a janitor. In April 2008, [[Forbes.com]], after consulting with law enforcement agencies around the world, listed him as one of the world's ten most wanted fugitives.<ref name=Forbes>{{cite magazine | url = https://www.forbes.com/business/2008/04/25/crime-binladen-guzman-biz-cz_nv_0425mostwanted.html | title = The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives | first = Nathan | last = Vardi | date = 2008-04-25 | magazine = Forbes.com | accessdate = 2008-04-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010132003/http://www.forbes.com/business/2008/04/25/crime-binladen-guzman-biz-cz_nv_0425mostwanted.html|archivedate=2008-10-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2008-01-01\"|2008\n|[[Yaser Abdel Said]]\n|unknown\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Abdel Said, an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] resident of the United States, is wanted for the murder of his two teenage daughters in [[Irving, Texas]], on 1 January. Last seen in 2008, and was added to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] [[Ten Most Wanted List]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/yaser-abdel-said|title=FBI \u2013 Yaser Abdul Said|work=[[FBI]]|accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2008-11-29\"|2008\n|[[Jason Derek Brown]]\n|38\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Brown, an American fugitive wanted for [[murder|first degree murder]] and armed robbery in [[Phoenix, Arizona]] on 29 November 2004, and on 8 December 2007 was named by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] as the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2000s|489th fugitive to be placed]] on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Ten Most Wanted list]].<ref name=\"murder\">{{cite web|first=Emily|last=Bittner|url=https://www.azcentral.com/community/ahwatukee/articles/130armoredcar30.html |title=Armored-car guard shot, killed|work=The Arizona Republic|date=30 November 2004|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref> Last confirmed sighting was in August 2008.\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Vassilis Palaiokostas]]\n|42\n|{{Flag|Greece}}\n|Palaiokostas is a [[Greeks|Greek]] [[fugitive]] who [[List of helicopter prison escapes|escaped by helicopter]] twice from the Greek high-security [[Korydallos prison]] while serving a 25-year sentence for [[kidnapping]] and [[robbery]]. He is believed to have been the mastermind of the kidnapping of Giorgos Mylonas, a Greek industrialist, as the ransom paid was traced back to him. In 2000 he was convicted for the 1995 kidnapping of Alexander Haitoglou, the CEO of [[Haitoglou Bros]], a food company in Northern Greece and sentenced to 25 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|last=\u039a\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03bc\u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2|first=\u03a6\u03ce\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|script-title=el:\u039f\u03ba\u03c4\u03ce \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03c5\u03b3\u03ba\u03bb\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf|url=http://www.makthes.gr/news/politics/19016/|newspaper=\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1|language=Greek|date=11 June 2008|access-date=16 October 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131016100515/http://www.makthes.gr/news/politics/19016/|archive-date=16 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On the afternoon of 22 February, Palaiokostas again escaped from Athens' [[Korydallos Prison]] by helicopter,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/greece/4782561/Greek-prisoner-escapes-from-maximum-security-jail-for-the-second-time.html|title=Greek prisoner escapes from maximum security jail for the second time|date=2009-02-22|access-date=2019-10-19|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has not been seen since. \n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2008-11-29\"|2009\n|[[Edgardo Leyva Escand\u00f3n]]\n|40\n|{{Flag|Mexico}}\n|Escand\u00f3n, a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] suspected criminal and high-ranking member of the [[Tijuana Cartel]], a criminal group based in Baja California. On 22 October 2009, the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] sanctioned Leyva Escand\u00f3n under the [[Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]] (sometimes referred to simply as the \"Kingpin Act\"), for his involvement in drug trafficking along with five other international criminals and one entity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Designations Pursuant to the Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designatio Act|url=http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/narco_designations_kingpin.pdf |publisher=[[United States Department of the Treasury]] |accessdate=28 May 2014 |page=9 |date=15 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514025153/http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/narco_designations_kingpin.pdf |archivedate=14 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is currently wanted in Mexico.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2008-01-01\"|2009\n|[[Jakrapob Penkair]]\n|40\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Thailand}}}}\n|[[Thai people|Thai]] politician and media personality, diplomat and politician who served as a [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bangkok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thaipoliticalprisoners.wordpress.com/tag/jakrapob-penkair/|title=Jakrapob Penkair|website=Political Prisoners in Thailand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref> the [[Spokesperson|Government Spokesperson]] of Prime Minister [[Thaksin Shinawatra]] from 2003 to 2005, and later as a [[Cabinet of Thailand|Cabinet Minister]] to the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Thailand)|Office of the Prime Minister]] from 2007 to 2008 under the premiership of [[Samak Sundaravej]]. He was forced to step down after allegations of [[L\u00e8se majest\u00e9 in Thailand|l\u00e8se majest\u00e9]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3650981/thailand-lese-majeste-article-112/|title=The Vicious Law Silencing Thai Dissent|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref> a legal weapon commonly used in Thailand to silence dissent, and has been in [[exile]] since the [[2009 Thai political unrest]], and is currently wanted.\n|-\n|}\n\n==2010s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age <small>(at disappearance)</small>\n!Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2010-03-25\"|2010\n|[[Santiago Villalba Mederos|Santiago Mederos]]\n|18\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Mederos disappeared from [[Tacoma, Washington]] after committing two murders in early 2010. He murdered 20-year-old Camille Love in a case of mistaken identity and killed 25-year-old Saul Lucas-Alfonso as he fled the scene of a robbery. He is believed to be hiding in Mexico. He was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on 25 September 2017 and remains at large.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/santiago-mederos|title=Santiago Villalba Mederos|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Dupont de Ligonn\u00e8s murders and disappearance|Xavier Dupont de Ligonn\u00e8s]]\n|50\n|{{Flag|France}}\n|Dupont de Ligonn\u00e8s disappeared from [[Nantes|Nantes, France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liberation.fr/societe/2011/04/22/xavier-de-ligonnes-un-profil-professionnel-tres-flou_730969|title=Xavier de Ligonn\u00e8s, un profil professionnel tr\u00e8s flou|work=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|access-date=2017-10-11|language=fr}}</ref> His wife, four children and two dogs had been shot and buried in the back garden of the family home. He was seen leaving a hotel in south-eastern France a few days after his family was murdered. He was the prime suspect in the killings and the subject of an [[Interpol notice|international arrest warrant]]. A man was arrested in [[Glasgow]], Scotland in October 2019 on suspicion of being Dupont de Ligonn\u00e8s, and was positively identified as such in the media, before the authorities announced that it was a case of mistaken identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191012-xavier-dupont-de-ligonn%C3%A8s-murder-mystery-and-an-8-year-manhunt|title=Xavier Dupont de Ligonn\u00e8s: Murder, mystery and an 8-year manhunt|date=12 October 2019|website=France 24|access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref> His whereabouts remain unknown.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2011-01-23\"|2011\n|[[David Durham (fugitive)|David Durham]]\n|43\n|{{Flag|United States}}\n|Durham was pulled over in a routine traffic stop by a [[Lincoln City, Oregon]], policeman on the night of 23 January and later shot the officer. He has not been seen since.<ref>Stover E. Harger III, [http://portlandtribune.com/scs/83-news/18800-the-disappearance-of-david-durham \"The disappearance of David Durham\"], ''Portland Tribune'', originally published 23 January 2012</ref><ref>Patrick Alexander, [http://www.thenewsguard.com/news/just-how-did-david-durham-escape/article_5ab59ad8-2e58-11e0-85ec-001cc4c002e0.html \"Just how did David Durham escape?\"], ''Lincoln City News Guard'', originally published 1 February 2011</ref> Law enforcement investigators have theorized that Durham attempted to swim across [[Alsea Bay]] and drowned.<ref name=al>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsguard.com/news/just-how-did-david-durham-escape/article_5ab59ad8-2e58-11e0-85ec-001cc4c002e0.html|work=The News Guard|location=Lincoln City, Oregon|title=Just how did David Durham escape?|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=7 November 2017|author=Alexander, Patrick}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2011-09-11\"|2011\n|[[Ayman al-Zawahiri]]\n|60\n|{{Flag|Egypt}}\n|Ayman al-Zawahiri has been the leader of [[al-Qaeda]] since June 2011, succeeding [[Osama bin Laden]], and is a current<ref name=bbc16jun11>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13788594|title=Ayman al-Zawahiri appointed as Al-Qaeda leader|date=16 June 2011|accessdate=28 April 2017 |via=www.bbc.co.uk |work=BBC News}}</ref> or former member and senior official of [[Islamist]] organizations which have orchestrated and carried out [[Offensive (military)|attacks]] in Asia, Africa, and the Middle East and also some in North America and Europe. Since the [[September 11 attacks]], the [[U.S. State Department]] has offered a [[United States dollar|US$]]25 million reward for [[Informant|information]] or [[Military intelligence#The intelligence process|intelligence]] leading to al-Zawahiri's capture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/CNN/Programs/people/shows/zawahiri/profile.html|title=CNN Programs \u2013 People in the News|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref> He is under [[International sanctions|worldwide sanctions]] by the [[Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee]] as a member of al-Qaeda.<ref name=refUN>[https://www.un.org/Docs/sc/committees/1267/tablelist.htm UN list of affiliates of al-Qaeda and the Taliban] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060728143814/http://www.un.org/Docs/sc/committees/1267/tablelist.htm |date=28 July 2006 }}</ref>\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Hafiz Saeed]]\n|45\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Pakistan}}}}\n|Saeed is a [[Pakistanis|Pakistani]] Islamist militant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-politics-jihad/charity-run-by-pakistani-islamist-with-10-million-bounty-launches-political-party-idUSKBN1AN1I5|title=Charity run by Pakistani Islamist with $10&nbsp;million bounty launches political party|last=Shahzad|first=Asif|date=2017-08-17|work=Reuters|language=en-US|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/70wl2wP5T?url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-politics-jihad/charity-run-by-pakistani-islamist-with-10-million-bounty-launches-political-party-idUSKBN1AN1I5|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2018-07-16|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=bbc20120403>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-17594018|title=US puts $10m bounty on Lashkar-e-Taiba's Hafiz Saeed|date=2012-04-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-07-16|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/70wYc5L1k?url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-17594018|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|language=en-GB|df=dmy-all}}</ref> who is a co-founder of [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT) and the chief of Jama'at-ud-Da'wah (JuD), operating mainly from Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1149307|title=Footprints: JuD's show of strength|author=Mahmood|first=Amjad|date=2014-12-07|website=Dawn.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209003644/http://www.dawn.com/news/1149307|archive-date=2014-12-09|url-status=live|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e.jamatdawa.org/pages.php?action=menu&id=3|title=Jamaat-ud-Dawah website-Organization|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716053203/http://e.jamatdawa.org/pages.php?action=menu&id=3|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/12/un_declares_jamaatud.php|last=Roggio|first=Bill|date=2008-12-11|website=The Long War Journal|title=UN declares Jamaat-ud-Dawa a terrorist front group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217113851/https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/12/un_declares_jamaatud.php|archive-date=2008-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2012, the United States announced a bounty of $10&nbsp;million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-puts-10-million-bounty-on-pakistan-terror-groups-leader/2012/04/03/gIQAx9NjsS_story.html|title=U.S. puts $10 million bounty on Pakistan terror group\u2019s leader|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> on Saeed for his alleged role in the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]] that killed 164 civilians. While India supported the US move, there were protests against it in Pakistan.<ref name=\"ndtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/india-welcomes-10-million-bounty-on-hafiz-saeed/228229|title=India welcomes $10&nbsp;million bounty on Hafiz Saeed|date=2012-04-03|website=NDTV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801202118/https://www.ndtv.com/video/news/news/india-welcomes-10-million-bounty-on-hafiz-saeed-228229|archive-date=2017-08-01|url-status=live|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnbcpakistan.com/Thousands-protest-against-US-bounty-on-Hafiz-Saeed-news-2027.html|title=Thousands protest 