fugitive who was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on 29 May 2019. He is wanted for allegedly shooting and killing his daughter-in-law, Tammy Palmer, on 24 September 2012 in [[Stony Point, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/eugene-palmer|title=Eugene Palmer|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=28 May 2019}}</ref> Palmer is the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2010s|523rd and most recent fugitive to be placed]] on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted Fugitives list. The FBI is offering a reward of up to $100,000 for information leading to his capture.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/new-top-ten-fugitive-eugene-palmer-052919|title=Eugene Palmer Added to Ten Most Wanted Fugitives List|date=28 May 2019|access-date=28 May 2019|work=[[FBI]] |publisher=[[U.S. government]], [[U.S. Department of Justice]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Lo Fu-chu]]\n|69\n|{{Flag|Taiwan}}\n|Fu-chu, a [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples|Taiwanese]] politician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/in-taiwan-gangsters-dont-just-bribe-politicians--they-become-them-2012-6|title=In Taiwan, Gangsters Don't Just Bribe Politicians \u2013 They Become Them|last=Nunns|first=Cain|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> was at one time a \"Celestial Alliance\" organized criminal organization. On 28 March 2013, Lo was convicted of [[stock manipulation]], money laundering, and insider trading and was sentenced to four years in jail and fined NT$6 million (US$200,000). Later he was released on a NT$10 million (US$330,000) bond, but then failed to report to police on 24 April 2013 when he was to start his sentence. He is believed to have fled to either the United States, Australia, or China,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2012-06-08/taiwanese-politics-gangsters-paradise|title=Taiwanese politics: gangsters\u2019 paradise?|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</