d]]\n|45\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Pakistan}}}}\n|Saeed is a [[Pakistanis|Pakistani]] Islamist militant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-politics-jihad/charity-run-by-pakistani-islamist-with-10-million-bounty-launches-political-party-idUSKBN1AN1I5|title=Charity run by Pakistani Islamist with $10&nbsp;million bounty launches political party|last=Shahzad|first=Asif|date=2017-08-17|work=Reuters|language=en-US|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/70wl2wP5T?url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-politics-jihad/charity-run-by-pakistani-islamist-with-10-million-bounty-launches-political-party-idUSKBN1AN1I5|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2018-07-16|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=bbc20120403>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-17594018|title=US puts $10m bounty on Lashkar-e-Taiba's Hafiz Saeed|date=2012-04-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-07-16|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/70wYc5L1k?url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-17594018|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|language=en-GB|df=dmy-all}}</ref> who is a co-founder of [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT) and the chief of Jama'at-ud-Da'wah (JuD), operating mainly from Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1149307|title=Footprints: JuD's show of strength|author=Mahmood|first=Amjad|date=2014-12-07|website=Dawn.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209003644/http://www.dawn.com/news/1149307|archive-date=2014-12-09|url-status=live|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e.jamatdawa.org/pages.php?action=menu&id=3|title=Jamaat-ud-Dawah website-Organization|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716053203/http://e.jamatdawa.org/pages.php?action=menu&id=3|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/12/un_declares_jamaatud.php|last=Roggio|first=Bill|date=2008-12-11|website=The Long War Journal|title=UN declares Jamaat-ud-Dawa a terrorist front group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217113851/https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/12/un_declares_jamaatud.php|archive-date=2008-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2012, the United States announced a bounty of $10&nbsp;million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-puts-10-million-bounty-on-pakistan-terror-groups-leader/2012/04/03/gIQAx9NjsS_story.html|title=U.S. puts $10 million bounty on Pakistan terror group\u2019s leader|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> on Saeed for his alleged role in the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]] that killed 164 civilians. While India supported the US move, there were protests against it in Pakistan.<ref name=\"ndtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/india-welcomes-10-million-bounty-on-hafiz-saeed/228229|title=India welcomes $10&nbsp;million bounty on Hafiz Saeed|date=2012-04-03|website=NDTV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801202118/https://www.ndtv.com/video/news/news/india-welcomes-10-million-bounty-on-hafiz-saeed-228229|archive-date=2017-08-01|url-status=live|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnbcpakistan.com/Thousands-protest-against-US-bounty-on-Hafiz-Saeed-news-2027.html|title=Thousands protest against US bounty on Hafiz Saeed|date=2015-01-02|website=JAAG TV|publisher=CNBC Pakistan|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150102080111/http://www.cnbcpakistan.com/Thousands-protest-against-US-bounty-on-Hafiz-Saeed-news-2027.html|archivedate=2015-01-02|url-status=dead|access-date=2015-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/pakistan/story/india-will-leave-kashmir-just-as-us-leaving-afghanistan-hafiz-saeed-176578-2014-01-13|title=India will be forced to Kashmir just like US in Afghanistan: Hafiz Saeed|date=2014-01-13|work=India Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716061653/https://www.indiatoday.in/world/pakistan/story/india-will-leave-kashmir-just-as-us-leaving-afghani