016}}</ref> a pro-Pakistan [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|Kashmiri separatist]] militant organisation operating in [[Kashmir]]. He also heads the [[United Jihad Council]], a Pakistan-based conglomeration of jihadist militant groups sponsored by the [[Inter-Services Intelligence|ISI]],<ref>{{citation |author=International Crisis Group |title=Kashmir: Confrontation and Miscalculation |publisher=International Crisis Group |date=2002 |url=http://www.css.ethz.ch/en/services/digital-library/publications/publication.html/28348|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0cPjAAAAQBAJ|title=Kashmir: The Unwritten History|last=Snedden|first=Christopher|publisher=HarperCollins India|year=2013|isbn=9350298988|location=|pages=198|orig-year=first published as ''The Untold Story of the People of Azad Kashmir'', 2012}}</ref> with the goal of annexing [[Jammu and Kashmir]] to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|last=PTI|title=Hizb chief Syed Salahuddin warns Pakistan against withdrawing support on Kashmir|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/Hizb-chief-Syed-Salahuddin-warns-Pakistan-against-withdrawing-support-on-Kashmir/articleshow/13932562.cms|accessdate=8 June 2012|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=8 Jun 2012}}</ref><ref name=arab_news_pak>{{cite news|title=Normalization of Indo-Pak ties hurts Kashmir cause: Salahuddin|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/413443|accessdate=8 June 2012|newspaper=[[Arab News]]|date=8 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2017/05/time-for-pakistan-to-cut-ties-with-hizbul-mujahideen/|title=Time for Pakistan to Cut Ties With Hizbul Mujahideen|first=Kunwar Khuldune|last=Shahid|work=The Diplomat|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/hum.htm|title=Hizb-ul-Mujahideen|last=Pike|first=John|website=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=2017-06-27}}</ref> Salahuddin vowed to block any peaceful resolution to the Kashmir conflict, threatened to train more Kashmiri suicide bombers, and vowed to turn the Kashmir valley \"into a graveyard for Indian forces.\"<ref name=\"U.S. Department of State\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2017/06/272168.htm|title=State Department Terrorist Designations of Mohammad Yusuf Shah AKA Syed Salahuddin|work=U.S. Department of State|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1341914/kashmiri-militant-leader-punished-as-modi-visits-us|title=Kashmiri militant leader punished as Modi visits US|last=Siddiqui|first=AP {{!}} Naveed|date=2017-06-26|work=Dawn.com|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en}}</ref> He is currently listed on the [[NIA Most Wanted|Most Wanted List]] of India's [[National Investigation Agency]].{{sfn|Bloeria, Conflicts in Jammu and Kashmir|2012}} He is named as a [[Specially Designated Global Terrorist]] by the [[United States Department of State|US Department Of State]].<ref>{{cite web|title=State Department Terrorist Designations of Mohammad Yusuf Shah AKA Syed Salahuddin|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2017/06/272168.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=India stands vindicated as US names Hizbul chief Syed Salahuddin 'global terrorist'|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/india-stands-vindicated-as-us-names-hizb-man-syed-salahuddin-global-terrorist/articleshow/59326622.cms}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Rocco Morabito (mobster, born 1966)|Rocco Morabito]]\n|51\n|{{Flag|Italy}}\n|Morabito is an [[Italians|Italian]] criminal and a member of the [['Ndrangheta]], a Mafia-type organisation in [[Calabria]]. Before being arrested in [[Uruguay]] on 4 September 2017,<ref name=bbc040917>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-41146886 Rocco Morabito: Italian mafia boss held in Uruguay], BBC News, 4 September 2017</ref> he had been a fugitive since 1994 being wanted for drug trafficking, Mafia association and other serious crimes. On 24 June 2019, Morabito escaped from the central penitentiary (C\u00e1rcel Central) of Montevideo with three other inmates \"through a hole in the roof of the building\".<ref name=abc040917>[https://www.montevideo.com.uy/Noticias/Se-fugaron-4-peligrosos-presos-de-Carcel-Central-Uno-de-ellos-es-Rocco-Morabito-uc722190 Se fugaron 4 peligrosos presos de C\u00e1rcel Central. Uno de ellos es Rocco Morabito]</ref> At the time, he was awaiting extradition to Italy, based on prior convictions made in absentia for links to organized crime and drug trafficking.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-48750218 |title=Rocco Morabito: Italian mafia boss escapes from Uruguayan prison |date=24 June 2019 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=24 June 2019 |quote=Morabito and three other inmates \"escaped through a hole in the roof of the building\" late on Sunday and robbed the owner of a nearby farmhouse for money, the ministry said in a statement (in Spanish).}}</ref> He is currently on the [[list of most wanted fugitives in Italy]].<ref name=ricerca>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.interno.gov.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/2013_07_31_morabito.html Morabito Rocco], Direzione centrale della Polizia Criminale \u2013 Programma Speciale di Ricerca</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Carlos Ghosn]]\t\n|65\n|{{Flag|Japan}}\n|Ghosn is a [[Brazilians|Brazilian]]-born French businessman of Lebanese descent,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/nissan-ex-chair-ghosn-released-from-japanese-detention/ar-BBWgjP3?OCID=ansmsnnews11|title=Nissan ex-chair Ghosn released from Japanese detention|website=www.msn.com|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> who is currently a wanted fugitive in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/03/793508679/fugitive-carlos-ghosn-escaped-house-arrest-by-walking-out-not-in-box-officials-s|title=Fugitive Carlos Ghosn Escaped House Arrest By Walking Out, Not In Box, Officials Say|website=NPR.org}}</ref> He was suspected of committing crime and was imprisoned, and after being released on bail on 25 April he later fled from Japan to [[Beirut]], Lebanon on 30 December, which was an infringement of his bail agreement. On 2 January 2020, [[Interpol]] issued an arrest warrant for Ghosn's capture,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50972149|title=Interpol issues notice for Carlos Ghosn arrest|date=2 January 2020|access-date=3 January 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> he is an internationally wanted fugitive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/03/793508679/fugitive-carlos-ghosn-escaped-house-arrest-by-walking-out-not-in-box-officials-s|title=Fugitive Carlos Ghosn Escaped House Arrest By Walking Out, Not In Box, Officials Say|website=NPR.org}}</ref> as he is currently sought by the police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/where-is-former-nissan-ceo-carlos-ghosn-achrafieh-beirut-lebanon-2020-1|title=Fugitive former Nissan CEO Carlos Ghosn is holed up in a blush-colored mansion in one of Beirut's most expensive districts after his 'easy' escape from Japan, according to reports. Here's what Achrafieh is like.|last=Wiley|first=Melissa|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Fugitives who are no longer sought==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date of disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age at disappearance\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Country\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n|-\n|1724\n|[[Jack Sheppard]]\n|22\n||{{nowrap|{{Flag|England|1724}}}}\n|Sheppard nicknamed \"Honest Jack\", was a notorious English [[Theft|thief]] and [[prison escape]]e of early 18th-century [[London]]. Born into a poor family, he was [[apprentice]]d as a carpenter, but took to theft and burglary in 1723, with little more than a year of his training to complete. He was arrested and imprisoned five times in 1724, but [[List of people who escaped multiple times from prison|escaped four times from prison]], making him a notorious public figure, and wildly popular with the poorer classes. He escaped from a prison in October 1724 for the last time. He disguised himself as a beggar and returned to the city. He broke into the Rawlins brothers' [[pawnbroker]]'s shop in Drury Lane on the night of 29 October 1724, taking a black silk suit, a silver sword, rings, watches, a wig, and other items.<ref name=\"moore164\">Moore, p.164.</ref><ref>Lynch, para.46.</ref> He dressed himself as a dandy gentleman and used the proceeds to spend a day and the following evening on the tiles with two mistresses. He was arrested a final time in the early morning on 1 November, blind drunk, \"in a handsome Suit of Black, with a Diamond Ring and a [[carnelian]] ring on his Finger, and a fine [[Peruke|Light Tye Peruke]]\", and was convicted, and [[hanging|hanged]] at [[Tyburn, London|Tyburn]], ending his brief criminal career after less than two years.<ref>''The London Journal'', 7 November 1724. Mullan, p.186.</ref> \n|-\n|1871\n|[[Elbert A. Woodward]]\n|33\u201334\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1871}}}}\n|Woodward was a major member in the [[William M. Tweed|Boss Tweed]] corruption scandal in 1871 that took place in Chicago. He and others defrauded Chicago between $25 and $45 million. He was indicted and tried, but fled the to Spain to escape punishment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artoftheprint.com/artistpages/nast_thomas_william_tweed_1876.htm|title=Thomas Nast Harper's Weekly New York A Journal of Civilization - Willie We have Missed You William M. Tweed Boss Tweed Returned to Prison the New York Tammany Ringdom|website=www.artoftheprint.com|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref> He was later sent back to Chicago and later to New York. He avoided jail time by repaying $151,779 of stolen money. In his later years, he became a farmer in Norwalk.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=HqtWCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT123&lpg=PT123&dq=Elbert+A.+Woodward+was+a+farmer&source=bl&ots=vga-zkopQT&sig=ACfU3U1HnsZY8qxw1RYkt5Jo7RU65oBS6A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwicgZ3A9c3mAhWPFTQIHUzuA5UQ6AEwBHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Elbert%20A.%20Woodward%20was%20a%20farmer&f=false|title=Lee County, Virginia: History Revealed Through Biographical and Genealogical Sketches of Its Ancestors|last=Secrist|first=M.|date=2013-02-03|publisher=Lulu Press, Inc|isbn=978-1-300-70171-2|language=en}}</ref> He died on 29 September 1905.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=Elbert+A.+Woodward+died+1905&rlz=1C1AVFC_enCA736CA736&oq=Elbert+A.+Woodward+died+1905&aqs=chrome..69i57.6704j0j8&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8|title=Elbert A. Woodward died 1905 - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref> \n|-\n|1872\n|[[Davy Crockett (outlaw)|Davy Crockett]]\n|23\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1875}}}}\n|Crockett was a younger relative of the famed [[Americans|American]] [[American frontier|frontiersman]] [[Davy Crockett]],<ref name=\"Metz, pg. 54-55\">{{cite book | last=Metz| first=Leon Claire| authorlink=Leon Claire Metz| title=The Encyclopedia of Lawmen, Outlaws, and Gunfighters| publisher=Infobase Publishing| year=2002| isbn=978-1-4381-3021-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/David-Davy-Crockett/6000000021644981936|title=David|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> but unlike the hero Davy Crockett this Davy Crockett was an [[outlaw]]. He was sent to jail for criminal acts that he committed, but escaped in 1872 after he which fled to a ranch. He was killed four years later in 1876.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=BegmwZ3fuGUC&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=outlaw+davy+crockett+had+disappeared&source=bl&ots=seDoa-FhGf&sig=ACfU3U0kRbM0GKvD94ksX8bmz58N8m6SiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiKvNuRvpvhAhXWvp4KHbYMBMwQ6AEwDHoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=outlaw%20davy%20crockett%20had%20disappeared&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Lawmen, Outlaws, and Gunfighters|last=Metz|first=Leon Claire|date=2002|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-3021-7|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1875\n|[[William M. Tweed]]\n|53\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1875}}}}\n|Tweed was an American politician most notable for being the \"[[Political boss|boss]]\" of [[Tammany Hall]], the [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] [[political machine]] that played a major role in the politics of [[History of New York City (1855\u20131897)|19th century New York City]] and [[New York (state)|State]]. Tweed was imprisoned in the [[Ludlow Street Jail]] for a corruption scandal in 1871, although he was allowed home visits and on 4 December 1875, which during one of these Tweed fled to Spain,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americaslibrary.gov/jb/recon/jb_recon_boss_1.html|title=Boss Tweed Escaped From Prison|website=www.americaslibrary.gov|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref> and got a job working as a common seaman on a ship. The U.S. government later discovered his whereabouts and arranged for his arrest once he reached the Spanish border; he was recognized from Nast's political cartoons. He was turned over to an American warship, which took him to authorities in New York City on 26 November 1876, and he was sent back prison.<ref name=\"History.com\">[http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/boss-tweed-delivered-to-authorities \"'Boss' Tweed Delivered to Authorities\"] ''[[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]]'' website, n.d.g. Retrieved 3 February 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000440 |title=Tweed, William Marcy, (1823\u20131878) |publisher=bioguide.congress.gov |accessdate=19 July 2009}}</ref> He died in the [[Ludlow Street Jail]] on 12 April 1878.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1881-01-01\"|1881\n|[[Billy the Kid]]\n|21\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1881}}}}\n|Billy the Kid, who was born Henry McCarty and also known as William H. Bonney, was an [[Americans|American]] [[American Old West|Old West]] outlaw and [[gunfighter]] who killed eight men before he was shot and killed.{{sfn|Rasch|1995|pp=23\u201335}}{{sfn|Wallis|2007|pp=244\u2013245}} He took part in New Mexico's [[Lincoln County War]], during which he allegedly committed three murders. After being jailed he escaped from the jailhouse in Lincoln, New Mexico on 28 April 1881.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americaslibrary.gov/jb/gilded/jb_gilded_billykid_1.html|title=Billy the Kid Escaped from Jail|website=www.americaslibrary.gov|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref> He evaded law enforcement until 14 July 1881, when he was ambushed and killed by Sheriff Pat Garrett at a ranch house.\n|-\n|1882\n|[[Pugsey Hurley]]\n|45\u201346\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1882}}}}\n|Hurley, also known as \"Pugsey Reilly\" or \"Pugsey Hanley\", was an [[Americans|American]] burglar of English descent, who was a river pirate and underworld figure in [[New York City]] during the mid-to late 19th century.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/scorseseupcloses0000nyce|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/scorseseupcloses0000nyce/page/165 165]|quote=Pugsy Hurley a criminal.|title=Scorsese Up Close: A Study of the Films|last=Nyce|first=Ben|date=2004|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-4787-3|language=en}}</ref> After doing multiple crimes he was sent to jail after 15 August 1874 and broke out in April 1882.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Zo4_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=Pugsey+Hurley+escaped+from+jail&source=bl&ots=DMVjfRUM8J&sig=ACfU3U0G3DOUxGsEdRh1tM-qyN8jsn8Vtg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwivnp7p0fDmAhUHqp4KHR9nAmEQ6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Pugsey%20Hurley%20escaped%20from%20jail&f=false|title=1886 Professional Criminals of America|last=Byrnes|first=Thomas|date=1886|publisher=Chelsea House Publishers|language=en}}</ref> He was captured by in New York City by the police on 1 August 1882, and was returned to jail.\n|-\n|1923\n|[[Tommy O'Connor (criminal)|Tommy O'Connor]]\n|30\u201331\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1923}}}}\n|O'Connor was a gangster who escaped from the Chicago, Illinois, courthouse in 1923, only four days before he was to have been executed at the Historical [[Gallows]]<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">Lydersen, Kari [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/30/AR2006103000984.html \"Infamous Piece of Chicago History Goes on the Block\"] ''The Washington Post'', 31 October 2006. Retrieved 7 April 2012.</ref> for the murder of a policeman. It is unknown how O'Connor died, though there is a tombstone of him at the [[Holy Sepulchre Cemetery (Worth, Illinois)|Holy Sepulchre Cemetery]] in [[Worth, Illinois]].<Ref>[https://www.limerickpost.ie/2018/08/11/the-twisted-tale-of-terrible-tommy-oconnor/ ''Limerick Post'']</ref> His year of death is accepted as being 1951 and therefore is no longer sought by the police.\n|-\n|1945\n|[[Josef Mengele]]\n|34\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Nazi Germany|1945}}}}\n|Nicknamed the \"Angel of Death\" by his victims, Josef Mengele was a German physician and [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] officer stationed at [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] to conduct [[Nazi human experimentation|human experimentation]] on inmates. He personally decided the fate of countless Jews and others, as he also partook in sending newly arrived prisoners to the [[Gas chamber|gas chambers]] or forcing them into slave labor. However, Mengele would also select certain inmates (especially twins) to undergo horrific experiments. Many of his victims died as a result of the brutality of the tests he performed.<ref>https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/josef-mengele</ref> As Auschwitz was evacuated, Mengele was transferred to [[Gross-Rosen concentration camp]] before going into hiding and ultimately fleeing to South America in 1949 under the false name \"Fritz Hollmann\". Despite numerous efforts of multiple government agencies and [[Nazi hunter|Nazi hunters]], including operations by the [[Mossad]] in [[Argentina]], [[Paraguay]] and [[Brazil]] to arrest Josef Mengele, he evaded capture for the rest of his life.<ref>https://beta.spectator.co.uk/article/how-did-the-infamous-josef-mengele-escape-punishment-</ref> In 1979, Mengele suffered a stroke while swimming and drowned off the coast of [[Bertioga]]. His remains were exhumed and identified in 1985, a discovery which was later confirmed by DNA testing in 1992.<ref>https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/the-angel-of-death-dies</ref>\n|-\n|1958\n|[[Frederick Grant Dunn]]\n|52\u201353\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1958}}}}\n|Dunn, an [[Americans|American]] criminal, burglar having a career that started in 1919. Dunn was labeled by the press as \"the modern John Dillinger\", and his crimes resulted in him being listed on the [[FBI's Ten Most Wanted]] in 1958.<ref name=\"Newton\">Newton, Michael. ''The Encyclopedia of Robberies, Heists, and Capers''. New York: Facts On File Inc., 2002. (pg. 90-91) {{ISBN|0-8160-4488-0}}</ref> In 1958 he disappeared and was found dead in 1959,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ytwsCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA128&lpg=PA128&dq=Frederick+Grant+Dunn+died+mysteriously&source=bl&ots=mAppBlN0wo&sig=ACfU3U0ONNky0ILeQVGxRgp8zQmr6H3FLw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj4896V8fLmAhVKvZ4KHdXZCxEQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Frederick%20Grant%20Dunn%20died%20mysteriously&f=false|title=A History of Heists: Bank Robbery in America|last=Clark|first=Jerry|last2=Palattella|first2=Ed|date=2015-07-09|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-3546-5|language=en}}</ref> and is no longer sought by the police. \n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1959-01-01\"|1959\n|[[Frank Freshwaters]]\n|23\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1959}}}}\n|Freshwaters is an [[Americans|American]] criminal and former fugitive who was arrested in 1957 for the death of Eugene Flynt, whom he struck and killed while speeding. He had been on the run for 56 years after he escaped from an honor farm in 1959.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/05/05/us/shawshank-fugitive-caught/index.html|title=Frank Freshwaters caught after 56 years on the lam|author1=Kevin Conlon |author2=Greg Botelho |author3=Jason Hanna|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-31}}</ref> In the intervening years, Freshwaters lived under an assumed name and sought work as a truck driver. He was extradited back to Ohio, and served at the Ohio Department of Rehabilitation and Correction. According to Gallop, \"more than 2,000 people from half a dozen states\" wrote in to the parole board to support him. On 25 February 2016, it was voted to release Freshwaters after his attorney argued he had caused no harm in his years evading officials. He was placed on parole with five years supervision. He was released on 16 June 2016 and is no longer wanted.\n|-\n|1963\n|[[Bernardo Provenzano]]\n|26\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|1963}}}}\n|Provenzano, an [[Italians|Italian]] [[mobster]] and chief of a clan known as the [[Corleonesi]], a Mafia faction that had is roots in the town of [[Corleone]]. He disappeared in September 1963 and was caught in April 2006 after nearly 43 years on the run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gangstersinc.ning.com/profiles/blogs/cosa-nostra-boss-of-bosses-bernardo-provenzano-dead-at-83|title=Cosa Nostra boss of bosses Bernardo Provenzano dead at 83|last=Posted by Gangsters Inc. on July 13|first=2016 at 11:49am|last2=Blog|first2=View|website=gangstersinc.ning.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> On 13 July 2016 he died from [[bladder cancer]] at San Paol Prison Hospital in [[Milan]], Italy at age 83,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36782555|title=Italian mafia boss Bernardo Provenzano, 83, dies in jail|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=2016-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secoloditalia.it/2016/07/per-provenzano-funerali-vietati-ce-si-indigna-non-fa-vendette/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714163011/https://www.secoloditalia.it/2016/07/per-provenzano-funerali-vietati-ce-si-indigna-non-fa-vendette/|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 July 2016|publisher=Secolo d'Italia|date=13 July 2016|language=Italian|title=Per Provenzano funerali vietati. Ma c\u2019\u00e8 chi si indigna: lo Stato non fa vendette}}</ref> after being sick since 2014.\n|-\n|1967\n|[[Donald Richard Bussmeyer]]\n|31\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1967}}}}\n|Bussmeyer is an American criminal and a former member of the FBI's [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Ten Most Wanted]] list in 1967.<ref>Born in Missouri according to a [http://www.ancestry.com/1940-census/usa/Missouri/Donald-R-Bussmeyer_34nmz2 1940 census], retrieved 2014-01-10.</ref> He became a career criminal and drug addict with convictions for auto theft, attempted burglary, assault with intent to kill, and armed robbery when, on 2 March 1967, he and two accomplices, James Alaway and Russell Jones, robbed $75,000 from a Los Angeles bank and went on the run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/topten-history/hires_images/FBI-251-DonaldRichardBussmeyer.jpg/view|title=251. Donald Richard Bussmeyer|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> Due to large media coverage and publicity,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fbimostwanted.us/zc/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=6&products_id=1063|title=Donald Richard Bussmeyer [1063] \u2013 $19.99 : FBIMostWanted.us, Wanted Posters & Related Collectibles|website=fbimostwanted.us|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> Bussmeyer was eventually traced to a safehouse in [[Upland, California]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/ten-most-wanted-fugitives-faq/ten-most-wanted-201-300|title=Ten Most Wanted Fugitives 201 to 300|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> within two months, and on 24 August he was captured along with his wife Hallie and associate Gene Harrington.\n|-\n|1968\n|[[Benjamin Hoskins Paddock]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1968}}}}\n|Paddock was an American bank robber and con man who after escaping prison in 1968, was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list from 1969 and remained on it to 1977.<ref name=\"Inc1971\">{{cite book|author=Time Inc|title=LIFE|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MkAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42|date=9 April 1971|publisher=Time Inc|page=42}}</ref><ref name=\"norman2017\">{{cite news |last=Norman |first=Greg |date=October 2, 2017 |title=Las Vegas shooter's father, 'Bingo Bruce,' lived a colorful life of crime and deception |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/10/02/las-vegas-shooters-father-bingo-bruce-lived-colorful-life-crime-and-deception.html |work=[[Fox News]] |location= |access-date= 6 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=September 15, 1978 |title=Prison Escapee to Stand Trial on Bank Charge |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19780915&id=w_lVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CuIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2278,4163503 |work=[[The Register-Guard]] (Eugene, Oregon) |location= |access-date=  6 October 2017}}</ref> He was captured and arrested in early September 1978 in [[Springfield, Oregon]], and was sent back to jail, but was eventually released on parole.<ref name=ArizonaRepublic1978>{{cite news|title=10-year Fugitive Jailed in Oregon|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14160106/10year_fugitive_jailed_in_oregon/|access-date=3 October 2017|work=Arizona Republic|date=September 9, 1978|location=Phoenix, Arizona|page=3}}</ref> He died of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 18 January 1998, in [[Arlington, Texas]].\n|-\n|1969\n|[[Marie Dean Arrington]]\n|35\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1969}}}}\n|Arrington was an American [[criminal]]. On 1 March 1969, Arrington escaped from Florida Correctional Institution in her pajamas by cutting a window screen and jumping out. In May 1969 she was placed on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted List, making her the second woman to ever be placed on the list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lakeandsumterstyle.com/first/|title=The first|last=Lake & Sumter Style|date=2014-07-10|website=Lake & Sumter STYLE|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-lists/fbi-adds-10th-woman-to-most-wanted-list-meet-them-all-18075/|title=FBI Adds 10th Woman to 'Most Wanted' List: Meet Them All|last=Weiser|first=Sonia|last2=Stone|first2=Rolling|date=2016-06-30|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> Arrington wasn't captured until two years later in March 1972 after having fled to New Orleans and worked as a [[Waiting staff|waitress]]. Arrington died on 10 May 2014 in [[Lowell Correctional Institution]] in [[Marion County, Florida]], the same institution from which she escaped.\n|-\n|1970\n|[[Susan Edith Saxe]]\n|26\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1970}}}}\n|Saxe who charged with [[Bank robbery]] is one of the ten women ever to make the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI's]] [[most wanted list]]. She was on the list on from 17 October 1970,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-lists/fbi-adds-10th-woman-to-most-wanted-list-meet-them-all-18075/|title=FBI Adds 10th Woman to 'Most Wanted' List: Meet Them All|last=Weiser|first=Sonia|last2=Stone|first2=Rolling|date=2016-06-30|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> until March 1975 after she was caught in [[Philadelphia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/03/29/archives/susan-saxe-held-on-350000-bail-bank-theft-suspect-sends-greetings.html|title=Susan Saxe Held on $350,000 Bail|date=1975-03-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|-\n|1971\n|[[John List]]\n|46\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1971}}}}\n|List was an American [[mass murder]]er<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crimemuseum.org/crime-library/serial-killers/serials-killers-vs-mass-murderers/|title=Serial Killers vs. Mass Murderers|publisher=[[National Museum of Crime & Punishment|Crime Museum]]|access-date=17 January 2018}}</ref> and long-time [[fugitive]] who disappeared on 9 November 1971 after he killed his wife, mother, and three children at their home in [[Westfield, New Jersey]]. He was captured on 1 June 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@delanirbartlette/john-list-he-committed-the-almost-perfect-murder-4a30ad9199b9|title=John List: He Committed the (Almost) Perfect Murder|last=Bartlette|first=DeLani R.|date=2019-06-03|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> and was sent back to jail and died in prison in 2008 at the age of 82.\n|-\n|1972\n|[[George Wright (fugitive)|George Wright]]\n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1972}}}}\n|Wright is a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] citizen of American origin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=pt&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&layout=2&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fsicnoticias.sapo.pt%2Fpais%2F2011%2F09%2F28%2Fforagido-george-wright-apanhado-em-portugal-atraves-de-chamada-telefonica | title=Foragido George Wright apanhado em Portugal atrav\u00e9s de chamada telef\u00f3nica  convicted kidnapper and murderer |publisher=SIC Noticias | date=26 September 2011}}</ref> who in 1961, graduated from [[Mary Bethune]] High School in [[Halifax, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Awaiting Extradition U.S. Fugitive Is Far From His Hometown In Halifax|url=http://www.sovanow.com/index.php?/news/article/awaiting_extradition_u.s._fugitive_is_far_from_his_hometown_in_halifax/|publisher=News & Record|date=3 October 2011}}</ref> Wright was originally arrested and convicted for murder in 1962 and sentenced to up to 30 years in prison. He escaped from prison in 1970 and hijacked a [[Delta Air Lines]] flight in 1972 with a number of accomplices. On 26 September 2011, he was arrested in Portugal<ref name=\"AP Fox\">{{Cite news |title=U.S. Officials Reportedly Knew Fugitive Was in Africa |date=29 September 2011 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Fox News]] |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/09/29/us-officials-reportedly-knew-fugitive-was-in-africa/\n}}</ref> and taken into custody.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/hijacker-fugitive-george-wright-caught-after-41-years-says-fbi/|title=Hijacker-fugitive George Wright caught after 41 years, says FBI|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1976\n|[[Vathaire affair|Herv\u00e9 de Vathaire]]\n|50\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|France|1976}}}}\n|Vathaire was a private financial director of [[Marcel Dassault]], and founder of an aerospace company the [[Dassault Group]], and had just become a widow since his wife, who had committed [[suicide]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/09/09/archives/frenchman-is-home-missing-money-isnt-accountant-who-disappeared.html|title=Frenchman Is Home, Missing Money Isn't|last=Times|first=James F. Clarity Special to The New York|date=1976-09-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 6 July 1976, Vathaire disappeared after he went to a [[BNP Paribas]] branch<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NBVg-Iho-1MC&pg=PA181&lpg=PA181&dq=herv%C3%A9+de+vathaire+has+disappeared&source=bl&ots=fvUNZhmPYN&sig=ACfU3U1TQ4Rcy1GJFA_FyjmRsfxEHePLiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj0pd2t_fLmAhVMGTQIHb1jAiwQ6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=herv%C3%A9%20de%20vathaire%20has%20disappeared&f=false|title=Humanitarian Problems in Lebanon: Hearing Before the Subcommittee to Investigate Problems Connected with Refugees and Escapees of the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, Ninety-fourth Congress, Second Session, April 5, [July 29] 1976|last=Escapees|first=United States Congress Senate Committee on the Judiciary Subcommittee to Investigate Problems Connected with Refugees and|date=1976|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|language=en}}</ref> and withdrew 8 million francs (800 million old francs, 1.2 million euros, $1.6 million at the time)<ref>Robert Nash, Jay (1977) ''Among The Missing'', p.413, {{ISBN|0-671-24005-6}}.</ref> from Marcel Dassault's account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&u=http://www.larousse.fr/archives/journaux_annee/1977/330/faits_divers&prev=search|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/09/12/archives/herve-de-vathaire-is-back.html|title=Nerve de Vathaire Is Back.|date=1976-09-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A manhunt that was conducted to find him ended on 26 September 1976, when Vathaire returned to [[Paris]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/09/04/archives/dassault-accountant-vanishes-with-16-million-in-2-valises-dassault.html|title=Dassault Accountant Vanishes With $1.6 Million in 2 Valises|last=Times|first=James F. Clarity Special to The New York|date=1976-09-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1977-01-01\"|1977\n|[[Ted Bundy]]\n|28\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1977}}}}\n|Bundy was an [[Americans|American]] [[serial killer]], [[kidnapping|kidnapper]], [[Rape|rapist]], [[Burglary|burglar]], and [[Necrophilia|necrophile]] who assaulted and murdered numerous young women and girls during the 1970s and possibly earlier. In 1975, Bundy was jailed for the first time when he was incarcerated in [[Utah]] for aggravated kidnapping and attempted criminal assault. He then became a suspect in a progressively longer list of unsolved homicides in multiple states. Facing murder charges in [[Colorado]], he engineered two dramatic escapes and committed further assaults,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/ted-bundy-gets-caught-973179|title=How One Notorious Serial Killer Got Caught|last=writer|first=Charles Montaldo Charles Montaldo is a|last2=Enforcement|first2=Former Licensed Private Detective Who Worked with Law|website=ThoughtCo|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26|last3=Crime|first3=Insurance Firms Investigating|last4=fraud.}}</ref> including three murders, before his ultimate recapture in [[Florida]] in 1978. For the Florida homicides, he received three death sentences in two separate trials. Bundy was executed in the [[electric chair]] at [[Florida State Prison]] on 24 January 1989.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Barry|last1=Bearak|title=Bundy Electrocuted After Night of Weeping, Praying : 500 Cheer Death of Murderer|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1989-01-24/news/mn-1075_1_ted-bundy|accessdate=16 July 2016|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=24 January 1989|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160718145205/http://articles.latimes.com/1989-01-24/news/mn-1075_1_ted-bundy|archivedate=18 July 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n|-\n|1978\n|[[George Feigley]]\n|37\u201338\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1978}}}}\n|Feigley was an American church leader. He has been described as a sex [[cult]] leader. Feigley served over 32 years in prison for sex crimes against children, from 1975 to 2008. Feigley was sent to the [[Taylor County, West Virginia|Taylor County]] Jail in [[Grafton, West Virginia|Grafton]] in 1978, but escaped less than a month later while awaiting extradition back to Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26040960/george_feigley_escapes_from_jail_after/|title=Search for rapist|last=|first=|date=18 October 1978|work=Evening Herald of Shenandoah-Ashland-Mahanoy City|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> After this he was free for two months before he was captured, hiding on another farm near [[Sneedville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26041289/george_feigley_recaptured_in_tennessee/|title=Sneedville Cult Leader Charged In Prison Escape|last=|first=|date=22 February 1979|work=The Tennessean|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> Feigley became eligible for [[parole]] in 1990, but parole was denied then and at each subsequent annual review. Having served the full-time for all his convictions, Feigley was released from prison on 15 August 2008. His health which was already bad got worse and he died on 13 April 2009.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1978-01-01\"|1978\n|[[Jerry Balisok]]\n|22\u201323\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1978}}}}\n|Balisok was an [[Americans|American]] [[professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] who used the name Mr. X. He was indicted on multiple counts of check forgery in 1977, but skipped bail, stole the identification documents of his girlfriend's cousin Ricky Allen Wetta, assumed his identity and fled with her via Florida to the Caribbean. After he failed to appear for his trial in 1978, [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] investigators were misled into believing that they had died in the [[Jonestown]] mass suicides that year. He returned to the United States and in 1989 was arrested for attempted murder. Fingerprinting revealed his identity. He was found guilty and served 13 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19900310&slug=1060248|title=Man Feared Dead In Jonestown Ran Hoax, Police Say|date=10 March 1990|website=seattletimes.com|publisher=Seattle Times|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> Balisok died in prison in 2013 of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] that was caused by a [[heat stroke]].\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1979-01-01\"|1979\n|[[Idi Amin]]\n|54\n||{{nowrap|{{Flag|Uganda|1979}}}}\n|Idi Amin was the third [[President of Uganda]] and chairman of the [[Organization of African Unity]]. Under his leadership, ethnic minorities and political dissidents were brutally executed, giving Amin his nickname, \"The Butcher of Uganda\". <ref>https://www.history.com/topics/africa/idi-amin</ref> When [[Fall of Kampala|Kampala fell to Tanzanian forces]], Idi Amin fled by helicopter into exile. He died in [[Saudi Arabia]] on 16 August 2003 from [[kidney failure]] before he could ever be extradited back to Uganda.<ref>https://apnews.com/0da73ef4003fd1464ffe7c411eb568f1</ref>  \n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1981-07-04\"|1980\n|[[Donald Eugene Webb]]\n|50\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1980}}}}\n|Donald Eugene Webb was an [[Americans|American]] [[career criminal]] and [[fugitive]] wanted for [[Burglary|attempted burglary]] and the [[murder]] of police chief Gregory Adams in the small community of [[Saxonburg, Pennsylvania]] on 4 December 1980.<ref name=\"postgazette\">{{cite news |first=Jerry |last=Roberts |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=X0QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4469,535164&dq=donald-eugene-webb |title=Year later, police-slaying suspect still free |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=3 December 1981 |accessdate=11 September 2010 }}</ref> The last confirmed sighting of him was in July 1981, reported by an anonymous tipster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=X0QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4469,535164&dq=donald-eugene-webb|title=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette \u2013 Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2017-07-03}}</ref> On 4 May 1981, Webb was named as the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 1980s|375th fugitive to be placed]] on the [[Federal Bureau of Investigations|FBI]]'s [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Ten Most Wanted list]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/10/27/wanted-donald-eugene-webb-for-murder-pennsylvania-police-chief.html|title=WANTED: Donald Eugene Webb for the Murder of a Pennsylvania Police Chief|last=Maskaly|first=Michelle|date=27 October 2008|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-07-03|language=en-US}}</ref> On 14 July 2017, remains found at the Dartmouth home of Webb's wife were identified as belonging to Webb. Investigators stated that Webb had died in 1999 after suffering multiple strokes.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Victoria |last=Warren |url=http://whdh.com/news/fbi-remains-found-in-dartmouth-yard-are-those-of-fugitive-wanted-for-killing-police-chief |title=Remains found in Dartmouth yard are those of fugitive wanted for killing police chief |publisher=The Associated Press via WHDH News |date=14 July 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916204734/http://whdh.com/news/fbi-buried-body-found-in-dartmouth-is-fugitive-accused-in-police-chiefs-murder/ |archive-date=16 September 2017 |access-date=30 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|1981\n|[[Nehanda Abiodun]]\n|37\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1981}}}}\n|Abiodun, born \"Cheri Laverne Dalton,\" was an [[African Americans|African American]] [[rap music|hip hop]] activist, black revolutionary, and [[fugitive]] who had fled to [[Cuba]].<ref name=\"lacey\">{{cite news |last=Lacey |first=Marc |title=Cuba's Rap Vanguard Reaches Beyond the Party Line |quote=One of those working behind the scenes to aid Cuba's rappers is Cheri Dalton, an American who goes by the name Nehanda Abiodun. She is a black militant who was wanted by the F.B.I. in connection with a string of robberies, including a 1981 holdup of an armored car near Nyack, N.Y. Now living in exile in Cuba, she has formed a Havana chapter of Black August, a grass-roots group that promotes hip-hop culture. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 December 2006 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/15/world/americas/15cuba.html |accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> Abiodun was wanted by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] in connection of the 1981 robbery of a [[Brink's]] truck that resulted in the killing of a Brink's guard and two police officers.<ref name=\"fbi\">{{cite web |title=CHERI LAVERNE DALTON |url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/dt/cheri-laverne-dalton/view |website=Federal Bureau of Investigation |publisher=United States Government, Department of Justice |accessdate=9 February 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624040313/https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/dt/cheri-laverne-dalton/view |archivedate=2018-06-24 |language=en-us}}</ref> The United States federal government also charged Abiodun in connection with [[Assata Shakur]]'s escape from prison, along with [[Susan Rosenberg]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Feron |first=James |title=TURMOIL CONTINUES AT BRINK'S HEARING |quote=Two women, identified as Cheri Dalton and Susan Rosenberg, were added as defendants in the new Federal indictment. Arrest warrants were issued for Miss Dalton, also known as Nahanda, and Miss Rosenberg, also known as Elizabeth. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=21 September 1982 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/09/21/nyregion/turmoil-continues-at-brink-s-hearing.html |accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> She was wanted since 17 November 1982. She died on 30 January 2019.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1984-01-01\"|1984\n|[[Carmine Persico]]\t\n|51\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1984}}}}\n|On 14 October 1984, Persico and the rest of the Colombo family leadership were indicted on multiple racketeering charges as part of the \"Colombo Trial\".<ref name=\"11 indicted\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H|title=11 Indicted by U.s. as the Leadership of a Crime Family |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/25/nyregion/11-indicted-by-us-as-the-leadership-of-a-crime-family.html|accessdate=15 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 October 1984}}</ref> After the indictment was published, Persico went into hiding. On 26 October, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] began a national [[Manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunt]] for Persico,<ref name=\"FBI hunting\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|title=F.B.I. Hunting 4 Indicted as Colombo Mob Chiefs |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/28/nyregion/fbi-hunting-4-indicted-as-colombo-mob-chiefs.html?scp=18&sq=%22carmine+persico%22&st=nyt|accessdate=16 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=28 October 1984}}</ref> and soon named him as the 390th fugitive to be added to their [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 1980s|Ten Most Wanted]] list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chronological Listing of The FBI's \"Ten Most Wanted Fugitives\" March 14, 1950 \u2013 March 1, 2010|url=https://www.fbi.gov/stats-services/publications/ten-most-wanted-fugitives-60th-anniversary-1950-2010/chronological_listing|publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=2011-10-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031164022/http://www.fbi.gov/stats-services/publications/ten-most-wanted-fugitives-60th-anniversary-1950-2010/chronological_listing|archivedate=31 October 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nPersico hid in the home of his cousin, mob associate Fred DeChristopher, in [[Hempstead, New York]]. Unbeknownst to Persico, DeChristopher had been relaying information to the FBI for the previous two years after being caught up in a [[sting operation]], and had already told the Bureau of Persico's whereabouts. The FBI concocted the fake \"manhunt\" to shield DeChristopher, who would later provide damning testimony against Persico as a key witness for the prosecution. Persico was arrested on 15 February 1985.<ref name=\"arrested on L.I.\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|title=Reputed Leader of Colombo Crime Group Is Arrested as a Fugitive on L.I. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/02/16/nyregion/reputed-leader-of-colombo-crime-group-is-arrested-as-a-fugitive-on-li.html?scp=15&sq=%22carmine+persico%22&st=nyt|accessdate=16 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 February 1985}}</ref> On 14 June 1986, Persico was convicted of racketeering in the Colombo Trial.<ref name=\"convicted Colombo trial\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|title=Persico Convicted in Colombo Trial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/14/nyregion/persico-convicted-in-colombo-trial.html?scp=13&sq=%22carmine+persico%22&st=nyt|accessdate=16 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 June 1986}}</ref> On 17 November, he was sentenced to 39 years in prison.<ref name=\"sentenced Colombo trial\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|title=Persico, His Son and 6 Others Get Long Terms as Colombo Gangsters |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/18/nyregion/persico-his-son-and-6-others-get-long-terms-as-colombo-gangsters.html?scp=5&sq=%22carmine+persico%22&st=nyt|accessdate=16 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 November 1986}}</ref> The sentencing judge, [[John F. Keenan]], nonetheless praised Persico's performance as his own lawyer in the Commission Trial and said, \"Mr. Persico, you're a tragedy. You are one of the most intelligent people I have ever seen in my life.\"<ref>Raab, p. 349.</ref> On 19 November Persico and the other Commission Trial defendants were convicted on all charges.<ref name=\"us jury convicts eight\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H|title=U.S. Jury Convicts Eight as Members of Mob Commission |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/20/nyregion/us-jury-convicts-eight-as-members-of-mob-commission.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=13 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 November 1986}}</ref> On 13 January 1987, Keenan sentenced Persico to 100 years in prison, to run consecutively with his 39-year sentence in the Colombo trial.<ref name=\"judge sentences 8\">{{cite news|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|title= Judge Sentences 8 Mafia Leaders to Prison Terms |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/14/nyregion/judge-sentences-8-mafia-leaders-to-prison-terms.html?src=pm|accessdate=13 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 January 1987}}</ref> On 7 March 2019, Persico died at [[Duke University Hospital|Duke University Medical Center]] in [[Durham, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Legendary-New-York-Mob-Boss-Carmine-Persico-Dead-at-Age-85-506873551.html|title=Legendary New York Mob Boss Carmine Persico, Head of Colombo Family, Dead at Age 85|publisher=nbcnewyork.com|date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|1989\n|[[Costabile Farace]]\n|25\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1989}}}}\n|Costabile \"Gus\" Farace, Jr. was a criminal with the [[Bonanno crime family]] who murdered a teenage male prostitute and a federal [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) agent in [[New York City]] who disappeared shortly after 28 February 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/topten-history/hires_images/FBI-426-CostabileGusFarace.jpg/view|title=426. Costabile \"Gus\" Farace|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> A manhunt was set up to find Farace, Jr., and at 11:08&nbsp;p.m. on 17 November 1989, police dispatchers received a [[9-1-1]] emergency call about a car parked at 1814 81st Street in the [[Bensonhurst]] section of [[Brooklyn]], and Farace, Jr. was found dead.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/11/19/nyregion/suspect-in-drug-agent-s-slaying-found-shot-to-death.html |title= Suspect in Drug Agent's Slaying Found Shot to Death|author=French, Howard W.|work= New York Times|date=19 November 1989}}</ref>\n|-\n|1989\n|[[Yip Kai Foon]]\n|37\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Hong Kong|1989}}}}\n|Foon, also known as \"Teeth Dog\" and \"Goosehead\", was an infamous Chinese [[illegal immigrant]] turned gangster who was most active in Hong Kong from the early 1980s to 1990s. He and his gang specialised in robbing jewellery stores with [[assault rifle]]s. Their weapon of choice was the [[AK-47 assault rifle]], which they acquired from black markets hosted by [[Triad society|triads]]. He is also the first person to have used an AK-47 during an armed-robbery in Hong Kong. He had escaped from jail on 24 August 1989. His career finally came to an end on 1996-05-13 when he was arrested following a [[Kennedy Town]] gunfight with police that left him paralyzed from the waist down. At the time he had a {{HKD|1}}&nbsp;million reward on his head,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scmp.com/article/147684/hong-kongs-most-wanted |title=Hong Kong's most wanted |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1996-01-28 |newspaper=South China Morning Post |location=Hong Kong |accessdate=2014-12-12 }}</ref> On 1 April 2017, he was hospitalised at [[Queen Mary Hospital (Hong Kong)|Queen Mary Hospital]] for cancer treatment. He died on 19 April 2017 of [[lung cancer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/news/20170419/56583767 | title=\u3010\u8cca\u738b\u75c5\u901d\u3011\u60a3\u80ba\u764c\u4e0b\u534a\u8eab\u7671\u7613 \u5065\u5eb7\u8a31\u53ef\u4e0b\u7372\u5b89\u6392\u505a\u8eca\u8863\u647a\u71a8 |publisher=[[Apple Daily]] |date=19 April 2017}}{{in lang|zh-hant}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20170419/bkn-20170419094611415-0419_00822_001.html|title=\u4e00\u4ee3\u8cca\u738b\u8449\u7e7c\u6b61\u764c\u75c7\u64f4\u6563\u3000\u91ab\u9662\u75c5\u901d|work=on.cc\u6771\u7db2|access-date=2017-04-19|language=zh-hk}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1990-01-01\"|1990\n|[[Paddy Mitchell]]\t\n|51\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1990}}}}\n|On 23 November 1990, Mitchell was added to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]'s [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|most wanted list]] for [[bank robbery]] charges.<ref name=fbim/> Finally, on 22 February 1994, he was arrested just after a solo robbery in [[Southaven, Mississippi]], convicted of bank robbery, and sentenced to a 65-year prison sentence.<ref name=death>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/stopwatch-gang-leader-paddy-mitchell-dies-1.677817|publisher=cbc.ca|date=14 January 2007|title=Stopwatch Gang leader, Paddy Mitchell, dies}}</ref><ref name=fbim>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/ten-most-wanted-fugitives-faq/ten-most-wanted-401-500|title=Ten Most Wanted Fugitives 401 to 500|publisher=fbi.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n|1991\n|[[Dave Everett|David Everett]]\n|29\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Australia|1991}}}}\n|Everett, an [[Australians|Australian]] criminal, writer and former member of the Australian [[Special Air Service Regiment]] and [[Karen National Liberation Army]] who disappeared in 1991. He turned to armed robbery, and during his manhunt he was regarded as the most wanted man in the history of Australian criminals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fugitives.com.au/fugitives-articles/1992/1/19/australias-mostwanted-army-hero/ |title=Australia's Most-wanted Army Hero |publisher=Fugitives.com.au |date=1992-01-19 |accessdate=2014-07-06}}</ref> Everett was released in 2002 following ten and a half years in prison. He apparently maintained good relations with his children and married Australian Commonwealth government lawyer Darryl Wookey. He was diagnosed with [[Worster-Drought syndrome|suprabulbar palsy]], the disease that killed his father. He died aged 51 on 13 May 2013 after a year long battle with cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defencenetwork.com/cancer-kills-notorious-sas-man |title=Cancer kills notorious SAS man |publisher=Defence Network |date=2013-05-16 |accessdate=2014-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Gary |last=Adshead |url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/17172626/cancer-kills-notorious-sas-man/ |title=Cancer kills notorious SAS man \u2013 Yahoo!7 |publisher=Au.news.yahoo.com |date=2013-05-16 |accessdate=2014-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714214943/https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/17172626/cancer-kills-notorious-sas-man/ |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|1993\n|[[Antonino Giuffr\u00e8]]\n|57\u201358\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|1993}}}}\n|Giuffr\u00e8, is an Italian [[Sicilian Mafia|mafioso]] from [[Caccamo]] in the [[Province of Palermo]], [[Sicily]] who was wanted since 1993.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NuK3RiSFPTMC&pg=PT115&lpg=PT115&dq=Antonino+Giuffr%C3%A8+was+wanted+since+1993&source=bl&ots=4AT1TL-I4C&sig=ACfU3U1obG3EhxL1XySoFeZVoRaU98l80w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwis6-i9kLHmAhUNvZ4KHdvXA7IQ6AEwAHoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Antonino%20Giuffr%C3%A8%20was%20wanted%20since%201993&f=false|title=The Honored Society: A Portrait of Italy's Most Powerful Mafia|last=Reski|first=Petra|date=2013-01-08|publisher=PublicAffairs|isbn=978-1-56858-969-5|language=en}}</ref> Giuffr\u00e8 was trained as an agricultural sciences specialist. His rise in the Mafia ran parallel to the ascension of the Corleonesi clan headed by [[Salvatore Riina]]. He became the head of the [[mandamento (Sicilian Mafia)|mandamento]] of Caccamo.He was captured by the police on 16 April 2002.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=_W6WBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA330&lpg=PA330&dq=antonino+giuffr%C3%A8+was+captured&source=bl&ots=gPDEGxFSqW&sig=ACfU3U338eQUeRQ1_gtYstTck5GkRR1Vkw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi0rqv3krHmAhUXup4KHZfYCgIQ6AEwFXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=antonino%20giuffr%C3%A8%20was%20captured&f=false|title=Cosa Nostra: A History of the Sicilian Mafia|last=Dickie|first=John|date=2015-03-31|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4668-9305-4|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Syed Abdul Karim Tunda]]\n|49\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|India|1994}}}}\n|Syed Abdul Karim, alias \"Tunda\", was an alleged bomb maker of terror outfit [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]], and was accused of masterminding over 40 bombings in India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-08-17/india/41420067_1_jammu-and-kashmir-terror-outfit-major-terror-attacks |work=Times of India |date=8 August 2013 |title=Jammu and Kashmir terror outfit major attacks}}Who is Abdul Karim Tunda?</ref> He was arrested by Indian authorities on 16 August at the India-Nepal border. However, the exact timing of this arrest is disputed with various versions being reported.<ref>[http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/08/the-controversy-over-arrest-of-abdul-karim-tunda/ The Controversy over Arrest of Abdul Karim Tunda]</ref><references group=\"News\" /> Later, he received a clean chit by a Delhi court in all four cases against him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Abdul Karim Tunda gets clean chit in all four cases|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/delhi-court-discharges-let-bomb-expert-abdul-karim-tunda/article8318199.ece|accessdate=7 March 2016|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|date=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Giuseppe Giorgi]]\n|35\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|1994}}}}\n|Giorgi is an [[Italians|Italian]] criminal belonging to the [['Ndrangheta]], a criminal organization in [[Calabria]]. After having been a fugitive for 23 years and been included on the [[list of most wanted fugitives in Italy]] he was captured in his home town [[San Luca]] on 2 June 2017.<ref name=rep020617>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2017/06/02/news/_ndrangheta_i_carabinieri_arrestano_latitante_giuseppe_giorgi-167026735/ 'Ndrangheta, catturato a San Luca il latitante Giuseppe Giorgi. E c'\u00e8 chi gli bacia le mani], La Repubblica, 2 June 2017</ref><ref name=occrp020617>[https://www.occrp.org/en/daily/6534-italian-carabinieri-arrest-major-ndrangheta-drug-boss Italian Carabinieri Arrest Major 'Ndrangheta Drug Boss], [[Organized Crime and Corruption Reporting Project]] (OCCRP), 2 June 2017</ref>\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Whitey Bulger]]\n|65\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1994}}}}\n|Bulger was an [[Irish-American]] [[organized crime]] [[Boss (crime)|boss]] and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] [[informant]] who led the [[Winter Hill Gang]] in the [[Winter Hill, Somerville, Massachusetts|Winter Hill]] neighborhood of [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]], [[Massachusetts]], a city directly northwest of Boston.<ref name=\"NYT-2011-06-23-Nagorney\">{{cite news| date = 23 June 2011| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/23/us/23bulger.html| title = Whitey Bulger Is Arrested in California| last1 = Nagorney | first1 = Adam | first2 = Ian | last2 = Lovett| work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/24/us/24southie.html| title = In South Boston, Mixed Memories of Whitey Bulger | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=Katie | last=Zezima | date=23 June 2011}}</ref> On 23 December 1994, Bulger fled the [[Boston]] area and went into hiding after his former FBI handler, [[John Connolly (FBI)|John Connolly]], tipped him off about a pending [[Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act|RICO]] indictment against him. Bulger remained at large for 16 years. Bulger was finally apprehended along with his longtime girlfriend [[Catherine Greig]] outside an apartment complex in [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]], [[California]] on 22 June 2011. Bulger given two life sentences and sent to jail and then transferred to different jails. By then he was in a wheelchair, and was found dead on 30 October 2018, at the age of 89. He was killed by inmates within hours of his arrival at Hazelton.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/30/us/james-whitey-bulger-killed/index.html|title=Boston gangster James 'Whitey' Bulger killed in West Virginia prison a day after transfer|work=[[CNN]]|last=Sanchez|first=Ray|date=30 October 2018|access-date=31 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/30/obituaries/whitey-bulger-dead.html|title=Whitey Bulger Is Dead in Prison at 89; Long-Hunted Boston Mob Boss|work=The New York Times|last=McFadden|first=Robert D.|authorlink=Robert D. McFadden|date=30 October 2018|access-date=31 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/local_coverage/2018/11/prison_drops_visits_after_whitey_bulger_slaying|title=Prison drops visits after Whitey Bulger slaying|newspaper=Boston Herald|access-date=7 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105054149/http://www.bostonherald.com/news/local_coverage/2018/11/prison_drops_visits_after_whitey_bulger_slaying|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|1995\n|[[Sebastiano Pelle]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|1995}}}}\n|Pelle, an [[Italians|Italian]] criminal belonging to the [['Ndrangheta]], a [[Mafia]]-type organization in [[Calabria]] (Italy). He was wanted since 1995 for membership of a criminal association aimed at trafficking weapons and drugs internationally, as well as for other crimes. He has been sentenced to 14 years in prison. In 2006, investigations were extended internationally for his [[extradition]].<ref name=\"interior_bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/app_notizia_20504.html |title=Ministero Dell'Interno \u2013 Approfondimento |publisher=Interno.it |date=2006-12-27 |accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/ministero/dipartimenti/dip_pubblica_sicurezza/direzione_centrale_della_polizia_criminale/scheda_16056.html |title=Ministero Dell'Interno \u2013 Scheda Editoriale |publisher=Interno.it |date=2005-01-27 |accessdate=2011-02-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107154821/http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/ministero/dipartimenti/dip_pubblica_sicurezza/direzione_centrale_della_polizia_criminale/scheda_16056.html |archivedate=2011-01-07 }}</ref> He was on the \"[[list of most wanted fugitives in Italy]]\" of the ministry of the Interior, until his arrest on 9 November 2011, in [[Reggio Calabria]].<ref name=cds101111>[http://www.corriere.it/International/english/articoli/2011/11/10/ndrangheta-arrested%20.shtml 'Ndrangheta Mobster Arrested After 16 Years On Run], Corriere della Sera, 10 November 2011</ref> \n|-\n|1996\n|[[Agust\u00edn V\u00e1squez Mendoza]]\n|21\u201322\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Mexico|1996}}}}\n|Mendoza is a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] citizen<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/115371.htm|title=Agustin Vasquez-Mendoza|website=U.S. Department of State|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> who was sought for four years in the late 1990s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ondeathrowusa.com/2017/06/agustin-vasquez-mendoza-fbi-most-wanted.html|title=Agust\u00edn V\u00e1squez Mendoza FBI Most Wanted|website=On Death Row USA|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> by the [[United States]] [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) as the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 1990s|445th FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitive]]<ref name=\"445. Agustin Vasquez-Mendoza\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/topten-history/hires_images/FBI-445-AgustinVasquezMendoza.jpg/view|title=445. Agustin Vasquez-Mendoza|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> for his alleged participation in a drug conspiracy which led to the death of a U.S. [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) Special Agent. He was captured in [[Puebla]] by [[Mexico|Mexican]] authorities in the summer of 2000.<ref name=\"445. Agustin Vasquez-Mendoza\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=0FlIEUy0W6IC&pg=PA186&lpg=PA186&dq=Agust%C3%ADn+V%C3%A1squez+Mendoza&source=bl&ots=-AcFOJhcpz&sig=ACfU3U1Uvtkn9xYBtHW7KTrHpoDotpSMuQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjdmLqe2ZXlAhXWu54KHeqXDqA4ChDoATAHegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=Agust%C3%ADn%20V%C3%A1squez%20Mendoza&f=false|title=Drug Enforcement Administration: A Tradition of Excellence, 1973\u20132008|last=Administration|first=United States Drug Enforcement|date=2008|publisher=Drug Enforcement Administration|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1996\n|[[Leslie Isben Rogge]]\n|54\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|1996}}}}\n|Rogge is an [[Americans|American]] [[bank robber]]. He was the first FBI Top Ten criminal to be apprehended due to the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lesrogge.com|title=Wanted: Gentleman Bank Robber \u2013 Nish Publishing|work=lesrogge.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130127161459/http://www.lesrogge.com/|archivedate=2013-01-27}}</ref> Rogge was imprisoned at the [[United States Penitentiary, Leavenworth|United States Penitentiary]] in [[Leavenworth, Kansas]], in the 1970s for car theft and grand larceny. He was later convicted and sentenced to 25 years for a 1984 bank robbery in [[Key Largo, Florida]]. In September 1985, he bribed a corrections officer and escaped from prison in [[Moscow, Idaho]]. Following his escape, he went on to commit additional bank robberies, including one at an [[Exchange Bank (El Dorado, Arkansas)|Exchange Bank]] branch in [[El Dorado, Arkansas]], and at a bank in [[High Point, North Carolina]], in 1986.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=UAqfDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA162&lpg=PA162&dq=leslie+isben+rogge+want+to+rob+a+bank+in+north+carolina&source=bl&ots=pqjmQqZfz9&sig=ACfU3U3x4FArE9-4mjL8YMcnth6owB40WQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwxLOX04jlAhVIpZ4KHZ3_DqUQ6AEwDHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=leslie%20isben%20rogge%20want%20to%20rob%20a%20bank%20in%20north%20carolina&f=false|title=On the Lam: A History of Hunting Fugitives in America|last=Clark|first=Jerry|last2=Palattella|first2=Ed|date=2019-09-17|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442262591|language=en}}</ref> On 19 May 1996, Rogge surrendered at the [[United States Embassy]] in [[Guatemala]], after Guatemalan authorities had launched a manhunt upon being tipped off by someone who saw Rogge's photo on the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] website,<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Fugitive Surrenders In Guatemala After Photo Is Seen On Internet |publisher=Associated Press |date=19 May 1996}}</ref> and is now in jail.\n|-\n|1996\n|[[Man Haron Monis]]\n|32\n|{{Flag|Iran|1996}}\n|Monis was an Iranian-born refugee and Australian citizen who took hostages in [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|a siege at the Lindt Chocolate Caf\u00e9]] at [[Martin Place]], [[Sydney]] [[Man Haron Monis#cite%20note-citizenship-2|[2]]]<nowiki/>on 15 December 2014, lasting for 17 hours, until the early hours of the following morning. The siege resulted in the death of Monis and two hostages. While Monis had a warrant out for his arrest in [[Iran]], he sought political asylum in [[Australia]] in 1996, which was granted in 2001.[[Man Haron Monis#cite%20note-7|[7]]]\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1999-11-24\"|1999\n|[[Fidel Urbina]]\n|23\u201324\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Mexico|1999}}}}\n|Urbina is a Mexican national former fugitive who was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list in June 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/06/fidel-urbina-chicago-murd_n_1573997.html|title=Fidel Urbina, Chicago Murder Suspect, Added To FBI's 10 'Most Wanted' List|date=2012-06-06|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> Urbina had been the subject of a manhunt since 1999 despite reported sightings in Mexico. A $100,000 reward was offered for information leading to Urbina's arrest. Urbina was captured on 22 September 2016 in [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua, Mexico]] after 17 years on the run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/chicago/news/press-releases/fbi-top-ten-most-wanted-fugitive-fidel-urbina-arrested |title=FBI \u2014 FBI Top Ten Most Wanted Fugitive Fidel Urbina Arrested |publisher=Fbi.gov |date=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-fugitive-captured-met-20170427-story.html|title=Longtime fugitive ordered held without bond on murder, rape charges|last=Crepeau|first=Megan|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/Merciless-Chicago-Man-on-Run-From-FBI-For-17-Years--Captured-in-Mexico--394610431.html|title='Merciless' Chicago Man On Top 10 Most Wanted List Nabbed|last=Ray|first=Richard|website=NBC Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2001-11-01\"|2001\n|[[Osama bin Laden]]\n|44\n||{{nowrap|{{Flag|Pakistan|2001}}}}\n|Bin Laden, also rendered Usama bin Ladin, was a founder of the [[pan-Islamic]] militant organization {{nowrap|[[al-Qaeda]]}}. He was a [[Saudi Arabia]]n until 1994 (stateless thereafter), a member of the wealthy [[bin Laden family]], and an ethnic Yemeni [[Kindah|Kindite]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Yemen still close to al Qaeda's heart |author=Scheuer, Michael |url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/JB07Ak01.html |newspaper=Asia Times Online |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref> From 2001 to 2011, bin Laden was a major target of the [[United States]], as the FBI offered a $25&nbsp;million bounty in their [[Search for Osama bin Laden|search for him]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/usama-bin-laden |title=Fbi \u2013 Usama Bin Laden |publisher=Fbi.gov |date=7 August 1998 |accessdate=15 May 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515104052/http://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/usama-bin-laden |archivedate=15 May 2011 }}</ref> He had gone into hiding after 11 September 2001 attacks on the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/06/osama-bin-laden-family-on-the-run-after-9-11|title=Osama bin Laden's family on the run: 'I never stopped praying our lives might return to normal'|last=Scott-Clark|first=Cathy|date=2017-05-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-31|last2=Levy|first2=Adrian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 2 May 2011, [[Death of Osama bin Laden|bin Laden was shot and killed]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sofmag.com/navy-seal-who-shot-bin-laden-rob-oneill-butte-montana |title=The Navy SEAL Who Shot Bin Laden Is: Rob O'Neill From Butte Montana |date=6 November 2014 |work=Soldier of Fortune Magazine |access-date=8 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141203151430/http://www.sofmag.com/navy-seal-who-shot-bin-laden-rob-oneill-butte-montana |archivedate=3 December 2014}}</ref> by United States Navy SEALs inside a [[Osama bin Laden's compound in Abbottabad|private residential compound]] in [[Abbottabad]], where he lived with a local family from [[Waziristan]], during a covert operation conducted by members of the [[United States Naval Special Warfare Development Group]] and [[Central Intelligence Agency]] [[Special Activities Division|SAD/SOG]] operators on the orders of U.S. President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Technology/uss-carl-vinson-osama-bin-ladens-burial-sea/story?id=13510831 |title=USS Carl Vinson: Osama Bin Laden's Burial at Sea |publisher=ABC News |location=USA |accessdate=1 May 2011 |date=1 May 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504142851/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/uss-carl-vinson-osama-bin-ladens-burial-sea/story?id=13510831 |archivedate=4 May 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|[[Robert Durst]]\n|56\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2001}}}}\n|Durst is an American [[real estate]] [[heir]], the son of [[New York City]] mogul [[Seymour Durst]], and the elder brother of [[Douglas Durst]], head of the [[Durst Organization]]. He is suspected of having murdered three individuals in different states who includes Kathleen McCormack Durst, his first wife, who disappeared in [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1982. On 9 October 2001, Durst was arrested in Galveston shortly after body parts belonging to his elderly neighbor, Morris Black, were found floating in [[Galveston Bay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/robert-durst-timeline-life-alleged-crimes/story?id=29668632|title=Robert Durst: A Timeline of His Life and Alleged Crimes|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> He was released on $300,000 [[Recognizance|bail]] the next day. Durst missed a court hearing on 16 October 2001 and a warrant was issued for his arrest on a charge of [[bail jumping]]. On 30 November 2001, he was caught inside a [[Wegmans]] supermarket in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]], after trying to shoplift [[Band-Aid]]s, a newspaper and a chicken-salad sandwich with roasted red peppers on a pumpernickel baguette, even though he had $500 cash in his pocket. He was later sent to jail.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/oct/26/multimillionaire-robert-durst-to-be-tried-for-of-susan-burman|title=Robert Durst, subject of HBO's The Jinx, to be tried for 2000 murder|agency=Associated Press|date=2018-10-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|[[Christian Longo]]\n|26\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2001}}}}\n|Longo is an American murderer who committed his crimes in the U.S. state of [[Oregon]].<ref name='NYT'>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/17/us/oregon-man-guilty-of-killing-his-family-gets-death-sentence.html|title=Oregon Man Guilty Of Killing His Family Gets Death Sentence|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 April 2003|accessdate=13 September 2018|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He was married to Mary Jane Baker at age 19 and they had three children together. He and his family often encountered financial difficulties due to his reckless spending habits.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Johnny|last=Dodd|url=http://www.people.com/article/true-story-real-life-christian-longo-speaks-out|title=Murderer Depicted in Movie ''True Story'' Tells PEOPLE: 'I Don't Feel I Can Be Redeemed'|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> After the body of Longo's four-year-old son, Zachery, was found on 19 December 2001, divers located that of his three-year-old daughter, Sadie. Those of Mary Jane and their two-year-old daughter, Madison, were found five days later. By that time, Longo was wanted in connection with the murder of Mary Jane and their three children. He later disappeared and was captured on 13 January 2001. He was taken into U.S. custody at [[George Bush Intercontinental Airport]] a day later.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/charles-mathews-special-agent-in-charge-of-the-fbi-in-oregon-announces-that-fbi-agents-have-transported-christian-michael-longo-back-to-the-united-states|title=FBI Agents Transport Christian Michael Longo Back to the United States|date=14 January 2002|accessdate=22 December 2011|publisher=FBI.gov}}</ref> He was sentenced to death in 2003,<ref>{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Duin|title=His victim's sister calls Christian Longo a 'monster' who won't let the family heal|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/oregonian/steve_duin/index.ssf/2011/04/his_victims_sister_calls_chris.html|newspaper=[[The Oregonian]]|publisher=Oregonian Media Group|location=Portland, Oregon|date=2 May 2011|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> but has not yet been executed.\n|-\n|2002\n|[[Kemar Jarrett]]\n|19\u201320\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Jamaica|2002}}}}\n|Jarrett, a [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] criminal who is a member of a gang called the [[Yardies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.betterworldbooks.com/product/detail/london-street-gangs-1157871801|title=Buy New & Used Books Online with Free Shipping|last=Books|first=Better World|website=Better World Books|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> and who in 2002 was listed as the number one criminal on the top ten most wanted list of criminals in Jamaica by the [[Jamaica Constabulary Force]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Jamaica Constabulary Force |authorlink=Jamaica Constabulary Force |title=Cops seek public's help in nabbing most wanted men |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20020422/news/news1.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020808234212/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20020422/news/news1.html|newspaper=[[Jamaica Gleaner]] |date=22 April 2002 |archivedate=2002-08-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> He disappeared in April 2002 and was captured on 18 February 2004 after being deported from the United Kingdom as a result related drug charges that he was charged with, and is now in prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20040221/news/news2.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621172633/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20040221/news/news2.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-06-21|title=Jamaica Gleaner - Most wanted behind bars - Saturday {{!}} February 21, 2004|date=2007-06-21|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2002-01-01\"|2002\n|[[Velupillai Prabhakaran]]\n|data-sort-value=\"048\"|48\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Sri Lanka|2002}}}}\n|Prabhakaran was the founder and leader of the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]], a militant organization that sought to create an independent [[Tamil Eelam|Tamil state]] in the north and east of [[Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Tamil Tigers |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Tamil-Tigers |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc. |accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> Wanted by the Sri Lankan government in 2002, and is known to have been killed on 18 May 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1899590,00.html|title=Prabhakaran: The Life and Death of a Tiger|last=THOTTAM|first=JYOTI|date=19 May 2009|work=Time|access-date=2017-09-15|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2003\"-01-01\"|2003\n|[[Saddam Hussein]]\n|69\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Iraq|2003}}}}\n|Hussein was [[President of Iraq]] from 16 July 1979 until 9 April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/baghdad_04-09-03.html |title=Online NewsHour Update: Coalition Says Iraqi Regime Has Lost Control of Baghdad&nbsp;\u2014 9 April 2003 |publisher=Pbs.org |date=9 April 2003 |accessdate=13 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201163438/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/baghdad_04-09-03.html |archivedate=1 December 2010 }}</ref> A leading member of the revolutionary [[Ba'ath Party|Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party]], and later, the [[Ba'ath Party (Iraqi-dominated faction)|Baghdad-based Ba'ath Party]] and its regional organization the [[Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party \u2013 Iraq Region|Iraqi Ba'ath Party]]\u2014which espoused [[Ba'athism]], a mix of [[Arab nationalism]] and [[Arab socialism|socialism]]\u2014Saddam played a key role in the 1968 coup (later referred to as the [[17 July Revolution]]) that brought the party to power in Iraq. He went into hiding, but was captured and on 5 November 2006, Saddam Hussein stood trial and was found guilty of the Dujail massacre. He was sentenced to death by [[hanging]] and executed on 30 December 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/nation-world/2018/12/saddam-hussein-captured-15-years-ago-in-iraq.html|title=Saddam Hussein captured 15 years ago in Iraq|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2003\"-01-22\"|2003\n|[[Andrew Luster]]\n|39\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2003}}}}\n|Luster was an American fugitive who was convicted of sexual assault. In 2000, he was arrested when a student at a local college told police that she had been raped at Luster's home, and later disappeared in January 2003. Upon investigation, police charged Luster with drugging three women with the date-rape drug [[GHB (drug)|GHB]], sexually assaulting them, and video-taping the assaults, having found videotapes of the assaults when they searched his home.<ref name=NYT2>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/08/us/cosmetics-heir-is-missing-as-his-rape-trial-proceeds.html | work=The New York Times | first=Charlie | last=Leduff | title=Cosmetics Heir Is Missing As His Rape Trial Proceeds | date=8 January 2003}}</ref> After paying $1 million bail, Luster failed to appear in court to defend himself against the charges in January 2003. Luster was convicted ''[[Trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' and sentenced to 124 years in prison, which was later reduced to 50 years<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/oct/04/2|title=Max Factor heir to pay damages|work=the Guardian|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> in June 2003, after he was captured by American [[bounty hunter]] [[Duane Chapman|Duane \"Dog\" Chapman]] in [[Puerto Vallarta]], [[Mexico]].\n|-\n|2004\n|[[Marco Di Lauro]]\n|24\u201325\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|2004}}}}\n|Di Lauro is an Italian [[Camorra|Camorrista]] and member of the [[Di Lauro clan]] from Naples. He was listed on \"[[List of most wanted fugitives in Italy|Italy's most wanted list]]\" since 2004, for Camorra association and other crimes. On 17 November 2006, an international warrant was issued against him, to be arrested for extradition.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/7_11_2007_latitante_di_lauro_marco_.html Direzione centrale della Polizia Criminale \u2013 \"Programma Speciale di Ricerca\" \u2013 Di Lauro Marco] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207092848/http://interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/polizia/7_11_2007_latitante_di_lauro_marco_.html |date=7 February 2009 }}</ref> After having been a fugitive for 14 years and been included on the [[list of most wanted fugitives in Italy]], he was captured in [[Naples]] on 2 March 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/03/super-fugitive-mafia-boss-arrested-after-14-years-on-the-run |title= \nSuper fugitive mafia boss arrested after 14 years on the run |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |language=English |date= 3 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2004\n|[[Raffaele Diana]]\n|65\u201366\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|2004}}}}\n|Diana, an Italian [[Camorra|Camorrista]] and senior boss of the [[Casalesi clan]] from [[Caserta]], who was eventually arrested on 2 May 2009, after having been on the run for five years. He was captured by officers of the mobile team of Caserta in an apartment in [[Casal di Principe]], near Caserta, where he was hidden in a bunker of cement produced in the stairwell.<ref name=\"Raffolito\">{{in lang|it}} [http://www.interno.it/mininterno/export/sites/default/it/sezioni/sala_stampa/notizie/antimafia/0535_2009_05_04_arresto_diana.html Arrestato a Casal di Principe il boss della camorra Raffaele Diana] \u2013 Ministero dell'Interno, 3 May 2009</ref> He was found in possession of two loaded pistols and some ammunition. A copy of the [[Gospel]], a book of [[Padre Pio]] of Pietrelcina, a copy of ''[[The Godfather]]'' and ''[[Il Capo dei Capi]]'' were also found. Diana's arrest was believed by law enforcement to have delivered a huge blow to the Casalesi.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/2009/04/sezioni/cronaca/camorra-9/arresto-diana/arresto-diana.html Casalesi, arrestato Diana, superlatitante da 5 anni], La Repubblica, 3 May 2009</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2005-01-01\"|2005\n|[[Joseph Lombardo]]\t\n|76\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2005}}}}\n|On 25 April 2005, Lombardo, along with 13 other defendants, was [[indicted]] as part of the federal government's [[Operation Family Secrets]] investigation, which lifted the veil on 18 killings since the 1970s that federal investigators had attributed to the Outfit. Lombardo was indicted for his role in at least one murder, as well as for running a racket based on [[illegal gambling]], loan sharking and murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipsn.org/mob_arrests-2005/us_drops_hammer_on_mob.htm|title=U.S. drops hammer on who's who of mob|website=Ipsn.org}}</ref> As federal agents rounded up the 14 defendants in April 2005, they realized that Lombardo had disappeared, who became a [[fugitive]] after they issued a federal [[arrest warrant]].<ref name=warrant/> The FBI then offered a $20,000 reward for information leading to Lombardo's capture.<ref name=warrant>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipsn.org/mob_arrests-2005/wanted_joseph_lombardo.htm|title=WANTED: JOSEPH LOMBARDO|website=www.ipsn.org}}</ref> On  13 January 2006, after over eight months at large, a bearded, unkempt Lombardo, was captured by FBI agents outside the [[Elmwood Park, Illinois]] home of his longtime friend Dominic Calarco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/mob/499770,CST-NWS-mob07.stng|title=\"'The Clown' hid near police station\"|website=Suntimes.com|access-date=21 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824120054/http://www.suntimes.com/news/mob/499770,CST-NWS-mob07.stng|archive-date=24 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Federal agents had been tipped off to Lombardo's whereabouts after Lombardo had visited dead Outfit mobster [[Tony Spilotro]]'s dentist brother, Patrick Spilotro, for an [[abscessed tooth]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coen |first1=Jeff |title=How dentist's tip led to Lombardo's arrest |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2007-08-08-0708071148-story.html |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=19 October 2019 |date=8 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=John L. |title=Dentist-brother\u2019s vow helped nab suspects in death of \u2018Tough Tony\u2019 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/dentist-brothers-vow-helped-nab-suspects-in-death-of-tough-tony/ |publisher=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |accessdate=19 October 2019 |date=19 August 2007}}</ref> On 10 September 2007, Lombardo was convicted of racketeering, extortion, [[loan sharking]] and murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/5-men-found-guilty-in-chicago-mob-trial/|title=5 Men Found Guilty In Chicago Mob Trial|website=Cbsnews.com}}</ref> On 27 September 2007, the same jury found Lombardo guilty of the 1974 Seifert murder. In 2009, Lombardo, seated in a wheelchair, was sentenced to [[life in prison]] for the convictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/ct-met-joey-lombardo-family-secrets-20180809-story.html|title=Serving life sentence, ex-mobster Joey 'the Clown' Lombardo writes letter asking he be appointed a lawyer|first=Jason|last=Meisner|website=Chicagotribune.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/|title=Chicago Breaking News \u2013 Chicago Tribune|website=Chicagotribune.com}}</ref> He served his sentence at [[ADX Florence]] supermax prison, where he died on 19 October 2019, at the age of 90.<ref name=life>{{cite web |title=Chicago Mobster Joey \u2018The Clown\u2019 Lombardo Dies While Serving Life Sentence |url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2019/10/20/reputed-mobster-joey-the-clown-lombardo-dies-while-serving-life-sentence/ |website=CBS Chicago |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2006\n|[[Richard Lee McNair]]\n|47\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2006}}}}\n|McNair, an [[Americans|American]] convicted murderer known for his multiple escapes and avoiding being captured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allthatsinteresting.com/richard-lee-mcnair|title=A Prison Inmate Mailed Himself To Freedom \u2013 Then Convinced A Cop He Wasn't The Escapee [VIDEO]|date=2018-03-20|website=All That's Interesting|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> His most recent escape was on 5 April 2006 when he escaped from a [[United States Penitentiary, Pollock|United States Penitentiary]] in [[Pollock, Louisiana]]. He was captured on 24 October 2007, when was seen near [[Nash Creek, New Brunswick]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://byronchristopher.org/2015/01/12/was-carl-bordelon-railroaded/|title=Was Carl Bordelon Railroaded?|last=Christopher|first=Byron|date=2015-01-12|website=Byron Christopher|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> and is now serving two life sentences in prison.\n|-\n|2006\n|[[Gianni Nicchi]]\n|24\u201325\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Italy|2006}}}}\n|Nicchi, who is nicknamed {{lang|scn|'u picciutteddu}} (\"the little boy\") is a member of the [[Sicilian Mafia]]. He is considered to be one of the leading mafiosi of Cosa Nostra in [[Palermo]] regardless of his young age. Before his arrest on 5 December 2009.<ref name=bbc051209>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8397622.stm Mafia 'second-in-command' arrested in Italy], BBC News, 5 December 2009</ref> he was on the \"[[List of most wanted fugitives in Italy|most wanted list]]\" of the Italian ministry of the Interior since 2006.<ref name=rep051209>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/2009/12/sezioni/cronaca/mafia-11/nicchi-arresto/nicchi-arresto.html Mafia, presi due superlatitanti], La Repubblica, December 5, 2009</ref> He is currently locked up in a special security prison in [[L'Aquila]] under the strict [[Article 41-bis prison regime]] regulation. \n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2007\"-01-01\"|2007\n|[[Liu Sung-pan]]\n|75\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Taiwan|2007}}}}\n|Liu was a Taiwanese politician who served as the [[President of the Legislative Yuan]] from 1992 to 1999. In July 2003 he was sentenced to five years imprisonment and NT$30 million fine for corruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former speaker convicted|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2003/07/12/2003059143|accessdate=14 May 2016|work=Taipei Times|date=12 July 2003}}</ref> After being declared a fugitive he fled to China in 2007 and died in 2016.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2008-01-01\"|2008\n|[[Eduardo Ravelo]]\n|41\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2008}}}}\n|Ravelo, leader of the [[Barrio Azteca]] gang, and also a fugitive wanted on several charges related to drugs and organized crime, was last seen in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/fbis-top-ten-most-wanted-9642372|title=FBI's Top Ten Most Wanted: Nightmarish tales of America's most feared criminals|last=Robson|first=Steve|date=2017-01-18|work=mirror|accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref> On 20 October 2009, he was named by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] as the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2000s|493rd fugitive to be placed]] on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Ten Most-Wanted list]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/fbis-top-10-most-wanted-fugitives/7|title=FBI's Top Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|date=2017-04-18|accessdate=2017-07-17|language=en}}</ref> On 26 June 2018, the FBI announced that Ravelo and several other Barrio Azteca gang members had been arrested during a police raid in Mexico.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kvia.com/crime/breaking-alleged-leader-of-barrio-azteca-gang-arrested-in-mexico/759296738|title=Alleged Barrio Azteca leader, FBI Most Wanted, arrested|last=Corral|first=Jose|date=2018-06-27|work=KVIA|access-date=2018-06-27|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627025401/http://www.kvia.com/crime/breaking-alleged-leader-of-barrio-azteca-gang-arrested-in-mexico/759296738|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Christopher Daniel Gay]]\n|34\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2009}}}}\n|Gay who is nicknamed \"Little Houdini\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/man-known-as-little-houdini-accused-of-more-thefts|title=\u2018Little Houdini' accused of more thefts|date=2018-11-15|website=WTVF|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> is an American habitual car thief and repeat escapee from custody. In 2007 he made major news after he stole the tour bus of country music singer [[Crystal Gayle]] after an escape.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2009/0307/p01s01-ussc.html|title=Tennessee's 'Little Houdini' revives the outlaw legend|date=2009-03-07|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2020-01-02|issn=0882-7729}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/101122|title=Escaped prisoner allegedly steals Crystal Gayle's bus to see his mom|date=2007-01-28|website=www.digitaljournal.com|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Gay's last escape was on the afternoon of 3 March 2009 while being transported from [[Orlando, Florida]] to [[Coffee County, Tennessee]] by the police, after he was able to free himself of his restraints after which he had fled for the car that he was being held captive in. Before this took place he had been arrested and held for [[larceny]] of a [[Wal-Mart]] truck.<ref name=\"AP fox\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,504452,00.html|title=Prisoner Known as 'Little Houdini' Escapes From Police|date=2009-03-04|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> Gay was captured in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/little-houdini-arrested-after-high-speed-chase|title='Little Houdini' arrested after high speed chase|date=2019-01-29|website=WTVF|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Semion Mogilevich]]\n|63\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Russia|2009}}}}\n|Mogilevich, a Ukrainian-born, Russian [[organized crime]] boss, believed by European and United States federal law enforcement agencies to be the \"[[Capo di tutti capi|boss of bosses]]\" of most [[Russian Mafia]] syndicates in the world.<ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Misha Glenny |last=Glenny |first=Misha |year=2008 |title=McMafia: A Journey Through the Global Criminal Underworld |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |pages=[https://archive.org/details/mcmafiajourneyth00glen/page/72 72\u201373] |isbn=978-1-4000-4411-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/mcmafiajourneyth00glen/page/72 }}</ref> Mogilevich is believed to direct a vast criminal empire and is described by the FBI as \"the most dangerous mobster in the world.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Petrostate: Putin, Power, and the New Russia |first=Marshall I. |last=Goldman |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-19-534073-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/petrostateputinp00gold }}</ref> He has been accused by the FBI of \"weapons trafficking, contract murders, extortion, drug trafficking, and prostitution on an international scale,\"<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.slate.com/blogs/crime/2013/08/05/semion_mogilevich_fbi_ten_most_wanted_list_this_obese_mob_boss_is_twice.html| title = This Obese Mob Boss Is Twice the Villain Whitey Bulger Ever Was| author = Peters, Justin| date = 5 August 2013| accessdate = 4 April 2014| magazine = Slate}}</ref> had disappeared and was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] on 23 October 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/2009/october/mogilevich_102109|title=New Top Ten \u2013 Global Con Artist|website=FBI|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> He was removed from the list on 17 December 2015 and now lives freely in [[Moscow]] as he is no longer wanted by the police.\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Colton Harris Moore]]\n|19\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2010}}}}\n|Moore, an American former fugitive, was charged with the theft of hundreds of thousands of dollars in property, including several small aircraft, boats, and multiple cars, all committed while still a teenager.<ref name=\"CNN-20100706-falcon\">{{cite news|last=Falcon|first=Gabriel|title='Barefoot bandit' faces indictment|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/07/06/barefoot.bandit.plane.theft/|accessdate=7 July 2010|publisher=CNN|date=6 July 2010}}</ref> While on the run he was captured in July 2010, but years later was released on [[parole]].\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Ricardo Asch]]\n|54\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Argentina|2011}}}}\n|Asch is an [[obstetrician]], [[Gynaecology|gynecologist]], [[Endocrinology|endocrinologist]], and [[Argentines|Argentine]] [[fugitive]] who was imprisoned, but was released on bail in early 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2011/03/23/doctor-accused-in-uci-fertility-scandal-released-from-mexican-jail/ |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Doctor Accused In UCI Fertility Scandal Released From Mexican Jail |publisher=[[CBS]] Los Angeles |date=March 23, 2011 |accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref> while he was in Mexico, but fled the country, and has now been caught after being on the run for eight years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/ReproductiveHealth/fugitive-fertility-doctor-ricardo-asch-arrested-mexico/story?id=12492575|title=Fertility Doctor on the Run Arrested in Mexico|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]]\n|66\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|Russia|2012}}}}\n|Berezovsky, also known as \"Platon Elenin\",<ref name=\"Pomerantsev\">{{cite journal |last=Pomerantsev |first=Peter |date=25 April 2013 |title=Berezovsky's Last Days |url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v35/n08/peter-pomerantsev/diary |journal=[[London Review of Books]] |volume=35 |issue=8 |pages=38\u201339 |accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> was a Russian [[business oligarch]], government official, engineer and mathematician.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hoffman |first=David E. |author-link=David E. Hoffman |date=13 September 2011 |title=The Oligarchs: Wealth and power in the new Russia |url=http://www.publicaffairsbooks.com/book/paperback/the-oligarchs/9781610390705 |location=New York |publisher=[[PublicAffairs]] |page=130 |isbn=9781610390705 |accessdate=9 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104034214/http://www.publicaffairsbooks.com/book/paperback/the-oligarchs/9781610390705 |archive-date=4 January 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2012, Berezovsky lost a London [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] case he brought over the ownership of the major oil producer [[Sibneft]], against [[Roman Abramovich]], in which he sought over \u00a33 billion in damages. The court concluded that Berezovsky had never been a co-owner of Sibneft.<ref name=\"independent-20120831\">{{cite news |last=Peck |first=Tom |date=31 August 2012 |title=Berezovsky humbled by verdict that leaves reputation in tatters|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/berezovsky-humbled-by-verdict-that-leaves-reputation-in-tatters-8099260.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> After that he disappeared and became a fugitive who was wanted by Russia. He was found dead on 23 March 2013,<ref>{{cite news |last=Barrett |first=David |date=23 March 2013 |title=Russian oligarch Boris Berezovsky found dead in his bath |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/russia/9950107/Russian-oligarch-Boris-Berezovsky-found-dead-in-his-bath.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref> from what might be a [[suicide]], and is no longer sought by the police.\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Eric Justin Toth]]\n|31\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2012}}}}\n|Toth is an American former [[fugitive]] convicted of possessing and producing [[child pornography]]. On 10 April 2012, Toth replaced [[Osama bin Laden]] on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|FBI Ten Most Wanted list]] as the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2010s|495th fugitive]] to be placed on that list by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]. Toth was captured by the Nicaraguan police in April 2013 in [[Estel\u00ed]], a northern city of Nicaragua. He was immediately extradited to the United States to face trial,<ref>{{cite news|title=Eric Justin Toth, one of FBI\u2019s \u2018most wanted,\u2019 captured in Nicaragua|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/eric-justin-toth-fbi-wanted-captured-nicaragua-article-1.1324396|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=NY Daily News|date=22 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/washingtondc/press-releases/2013/fbi-top-ten-fugitive-now-in-custody|title=FBI Top Ten Fugitive Now in Custody|work=FBI}}</ref> and  in March 2014, Toth was sentenced in federal court to 25 years in prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/washingtondc/press-releases/2014/former-teacher-sentenced-to-25-years-in-prison-for-production-of-child-pornography-and-other-charges|title=Former Teacher Sentenced to 25 Years in Prison for Production of Child Pornography and Other Charges|website=FBI|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Christopher Dorner shootings and manhunt|Christopher Dorner]]\n|33\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2013}}}}\n|Dorner, was a [[Los Angeles]] police officer in [[Orange County, California]] who began a series of shootings on 3 February, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/christopher-dorner-live-killing/story?id=18504028|title=Christopher Dorner Let Some Live While Killing Others|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> He disappeared leading to a manhunt. This concluded on 13 February 2013, with confirmation that human remains, found in a fire destroyed cabin, were his.<ref>{{cite web |title = Christopher Dorner Manhunt: Charred Human Remains Found in Burned Cabin |url = https://abcnews.go.com/US/christopher-dorner-manhunt-charred-human-remains-found-burned/story?id=18486569#.URtJEn8QuIA.twitter |publisher = ABC News |accessdate = February 13, 2013 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130213151848/http://abcnews.go.com/US/christopher-dorner-manhunt-charred-human-remains-found-burned/story?id=18486569#.URtJEn8QuIA.twitter |archivedate = February 13, 2013 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2014-11-24\"|2014\n|[[Lamont Stephenson]] \n|42\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2014}}}}\n|Stephenson was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on 11 October 2018. He was wanted for the murder of his fianc\u00e9e, Olga DeJesus, on 17 October 2014 in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. Stephenson was the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives, 2010s|521st fugitive to be placed]] on the [[FBI]]'s Ten Most Wanted Fugitives list. Police say that he was also wanted in a second homicide committed 6 March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lamont Stephenson|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/lamont-stephenson|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=11 October 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> He was captured in [[Maryland]] on 7 March 2019, as authorities were investigating a suspicious vehicle.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2015-11-24\"|2015\n|[[Luis Macedo]]\n|27\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2015}}}}\n|Macedo, an American&nbsp;fugitive&nbsp;wanted for questioning in connection with the 1 May 2009 murder of 15-year-old Alex Arellano in&nbsp;[[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]. He is thought to have fled the Chicago area soon after the murder, and was last seen on 24 Nov 2015.<ref name=\"staff\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-teen-killed-burned-10-most-wanted-arrest-20170827-story.html|title=10 Most Wanted suspect in teen's killing, burning is caught in Mexico: FBI|author=Chicago Tribune staff|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2016, Macedo was added to&nbsp;the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]]&nbsp;list. He was captured on 27 August 2017 in&nbsp;[[Guadalajara|Guadalajara,&nbsp;Jalisco,&nbsp;Mexico]]&nbsp;without incident.<ref name=\"staff\"/>\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Terry A. D. Strickland]]\n|24\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2016}}}}\n|Strickland, an [[Americans|American]] fugitive who was wanted for the murder of two men in July 2016. On 15 December 2016, Strickland was added to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]'s [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Top Ten Most Wanted]] list. He was apprehended without incident during a traffic stop at 5:10 a.m. [[Mountain Standard Time|MT]] and booked into the El Paso county jail. The FBI's public tip line was contacted earlier in the month suggesting that Strickland was living in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/story/news/crime/2017/01/15/fbi-most-wanted-fugitive-arrested-el-paso/96613996/|title=FBI Most Wanted fugitive arrested in El Paso|publisher=}}</ref> Strickland was arrested in El Paso, Texas on 15 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/fbi-strickland-milwaukee-homicide-top-10-most-wanted-407968315.html|title=Illinois Man on Top 10 Most Wanted List for Double Homicide|last=Ray|first=Richard|date=22 December 2016|work=|newspaper=NBC Chicago|access-date=14 January 2017|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/fbis-10-most-wanted-terry-d-strickland-has-been-called-cold-blooded-killer-here-why-he-tops-710427|title=FBI's 10 Most Wanted: Terry A D Strickland has been called a 'cold blooded' killer; here is why he tops the list|last=Bhat|first=Aditya|date=|work=|newspaper=[[International Business Times]], India Edition|language=en|access-date=2017-01-14|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/news/crime/2016/12/15/fbi-adds-suspect-milwaukee-double-homicide-most-wanted-list/95482294/|title=FBI adds suspect in Milwaukee double homicide to most wanted list|last=Luthern|first=Ashley|date=15 December 2016|work=|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|access-date=14 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Antwan Mims]]\n|unknown\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2018}}}}\n|Mims, an American criminal who was added to the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list on 27 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/new-top-ten-fugitive-antwan-tamon-mims-062718 |title=New Top Ten Fugitive. Help Us Catch a Killer |date=27 June 2018 |access-date=22 October 2018 |work=[[FBI]] |publisher=[[U.S. Department of Justice]]}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Michigan man on the FBI's Top 10 most wanted list|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7MGekzOC3XA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Mims was wanted for 25 March 2018 murders of Cortez Lamont Miller and Michael Canthrell Johnson<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/detroit/news/press-releases/antwan-mims-wanted-for-double-homicide-in-benton-harbor-added-to-fbis-ten-most-wanted-fugitives-list|title=Antwan Mims, Wanted for Double Homicide in Benton Harbor, Added to FBI\u2019s Ten Most Wanted Fugitives List \u2013 FBI|website=www.fbi.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> while they were attending a house party in [[Benton Harbor, Michigan]]. He was captured on 31 July 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/detroit/news/press-releases/ten-most-wanted-fugitive-antwan-mims-captured|title=Ten Most Wanted Fugitive Antwan Mims Captured \u2013 FBI|website=www.fbi.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> and was sentenced to life in prison in March 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/detroit/news/press-releases/ten-most-wanted-fugitive-antwan-mims-captured |title=Ten Most Wanted Fugitive Antwan Mims Capturedv |first=Tim |last=Wiley |date=1 August 2018 |access-date=22 October 2018 |work=[[FBI]] |publisher= [[U.S. Department of Justice]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|[[R\u00e9doine Fa\u00efd]]\n|46\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|France|2018}}}}\n|Faid, a [[French people|French]] [[gangster]] and serial [[Prison escape|jailbreaker]] known for his multiple prison escapes, and was named France's most wanted criminal since 2013.<ref name=australian>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/frances-most-wanted-gangster-redoine-faid-uses-explosives-to-blast-out-of-jail/story-e6frg6so-1226620023099|title=France's most wanted, gangster Redoine Faid, uses explosives to blast out of jail|work=The Australian|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref> Fa\u00efd's most recent escape was on 1 July 2018 when he broke out of a prison in [[R\u00e9au]] with the help of three armed accomplices and a helicopter.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/gunmen-help-french-gangster-escape-prison-in-helicopter-1.3550055|title=Gunmen help French gangster escape prison in helicopter|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref> He was caught on 3 October 2018 in [[Creil]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45732226|title=French jailbreak gangster hid in burqa|date=2018-10-03|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> and was sent back to jail.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2018-02-24\"|2018\n|[[Greg Alyn Carlson]]\n|47\n|{{nowrap|{{Flag|United States|2018}}}}\n|Carlson was an American criminal formerly on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]] list from 27 September 2018 to 13 February 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/topten/greg-alyn-carlson|title=Greg Alyn Carlson|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=21 February 2019}}</ref> Carlson was an alleged sexual predator involved in multiple armed sexual assaults in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], and was wanted by the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] for assault with intent to commit rape. He was also wanted by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] on charges of [[unlawful flight to avoid prosecution]] and was shot dead by FBI agents in [[Apex, North Carolina]] on 13 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/greg-alyn-carlson-fbi-most-wanted-list-man-fugitive-shot-killed-hotel-room-north-carolina-a8779886.html|title=Man in FBI's ten most wanted list shot and killed|date=14 February 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=21 February 2019}}</ref> Authorities found him hiding at a hotel and upon entering his room a violent altercation occurred, resulting in Carlson's death.\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fugitives]]\n[[Category:Lists of unexplained disappearances]]\n[[Category:Missing people]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBefore 1900:removed extraneous period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_fugitives_from_justice_who_disappeared"}
{"title_page": "Microwave Data Systems", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Microwave Data Systems / MDS / GE MDS\n| logo                = \n| type                = Wireless communications\n| foundation          = 1985\n| location            = 175 Science Pkwy\n[[Rochester, NY]], USA\n| industry            = RF Communications\n| revenue             = Undisclosed\n| products            = Point-to-Point and Point-to-Multipoint Radios\n| homepage            = GeGridSolutions.com/Communications\n}}\n\n'''GE MDS (Formerly Microwave Data Systems''', Inc. \u201c'''MDS\u201d''') is a company that makes wireless communications equipment for the industrial market. MDS was  a subsidiary of Moseley Associates and was acquired, in January 2007, by General Electric Multilin, becoming known as '''GE MDS, LLC'''. Prior to being a subsidiary of Moseley, Microwave Data Systems was a part of California Microwave.\n\nGE MDS Products include \"point-to-point\" and \"point-to-multipoint\" radios that operate in the licensed and unlicensed bands. The company is known particularly for long range communications, interference rejection, industrial quality, and high reliability. Customer applications are typically industrial and long range: Electrical Distribution Automation, Oil and Gas Wellhead monitoring, Oil and Gas pipeline monitoring, Railroad locomotive and wayside communications, Water/Waste-water monitoring, etc. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Wireless Modem]]\n* [[Wireless]]\n* [[Public Utility]] \n* [[Radio]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{webarchive |url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20070319073959/http://www.microwavedata.com/ |title=Official website |date=2007-03-19}} - Archived Website\n*[http://www.gegridsolutions.com/Communications Current website]\n\n==Sources==\n* http://www.controleng.com/article/CA6433353.html\n\n[[Category:Technology companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{tech-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Microwave Data Systems / MDS / GE MDS\n| logo                = \n| type                = Wireless communications\n| foundation          = 1985\n| location            = 175 Science Pkwy\n[[Rochester, NY]], USA\n| industry            = RF Communications\n| revenue             = Undisclosed\n| products            = Point-to-Point and Point-to-Multipoint Radios\n| homepage            = GeGridSolutions.com/Communications\n}}\n\n'''GE MDS (Formerly Microwave Data Systems''', Inc. \u201c'''MDS\u201d''') is a company that makes wireless communications equipment for the industrial market. MDS was  a subsidiary of Moseley Associates and was acquired, in January 2007, by General Electric Multilin, becoming known as '''GE MDS, LLC'''. Prior to being a subsidiary of Moseley, Microwave Data Systems was a part of California Microwave.\n\nGE MDS Products include \"point-to-point\" and \"point-to-multipoint\" radios that operate in the licensed and unlicensed bands. The company is known particularly for long range communications, interference rejection, industrial quality, and high reliability. Customer applications are typically industrial and long range: Electrical Distribution Automation, Oil and Gas Wellhead monitoring, Oil and Gas pipeline monitoring, Railroad locomotive and wayside communications, Water/Waste-water monitoring, etc. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Wireless Modem]]\n* [[Wireless]]\n* [[Public Utility]] \n* [[Radio]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{webarchive |url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20070319073959/http://www.microwavedata.com/ |title=Official website |date=2007-03-19}}\n*[http://www.gegridsolutions.com/Communications Current website]\n\n==Sources==\n* http://www.controleng.com/article/CA6433353.html\n\n[[Category:Technology companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{tech-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JustinSmith1020", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tagged website archive as such", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microwave_Data_Systems"}
{"title_page": "Heathfield Community School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n| name          = Heathfield Community School\n| image         = Heathfield Community School.JPG\n| image_size = 240px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.036|-3.062|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   = 1978\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Mr Peter Hoare\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| address        = School Road<br />[[Monkton Heathfield]]\n| city          = [[Taunton]]\n| county        = [[Somerset]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = TA2 8PD\n| local_authority           = [[Somerset County Council]]\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 933/4354\n| urn           = 123883\n| enrolment    = 1,254 pupils (in 2018)\n| gender        = [[Coeducation|Mixed]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.heathfield.somerset.sch.uk\n}}\n\n'''Heathfield Community School''' is a [[Community school (England and Wales)|community]] [[secondary school]] located at [[West Monkton]] in the outskirts of [[Taunton]], England. It had 1,192 pupils aged 11 to 18, of which 78 were in the sixth form, in 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 inspection report|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/2456441/urn/123883.pdf|publisher=Ofsted|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> and has an [[Arts College]] specialist status.<ref>[http://www.qca.org.uk/14-19/110_1819.htm Monkton Heathfield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824081407/http://www.qca.org.uk/14-19/110_1819.htm |date=24 August 2007 }}. Qualifications and Curriculum Authority. Retrieved on 3 March 2008.</ref>  The headteacher is Peter Hoare.\n\n== History ==\nWest Monkton Secondary Modern School was built in 1956. In 1978, the school merged with Priory Boys' School to form Heathfield Community School.\nSince then, new buildings have been added, such as; the Sports Hall in 1979 and the English Centre in 1991.<ref>[http://flipflashpages.uniflip.com/3/94614/333988/pub/document.pdf]. Impact Magazine. Retrieved 22 December 2014.</ref> In 1990, the school performed a version of [[Peace Child International|Peace Child]] which gave rise to a partnership with [[Kathleen Tacchi-Morris]]. In 1999, the Tacchi-Morris Trust donated \u00a31-million along with \u00a32.1 million from the Arts Council to build the Tacchi-Morris Arts Centre. The school has an annual Christmas Carol Concert, which involves pupils from all years, staff and members of the community.\n\n== Facilities ==\nA new sand-based astro [[Pitch (sports)|pitch]] was opened in 2003 and was funded partly through local businesses. The pitch is used both by the school and the local community with a local six-a-side league held there on Monday evenings.\n\nThe [[Kathleen Tacchi Morris|Tacchi-Morris]] Arts Centre is a theatre which is open to the community but is also used by the school for teaching and performing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tacchi-morris.com/|title=Tacchi-Morris Arts Centre|publisher=Tacchi-Morris Arts Centre|accessdate=1 April 2009}}</ref>  Some year-11 pupils perform their [[GCSE]] drama pieces in the theatre each year. The arts centre is also used by the school to perform musical concerts; however the Christmas concert is performed in the sports hall due to high demand.\n\n\"The Space\" is a new 6th form facility based on the Heathfield School site offering a performing arts diploma. The first cohort of students started September 2009.\n\nIn September 2012, the school opened its new [[library]] and [[Autism|autism centre]] known as the Cedar Centre, costing \u00a3610,000. This allowed the conversion of the old library into a staff room and the old staff room into two new English classrooms. [[Somerset County Council]] considered [[Kingsmead School, Wiveliscombe|Kingsmead School]] for the development but chose Heathfield as it \"was a better option in terms of pupils travelling to the base\".\n\nIn 2018, building began for a new performing arts building and an art & science block.\n\n== Cafe Paramo ==\nCafe Paramo allows pupils at the school learn business techniques by selling premium [[coffee]] and other merchandise. The project has been running since 2009. Through Cafe Paramo, the school has links to the Caxarumi co-operative in [[Ecuador]] and the [[Geographic Regions of the Dominican Republic|Valdesian region]] of the [[Dominican Republic]]. The Caxarumi co-operative consists of 60 farmers in [[Loja, Ecuador|Loja]]. The proceeds of the project go directly to the farmers, the local communities and schools in the area. The money for the local schools funds the basics such as tables, chairs etc. In the Valdesia region it even helps a small orphanage. The project also is part of the year 8 'Multicultural Week'.\n\n== Student honorable mentions ==\nSome recent notable pupils include:\n* Pip Anderson, [[Actor]] and [[Freerunning|Freerunner]]\n* [[Charlie Clough]], [[Footballer]]\n* [[Joel Conlon]], [[Rugby Union|Rugby player]]\n* [[Adam Pengilly]], [[Skeleton (sport)|Skeleton racer]]\n* [[Will Vaughan]], [[Rugby Union|Rugby player]]\n* [[Joe Snow]], [[Rugby Union|Rugby player]]\n* Rosie May Giblett, [[Singer-songwriter]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Somerset}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in Taunton]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Somerset]]\n[[Category:Community schools in Somerset]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n| name          = Heathfield Community School\n| image         = Heathfield Community School.JPG\n| image_size = 240px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.036|-3.062|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   = 1978\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Mr Peter Hoare\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| address        = School Road<br />[[Monkton Heathfield]]\n| city          = [[Taunton]]\n| county        = [[Somerset]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = TA2 8PD\n| local_authority           = [[Somerset County Council]]\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 933/4354\n| urn           = 123883\n| enrolment    = 1,254 pupils (in 2018)\n| gender        = [[Coeducation|Mixed]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.heathfield.somerset.sch.uk\n}}\n\n'''Heathfield Community School''' is a [[Community school (England and Wales)|community]] [[secondary school]] located at [[West Monkton]] in the outskirts of [[Taunton]], England. It had 1,192 pupils aged 11 to 18, of which 78 were in the sixth form, in 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 inspection report|url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/2456441/urn/123883.pdf|publisher=Ofsted|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> and has an [[Arts College]] specialist status.<ref>[http://www.qca.org.uk/14-19/110_1819.htm Monkton Heathfield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824081407/http://www.qca.org.uk/14-19/110_1819.htm |date=24 August 2007 }}. Qualifications and Curriculum Authority. Retrieved on 3 March 2008.</ref>  The headteacher is Peter Hoare.\n\n== History ==\nWest Monkton Secondary Modern School was built in 1956. In 1978, the school merged with Priory Boys' School to form Heathfield Community School.\nSince then, new buildings have been added, such as; the Sports Hall in 1979 and the English Centre in 1991.<ref>[http://flipflashpages.uniflip.com/3/94614/333988/pub/document.pdf]. Impact Magazine. Retrieved 22 December 2014.</ref> In 1990, the school performed a version of [[Peace Child International|Peace Child]] which gave rise to a partnership with [[Kathleen Tacchi-Morris]]. In 1999, the Tacchi-Morris Trust donated \u00a31-million along with \u00a32.1 million from the Arts Council to build the Tacchi-Morris Arts Centre. The school has an annual Christmas Carol Concert, which involves pupils from all years, staff and members of the community.\n\n== Facilities ==\nA new sand-based astro [[Pitch (sports)|pitch]] was opened in 2003 and was funded partly through local businesses. The pitch is used both by the school and the local community with a local six-a-side league held there on Monday evenings.\n\nThe [[Kathleen Tacchi Morris|Tacchi-Morris]] Arts Centre is a theatre which is open to the community but is also used by the school for teaching and performing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tacchi-morris.com/|title=Tacchi-Morris Arts Centre|publisher=Tacchi-Morris Arts Centre|accessdate=1 April 2009}}</ref>  Some year-11 pupils perform their [[GCSE]] drama pieces in the theatre each year. The arts centre is also used by the school to perform musical concerts; however the Christmas concert is performed in the sports hall due to high demand.\n\n\"The Space\" is a new 6th form facility based on the Heathfield School site offering a performing arts diploma. The first cohort of students started September 2009.\n\nIn September 2012, the school opened its new [[library]] and [[Autism|autism centre]] known as the Cedar Centre, costing \u00a3610,000. This allowed the conversion of the old library into a staff room and the old staff room into two new English classrooms. [[Somerset County Council]] considered [[Kingsmead School, Wiveliscombe|Kingsmead School]] for the development but chose Heathfield as it \"was a better option in terms of pupils travelling to the base\".\n\nIn 2018, building began for a new performing arts building and an art & science block.\n\n== Cafe Paramo ==\nCafe Paramo allows pupils at the school learn business techniques by selling premium [[coffee]] and other merchandise. The project has been running since 2009. Through Cafe Paramo, the school has links to the Caxarumi co-operative in [[Ecuador]] and the [[Geographic Regions of the Dominican Republic|Valdesian region]] of the [[Dominican Republic]]. The Caxarumi co-operative consists of 60 farmers in [[Loja, Ecuador|Loja]]. The proceeds of the project go directly to the farmers, the local communities and schools in the area. The money for the local schools funds the basics such as tables, chairs etc. In the Valdesia region it even helps a small orphanage. The project also is part of the year 8 'Multicultural Week'.\n\n== Student honorable mentions ==\nSome recent notable pupils include:\n* Pip Anderson, [[Actor]] and [[Freerunning|Freerunner]]\n* [[Charlie Clough]], [[Footballer]]\n* [[Joel Conlon]], [[Rugby Union|Rugby player]]\n* [[Adam Pengilly]], [[Skeleton (sport)|Skeleton racer]]\n* [[Will Vaughan]], [[Rugby Union|Rugby player]]\n* [[Joe Snow]], [[Rugby Union|Rugby player]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Somerset}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in Taunton]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Somerset]]\n[[Category:Community schools in Somerset]]\n", "name_user": "Barrettjonathan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStudent honorable mentions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heathfield_Community_School"}
