ity_rural_sq_mi = \n| population_metro_footnotes     = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_metro               = \n| population_density_metro_km2   = \n| population_density_metro_sq_mi = \n| population_density             = \n| population_density_rank        = \n| population_blank1_title        = Total\n| population_blank1              = 39441\n| population_density_blank1_km2  = \n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi= \n| population_blank2_title        = \n| population_blank2              = \n| population_density_blank2_km2  = \n| population_density_blank2_sq_mi= \n| population_demonym      = <!-- demonym, e.g. Liverpudlian for someone from Liverpool -->\n| population_note         = \n<!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1      = \n| demographics1_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| demographics1_title1    = \n| demographics1_info1     = <!-- etc., up to demographics1_title5 / demographics1_info5 -->\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->\n| demographics_type2      = \n| demographics2_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| demographics2_title1    = \n| demographics2_info1     = <!-- etc., up to demographics2_title5 / demographics2_info5 -->\n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[East Africa Time|EAT]]\n| utc_offset1             = +03:00\n| timezone1_DST           = <!-- CEST, EDT, etc. If timezone does not use DST, leave blank-->\n| utc_offset1_DST         = <!-- \u00b10:00. If timezone does not use DST, leave blank-->\n| timezone2               = \n| utc_offset2             = \n| timezone2_DST           = \n| utc_offset2_DST         = \n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- enter ZIP Code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n| postal_code             = \n| postal2_code_type       = <!-- enter ZIP Code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n| postal2_code            = \n| area_code_type          = <!-- defaults to: Area code(s) -->\n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n| registration_plate_type = \n| registration_plate      = \n<!-- blank fields (section 1) -->\n| blank_name_sec1         = \n| blank_info_sec1         = \n| blank1_name_sec1        = \n| blank1_info_sec1        = \n| blank2_name_sec1        = \n| blank2_info_sec1        = <!-- etc., up to blank7_name_sec1 / blank7_info_sec1 -->\n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n| blank_name_sec2         = \n| blank_info_sec2         = \n| blank1_name_sec2        = \n| blank1_info_sec2        = \n| blank2_name_sec2        = \n| blank2_info_sec2        = <!-- etc., up to blank7_name_sec2 / blank7_info_sec2 -->\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Kerugoya ''' is the biggest town in [[Kirinyaga County]]. Kerugoya is located 10 kilometres east of [[Karatina]] and 40 kilometres west of [[Embu, Kenya|Embu]].\nIt is situated in the former District of Kirinyaga. Travel directions by road from Nairobi, is through Thika road past Thika, Kenol and Makuyu (along the Thika Road). The road leads through Makutano until Sagana town, where a road branches off the East towards Kagio town up to Kirinyaga University branching North towards the town. \n\nYou can also drive through the Plains of Mwea branching east at Makutano, famous for the largest rice irrigation scheme in Eastern Africa, passing numerous communes inhabited by the Kikuyu, majority of whom practise Subsistence farming.\n\nKerugoya town mostly serves as an urban area to the inhabitants of Kangaita, Kimunye, Kagumo and Karia.\n\n==Name==\nThe word is Kerugoya comes from Kikuyu words 'Kiri-guoya' which means 'The fearful (Bush)'. The place was formerly covered with thick bushes and when the whites arrived in the villages, they named the so-called 'Kithaka kiri guoya' (Gichugu Dialect). Hence the modern name Kerugoya.\n\n==Administration==\nKerugoya forms a local authority together with another township, [[Kutus]]. It is known as ''Kerugoya/Kutus municipality''. The municipality has a population of 39,441, of whom 14,056 are classified urban (1999 census <ref>Kenya National Bureau of Statistics: [http://www.forestry.go.ke/cbs.go.ke/pdf/authority.pdf ''Population of local authorities''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928215608/http://www.forestry.go.ke/cbs.go.ke/pdf/authority.pdf |date=2007-09-28 }}</ref>).\n\nThe municipality has six wards: Kerugoya Central, Kerugoya North, Kerugoya South, Kutus South, Kutus Central and Nduini. Most of these wards belong to [[Kerugoya/Kutus Constituency]].<ref>Electoral Commission of Kenya: [http://www.eck.or.ke/downloads/pollingcentres.pdf ''Registration centres by electoral area and constituency''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070628084749/http://www.eck.or.ke/downloads/pollingcentres.pdf |date=2007-06-28 }}</ref> Kerugoya was also headquarters of the former ''Central division'' of Kirinyaga District.\n\n==Education==\nA famous deaf school [[Kerugoya School for the Deaf]] is based in Kerugoya Town. Others are, Kirinyaga Township Primary School, Kerugoya Boys High School, Kerugoya Girls High School, Facing MT. Kenya High. others are Kerugoya Good shepherd academy kerugoya St. Joseph Academy and many more.\n\nIn 2011, [[Kenya Certificate of Primary Education]] Kirinyaga county mean mark was number 1 out of 47in the whole country.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe Kirinyaga University, formally known as ''Kirinyaga Technical Institute'' as well as ''Kirinyaga University College'', is situated in Kerugoya. It received the charter to operate as independent university in October 2016 by Kenyan president [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] among 8 other universities.<ref name=standard>{{cite web|url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000218850/nyaga-kosgei-now-chancellors-as-universities-expansion-frozen|author=Nzau Musau|title=Nyaga, Kosgei now chancellors as universities expansion frozen |publisher=[[The Standard (Kenya)|The Standard]]|website=standardmedia.co.ke|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=jomo>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkuat.ac.ke/jkuat-to-mentor-kirinyaga-university-college/|title=JKUAT to Mentor Kirinyaga University College |publisher=[[Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology]]|website=jkuat.ac.ke|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nKerugoya is the biggest town in Kirinyaga county in terms of area, population, business capacity and amenities. It is associated as economic hub of the region given the big arable farms held by local farmers: Tea, coffee, macadamia and others food stuff are among the crops grown in the upper area, as the region is most suitable for farming.\n\nTo support agricultural and dairy farming there are several agro-vet business and officers from the Ministry of Agriculture\n\nThere are various banks (among them [[Equity Bank Kenya Limited|Equity bank]], [[Commercial Bank of Africa|CBA]], [[Cooperative Bank of Kenya|Cooperative Bank]], [[Family Bank]], [[Barclays Bank (Kenya)|Barclays Bank]], [[Sidian Bank]], Bigwa Sacco, Kirinyaga Farmers Sacco, Muhigia Sacco and FEP Bank)This shows good performance economically.\n\nMilk production in Kirinyaga county is on the rise with many farmers favoring dairy farming for its handsome rewards. Kirima Slopes Co-operative Society buys milk from farmers and then sells it to Brookside Dairy. In the year 2014, the cooperative society which is a community-based initiative received Ksh.89million as payment for milk sold to Brookside company.<ref>http://allafrica.com/stories/201406160800.html</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nWhen traveling from Nairobi, the capital city, Kerugoya town is easily accessible by use of public service vehicle ([[Matatu]]). it costs an average of 250 to 300 KES<ref>Registration centres by electoral area and constituency</ref> and it typically takes about 2 hrs of travel at a legal speed limit of 80&nbsp;km/h. Mostly these vehicles are located in [[Nyamakima (Nairobi)|Tea Room]] and [[Tearoom (Nairobi)|Nyamakima]] bus stages. The widely used Saccos are as follows: KUKENA, Supreme Shuttle, 2NK or Private vehicle etc.\n\nKerugoya has multiple gas stations such as Total, Kobil, and National Oil.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{First and second-level administrative divisions of Kenya}}\n\n[[Category:Kirinyaga County]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Central Province (Kenya)]]\n[[Category:County capitals in Kenya]]\n", "name_user": "Kosi grace", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammatical errors on the text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerugoya"}
{"title_page": "Nancy Donahue", "text_new": "{{short description|American fashion model and actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox model\n| name = Nancy Donahue\n| image = PhotoNancyDonahue.jpg\n| caption = Nancy Donahue, 2009\n| birth_name     = Nancy Castle Donahue\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|2|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], United States<ref>Fashion; Model of success; From magazine spreads in the '80s to dessert spreads in the '90s, Lowell's Nancy Donahue takes the cake, ''Boston Herald''; Oct 20, 1999 (bostonherald.com)</ref>\n| height        = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue height]</ref>\n| haircolor     = blonde<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue hair color]</ref>\n| eyecolor      = green<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue eye color]</ref>\n| measurements  = 34B-25-34\n| weight        = {{convert|125|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| dress size    = \n| shoesize      = 7.5 (US) 38 (EU)<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue shoe size]</ref>\n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1978-present\n| website      = http://www.nancydonahue.com/\n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''Nancy Donahue''' (born February 16, 1958) is an American [[Model (person)|fashion model]] and actress.\n\n== Career ==\nDonahue worked alongside some of the top international models of the 1980s, including [[Kim Alexis]], [[Carol Alt]], [[Gia Carangi]], [[Janice Dickinson]] and [[Paulina Porizkova]]. Donahue's face was on the cover and the inside fashion editorial of countless fashion magazines including [[Vogue (magazine)|American ''Vogue'']], [[Vogue Paris|French ''Vogue'']], ''[[Vogue Italia]]'', [[Vogue (British magazine)|British ''Vogue'']], ''[[Italian Bazaar]]'', ''Mademoiselle'', ''[[Self (magazine)|Self]]'', ''[[Redbook]]'', ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' and the ''[[New York Times]]'' and, more recently, ''[[More!]]'' magazine. Donahue was the face for [[Helena Rubenstein]]'s beauty campaign in the UK and [[Virginia Slims]] in the USA.\n\nDonahue often did the Paris collections for American Vogue along with Gia Carangi, [[Joan Severance]] and [[Kelly Le Brock]]. She also did some runway work in her early career for [[Calvin Klein]], [[Ralph Lauren]], [[Donna Karan]] and [[Perry Ellis]] in New York and [[Hong Kong]]. Donahue also did countless catalogs for [[Lord and Taylor]], [[Neiman Marcus]] and [[Bloomingdale's]]. She has worked with numerous photographers including [[Francesco Scavullo]], [[Irving Penn]], [[Steve Landis]], [[Arthur Elgort]], [[Denis Piel]] and [[Patrick Demarchelier]].\n\nNancy co-authored ONE on ONE with her former husband, the fashion model, [[Jeff Aquilon]], published by [[Simon & Schuster]], a best-selling book about two people giving to each other physically and emotionally.\n\nDonahue was the Pastry Chef at Bianco's Catering Company in [[Chelmsford, Massachusetts]] for the ten years where she won numerous awards for her pastry at different events.\n\n== Model mismanagement ==\n\nDonahue hit the headlines for all the wrong reasons in 1995 when the head of Elite Model Management, John Casablancas, blamed her for recommending David Weil to her as an experienced money manager. Casablancas claimed that the recommendation from Donahue was so good that he never investigated Weil further, nor did he search into the background of his business partner, Peter Bucchieri. The two operated a firm, Star Capital, within Elite's offices and managed many of the model's financial portfolios. They were subsequently accused of mismanaging the funds. On September 21, 1997, Bucchieri, pleaded guilty to conspiring with Weil to sell fictitious Colorado real estate investments to the models. Bucchieri was sentenced to 33 months in prison.  It was subsequently discovered that they had transferred many of the model's funds to their own bank accounts and used it to pay personal bills and make purchases, including a new Porsche. Donahue accepted no blame for the incident and claims that she also lost a considerable amount of money to Bucchieri and Weil.<ref>Vegas Swindler gets 33 months, ''Rocky Mountain News'', 21 September 1997</ref><ref>Model Mismanagement, ''New York'' Magazine, Jul 17, 1995</ref><ref>Two Men Accused of Bilking Models, ''New York Times'', December 19, 1995</ref>\n\n== Acting ==\n* ''Exposed'', with Natashia Kinski, 1983<ref>{{IMDb title|0085513|Exposed}}</ref>\n* ''Portfolio'', with Kelly Emberg, Julie Wolfe and Paulina Porizkova, 1983<ref>{{IMDb title|0086130|Portfolio}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Self-Destruction of Gia]]'', with Francesco Scavullo, Diane von F\u00fcrstenberg, and Janice Dickinson, 2002\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nDonahue resides in her hometown of Lowell, Massachusetts, with her third husband, local businessman, Steven Joncas.  She has a son, George Eng, from her second marriage.  He is a graduate of College of Charleston class of 2011. He currently resides in Washington, DC.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=xOQCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=%22Nancy+Donahue%22 ''New York'' magazine], Jul 17, 1995 - v. 28, no. 28\n* ''[[No Lifeguard on Duty: The Accidental Life of the World\u2019s First Supermodel]]''\n* {{Cite journal\n| first       = Dinah\n| last        = Prince\n| title       = Girl Crazy\n| url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=VeUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=%22Nancy+Donahue%22\n| work   = New York Magazine\n| location    = v. 21, no. 4\n| date        = 25 January 1988\n}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZOgCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=%22Nancy+Donahue%22 ''New York'' magazine], July 3, 1989 - v. 22, no. 27\n* ''One on One'', by Jeff Aquilon and Nancy Donahue, Simon & Schuster, 1984\n* \"Model Agent Prides himself on discovering \u2018raw talent\u2019\", ''Boca Raton News'' - July 5, 1983\n* \"Notes Gathered on the Campaign Trail\", ''Boston Globe'', Jan 27, 1980\n* \"Fashion; Model of success; From magazine spreads in the '80s to dessert spreads in the '90s, Lowell's Nancy Donahue takes the cake\", ''Boston Herald''; Oct 20, 1999\n* ''Becoming a Professional Model'', by Larry Goldman, Beech Tree Books (New York), 1986\n* ''Vogue USA'' 1980 Jan: \"Nancy Donahue\" by John Stember\n* \"Twenty Years as a Self Girl\", ''Self'' magazine, May 1999, page 218\n* \"Modeling mogul: It's big business seeking out the Elite\", ''The Ledger'', June 29, 1983\n* \"The Body Game\", ''People'' magazine, Jan 11, 1993, v. 39, no. 1\n* \"Spoiled Supermodels\", ''New York'' magazine - Mar 16, 1981 - v. 14, no. 11\n* \"Girl Crazy\", ''New York'' magazine, Jan 25, 1988 - v. 21, no. 4\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.nancydonahue.com/ Nancy Donahue's official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donahue, Nancy}}\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actors from Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American fashion model and actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox model\n| name = Nancy Donahue\n| image = PhotoNancyDonahue.jpg\n| caption = Nancy Donahue, 2009\n| birth_name     = Nancy Castle Donahue\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|2|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], United States<ref>Fashion; Model of success; From magazine spreads in the '80s to dessert spreads in the '90s, Lowell's Nancy Donahue takes the cake, ''Boston Herald''; Oct 20, 1999 (bostonherald.com)</ref>\n| height        = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue height]</ref>\n| haircolor     = blonde<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue hair color]</ref>\n| eyecolor      = green<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue eye color]</ref>\n| measurements  = 34B-25-34\n| weight        = {{convert|125|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| dress size    = \n| shoesize      = 7.5 (US) 38 (EU)<ref>[http://www.modelscomposites.com/fullsize.php?count=2 Nancy Donahue shoe size]</ref>\n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1978-present\n| website      = http://www.nancydonahue.com/\n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''Nancy Donahue''' (born February 16, 1958) is an American [[Model (person)|fashion model]] and actress.\n\n== Career ==\nDonahue worked alongside some of the top international models of the 1980s, including [[Kim Alexis]], [[Carol Alt]], [[Gia Carangi]], [[Janice Dickinson]] and [[Paulina Porizkova]]. Donahue's face was on the cover and the inside fashion editorial of countless fashion magazines including [[Vogue (magazine)|American ''Vogue'']], [[Vogue Paris|French ''Vogue'']], ''[[Vogue Italia]]'', [[Vogue (British magazine)|British ''Vogue'']], ''[[Italian Bazaar]]'', ''Mademoiselle'', ''[[Self (magazine)|Self]]'', ''[[Redbook]]'', ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' and the ''[[New York Times]]'' and, more recently, ''[[More!]]'' magazine. Donahue was the face for [[Helena Rubenstein]]'s beauty campaign in the UK and [[Virginia Slims]] in the USA.\n\nDonahue often did the Paris collections for American Vogue along with Gia Carangi, [[Joan Severance]] and [[Kelly Le Brock]]. She also did some runway work in her early career for [[Calvin Klein]], [[Ralph Lauren]], [[Donna Karan]] and [[Perry Ellis]] in New York and [[Hong Kong]]. Donahue also did countless catalogs for [[Lord and Taylor]], [[Neiman Marcus]] and [[Bloomingdale's]]. She has worked with numerous photographers including [[Francesco Scavullo]], [[Irving Penn]], [[Steve Landis]], [[Arthur Elgort]], [[Denis Piel]] and [[Patrick Demarchelier]].\n\nNancy co-authored ONE on ONE with her former husband, the fashion model, [[Jeff Aquilon]], published by [[Simon & Schuster]], a best-selling book about two people giving to each other physically and emotionally.\n\nDonahue was the Pastry Chef at Bianco's Catering Company in [[Chelmsford, Massachusetts]] for the ten years where she won numerous awards for her pastry at different events.\n\n== Model mismanagement ==\n\nDonahue hit the headlines for all the wrong reasons in 1995 when the head of Elite Model Management, John Casablancas, blamed her for recommending David Weil to her as an experienced money manager. Casablancas claimed that the recommendation from Donahue was so good that he never investigated Weil further, nor did he search into the background of his business partner, Peter Bucchieri. The two operated a firm, Star Capital, within Elite's offices and managed many of the model's financial portfolios. They were subsequently accused of mismanaging the funds. On September 21, 1997, Bucchieri, pleaded guilty to conspiring with Weil to sell fictitious Colorado real estate investments to the models. Bucchieri was sentenced to 33 months in prison.  It was subsequently discovered that they had transferred many of the model's funds to their own bank accounts and used it to pay personal bills and make purchases, including a new Porsche. Donahue accepted no blame for the incident and claims that she also lost a considerable amount of money to Bucchieri and Weil.<ref>Vegas Swindler gets 33 months, ''Rocky Mountain News'', 21 September 1997</ref><ref>Model Mismanagement, ''New York'' Magazine, Jul 17, 1995</ref><ref>Two Men Accused of Bilking Models, ''New York Times'', December 19, 1995</ref>\n\n== Acting ==\n* ''Exposed'', with Natashia Kinski, 1983<ref>{{IMDb title|0085513|Exposed}}</ref>\n* ''Portfolio'', with Kelly Emberg, Julie Wolfe and Paulina Porizkova, 1983<ref>{{IMDb title|0086130|Portfolio}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Self-Destruction of Gia]]'', with Francesco Scavullo, Diane von F\u00fcrstenberg, and Janice Dickinson, 2002\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nDonahue resides in her hometown of Lowell, Massachusetts, with her third husband, local businessman, Steven Joncas.  She has a son, George Eng, from her second marriage.  He is a graduate of College of Charleston class of 2011. He currently resides in Washington, DC.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=xOQCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=%22Nancy+Donahue%22 ''New York'' magazine], Jul 17, 1995 - v. 28, no. 28\n* ''[[No Lifeguard on Duty: The Accidental Life of the World\u2019s First Supermodel]]''\n* {{Cite journal\n| first       = Dinah\n| last        = Prince\n| title       = Girl Crazy\n| url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=VeUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=%22Nancy+Donahue%22\n| work   = New York Magazine\n| location    = v. 21, no. 4\n| date        = 25 January 1988\n}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZOgCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=%22Nancy+Donahue%22 ''New York'' magazine], July 3, 1989 - v. 22, no. 27\n* ''One on One'', by Jeff Aquilon and Nancy Donahue, Simon & Schuster, 1984\n* \"Model Agent Prides himself on discovering \u2018raw talent\u2019\", ''Boca Raton News'' - July 5, 1983\n* \"Notes Gathered on the Campaign Trail\", ''Boston Globe'', Jan 27, 1980\n* \"Fashion; Model of success; From magazine spreads in the '80s to dessert spreads in the '90s, Lowell's Nancy Donahue takes the cake\", ''Boston Herald''; Oct 20, 1999\n* ''Becoming a Professional Model'', by Larry Goldman, Beech Tree Books (New York), 1986\n* ''Vogue USA'' 1980 Jan: \"Nancy Donahue\" by John Stember\n* \"Twenty Years as a Self Girl\", ''Self'' magazine, May 1999, page 218\n* \"Modeling mogul: It's big business seeking out the Elite\", ''The Ledger'', June 29, 1983\n* \"The Body Game\", ''People'' magazine, Jan 11, 1993, v. 39, no. 1\n* \"Spoiled Supermodels\", ''New York'' magazine - Mar 16, 1981 - v. 14, no. 11\n* \"Girl Crazy\", ''New York'' magazine, Jan 25, 1988 - v. 21, no. 4\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.nancydonahue.com/ Nancy Donahue's official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donahue, Nancy}}\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actors from Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nancy_Donahue"}
{"title_page": "Katherine Neville (author)", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Katherine Neville\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Missouri]], United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Author\n| nationality = American\n| period = 1988\u2013present\n| genre = [[Quest]] / [[Adventure fiction]]\n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = [[The Eight (novel)|The Eight]], [[The Fire (novel)|The Fire]], The Magic Circle, [[A Calculated Risk (novel)|A Calculated Risk]] \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.katherineneville.com/}}\n| spouse = [[Karl H. Pribram]]\n| image_upright = \n}}\n \n'''Katherine Neville''' is a ''NY Times'', ''USA Today'' & #1 Internationally bestselling author American author who writes [[Adventure fiction|adventure]]/[[quest]] novels. Her novels include ''[[The Eight (novel)|The Eight]]'' (1988), ''[[A Calculated Risk (novel)|A Calculated Risk]]'' (1992), ''The Magic Circle'' (1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070428230428/http://www.randomhouse.com/features/magiccircle/conversation.html|title=A Conversation with Katherine Neville|date=2007-04-28|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and ''[[The Fire (novel)|The Fire]]'' (2008), which is a sequel to ''The Eight''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.katherineneville.com/home/about-katherine/short-bio/|title=Biography|website=Katherine Neville {{!}} NY Times and #1 Internationally Bestselling Author|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nKatherine Neville was born in the midwest and attended university in Colorado, later doing postgraduate studies in African literature. She then moved to New York City and began a career in the computer field working for IBM in transportation and energy.<ref name=\"bio\">[http://www.katherineneville.com/the-author/biography/ Katherine Neville Official Site - Biography], Accessed August 31, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s Neville was an international data processing consultant to the Algerian government, and in the late 1970s she went to work at the Department of Energy's nuclear research site in Idaho. In between jobs and during school, she supported herself as a painter and a model. This experience led her to develop her own photography skills and eventually start a photography business in Colorado, which she ran for several years.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn 1980, she moved to San Francisco and became a vice president at Bank of America.<ref name=\"bio\" /> After publication of her first book (''[[The Eight (novel)|The Eight]]''), she moved to Europe, living in Vienna, Austria, and northern Germany. She was married to the late neuroscientist [[Karl H. Pribram]]. In the 1990s Neville and Pribram moved to Virginia and Washington, DC.<ref name=\"bio\" /> She was featured in the Washington Post for reviving Teruo Hara's storied house.<ref>Macdonald, Christine, Novelist Katherine Neville revives Teruo Hara\u2019s storied Japanese-style house: https://www.washingtonpost.com/realestate/novelist-katherine-neville-revives-teruo-haras-storied-japanese-style-house/2014/01/02/91309fde-458b-11e3-a196-3544a03c2351_story.html</ref>\n\n== Board Memberships & Awards / Grants Sponsored ==\n\n* Katherine Neville was the first author invited to serve on the Advisory Board of the Smithsonian Libraries in Washington, DC, where she is emerita, having served a full three terms. Smithsonian sponsorships:\n** Neville co-sponsored, with Dr. Karl Pribram, the Smithsonian Libraries\u2019 Neville-Pribram Mid-Career Educators Award, the first grant in the U.S. created for mid-career teachers in middle school, high school and college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.si.edu/about/internships-and-fellowships/travel-awards/neville-pribram-educators-awards|title=Neville-Pribram Mid-Career Educators Awards|date=2014|website=library.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n** Neville created the Smithsonian Libraries\u2019 ''50th Anniversary: Famous Author Tributes'' - a series of brief films of personal tributes by award-winning journalists, historians, novelists, and poets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.si.edu/50th-anniversary/author-series/r-l-stine|title=Author Series: R. L. Stine|date=2019|website=library.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n* Katherine Neville also created and sponsored ''Art In Literature: The Mary Lynn Kotz Award'', given jointly by two prestigious institutions: the Library of Virginia and the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts. The award, for excellence in writing about the visual arts, is the first of its kind, given in multiple categories, including history, biography, fiction, poetry, journalism, young adult, and museum catalogues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/litawards/kotz.htm|title=Library of Virginia {{!}} The Mary Lynn Kotz Award|website=www.lva.virginia.gov|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n* Katherine Neville is one of the original sponsoring co-founders of the International Thriller Writers Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thrillerwriters.org/about-itw/officers-and-committees/|title=Officers and Committees \u2013 International Thriller Writers|website=thrillerwriters.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n* Neville currently serves on the Advisory Board of the Authors Guild Foundation in New York.\n\n==Works==\nNeville's novels have been compared with the works of [[Alexandre Dumas]], [[Umberto Eco]], [[Charles Dickens]], and [[Steven Spielberg]].<ref name=\"bio\" /> Her books have been translated into forty languages and are in print in over 80 countries. Neville\u2019s books have appeared on bestseller lists and received multiple awards and honors around the world.<ref name=\":0\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20131226065312/http://www.katherineneville.com/the-books/ Katherine Neville Official Site-The Books]. Archived from the [http://www.katherineneville.com/the-books/ original] on December 26, 2013. Accessed November 24, 2014</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Novel\n!Print \n!Ebook\n!Audio\n|-\n| 1988 ||''[[The Eight (novel)|The Eight]]''\n|Random House / Ballantine (Trade & Mass Market) \n|Open Road \n|Random House\n|-\n| 1992 ||''[[A Calculated Risk (novel)|A Calculated Risk]]''\n|Random House / Ballantine (Mass Market)\n|Open Road \n|Random House\n|-\n| 1998 ||''[http://www.katherineneville.com/home/the-books/magic-circle/ The Magic Circle]''\n|Random House / Ballantine (Mass Market)\n|Open Road\n|\n|-\n| 2008 ||''[[The Fire (novel)|The Fire]]''\n|Random House / Ballantine (Mass Market)\n|Open Road\n|\n|}\n\n== Acclaim ==\n''The Eight'' garnered international acclaim upon its release and continues to be ranked as a top thriller novel. ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' said, \u201cEven readers with no interest in chess will be swept up into this astonishing fantasy-adventure\u2026 Neville has great fun rewriting history and making it all ring true. With two believable heroines, nonstop suspense, espionage, murder, and a puzzle that seems the key to the whole Western mystical tradition, this spellbinder soars above the level of first-rate escapist entertainment.\u201d ''The Washington Post'' called ''The Eight'' \u201cA feminist answer to Raiders of the Lost Ark.\" The ''Boston Herald'' lauded the novel as \u201cThe female counterpart to Umberto Eco\u2019s The Name of the Rose\u2026 Impossible to put down.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.katherineneville.com/home/the-books/the-eight/|title=The Eight|website=Katherine Neville {{!}} NY Times and #1 Internationally Bestselling Author|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n''A Calculated Risk'' was selected as a [[The New York Times Book Review|''NY Times'' Notable Book]] for 1992.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/06/books/notable-books-of-the-year-1992.html|title=Notable Books of the Year 1992|last=|first=|date=|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Newgate Callendar of the [[The New York Times Book Review|''NY Times Book Review'']] said the novel \"churns up wave after wave of excitement.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Callendar|first=Newgate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/15/books/spies-thrillers.html|title=Spies & Thrillers|date=1992-11-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' stated, \"Katherine Neville\u2019s follow up to ''The Eight'', a cult classic that impressed many readers as a more intelligent and literary precursor to Dan Brown\u2019s ''The DaVinci Code.'' . . ''The Fire'' impresses as much for its literary aspects as it does for its action, puzzles and suspense . . . This is a book to be savored as it\u2019s read, and admired for the beauty of its accomplishment.\u201d\n\n''[[Booklist]]'' called ''The Magic Circle'' \"compelling\" and noted that \"fans of that emerging subgenre \u2014\u2013 the millennial thriller \u2014- will want to add this one to their reading list.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.katherineneville.com/press-page/reviews-novels/|title=Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=Katherine Neville|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Beth Dora Reisberg of ''[[January Magazine]]'' termed ''The Magic Circle'' a \"tour de force.\"<ref>Beth Dora Reisberg http://www.januarymagazine.com/fiction/mcircle.html</ref> \n\n''[[The Fire (novel)|The Fire]]'', Neville's sequel to ''[[The Eight (novel)|The Eight]],'' topped bestseller lists internationally and quickly became a ''[[The New York Times Best Seller list|NY Times Bestseller]].'' In a 2008 review in ''[[The Independent]]'' of [[London]], [[Barry Forshaw]] declared that ''The Fire'' was much better than ''[[The Da Vinci Code]]''.<ref>Forshaw, B. The Fire https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/the-fire-by-katherine-neville-1026131.html</ref>\n\nNeville\u2019s books have been bestsellers in many countries, and appeared on many bestseller lists in United States, including: ''USA Today, NY Times, Publishers Weekly, Wall Street Journal, Indie List, Seattle Times, San Francisco Chronicle, Los Angeles Times, Washington Post, St Paul Pioneer Press,'' and ''Denver Post''. \n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* 1988: Katherine Neville received the first full-page interview given to an unpublished author, in Publishers Weekly.\n* 1989: The Eight was chosen \"Critics' Choice\" by the editors of People Magazine.\n* 1992: A Calculated Risk was selected a New York Times \"Notable Book of the Year.\"\n* 1990: The Eight received the award for \"Best Historic Fiction\" from the editors of Romantic Times Magazine.\n* 1991: Katherine Neville was the invited keynote speaker at the prestigious \u00c2teneo de Madrid.\n* 1999: The Eight, in a national readers' poll by the noted Spanish journal ''El Pais'', was voted one of the top ten books of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.katherineneville.com/interviews/el-pais/|title=El Pais - The Eight|date=2020-04-20|website=Katherine Neville {{!}} NY Times and #1 Internationally Bestselling Author|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n*2000: Katherine Neville was awarded the Turkish Cultural Ministry's Medallion of Merit.\n* 2009: Neville was awarded the prestigious Silver Nautilus Award for Visionary Fiction for her novel, ''The Fire'' (sequel to ''The Eight''.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.katherineneville.com/the-fire-receives-the-nautilus-award/|title=The Fire receives The Nautilus Award|website=Katherine Neville {{!}} NY Times and #1 Internationally Bestselling Author|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n* 2010: The Eight was included by the editors of \"Thrillers: 100 Must-Reads\" (Oceanview Press) as one of the best one hundred thrillers of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oceanviewpub.com/books/thrillers-100-must-reads/|title=Thrillers: 100 Must Reads \u2013 Oceanview Publishing|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n* 2018: National Public Radio includes The Eight in \"Audience Picks: 100 Best Killer Thrillers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/06/13/128718927/audience-picks-top-100-killer-thrillers|title=Audience Picks: Top 100 'Killer Thrillers'|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n* 2019: Amazon.com includes The Eight in \"100 Mysteries & Thrillers to Read in a Lifetime.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/b?ie=UTF8&node=8994558011|title=100 Mysteries & Thrillers to Read in a Lifetime|last=|first=|date=|website=www.amazon.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.katherineneville.com/ Katherine Neville's official home page]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neville, Katherine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Katherine Neville\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Missouri]], United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Author\n| nationality = American\n| period = 1988\u2013present\n| genre = [[Quest]] / [[Adventure fiction]]\n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = [[The Eight (novel)|The Eight]], [[The Fire (novel)|The Fire]], The Magic Circle, [[A Calculated Risk (novel)|A Calculated Risk]] \n| influences = \